<HEADLINE>Row grows over single mothers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830465</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday branded Social Security Secretary Peter Lilley a
member of Mr John Major's ''Bastard Tendency'' in a row over single
mothers.
The attack came from Shadow Social Security Secretary Donald Dewar in
the aftermath of a debate sparked earlier this week by right-wing Tory
MP John Redwood, who urged teenage mothers to think seriously about
having their babies adopted.
Mr Dewar said: ''Peter Lilley, too, has made his own particular
contribution to the demonology. His speech suggesting young mothers
became pregnant to jump the housing queue was a classic example of
argument by accusation.
''Like John Redwood he is a founder member of the Prime Minister's
Bastard Tendency. Unlike John Redwood, he is in office and at the heart
of this Government's social policy.''
There were repeated reports that Mr Lilley was again targeting single
parents, he said. Income support, lone parent premium, one-parent
benefit, and maternity payments were all said to be in the firing line.
''Yet what will cutting lone parents' income mean? It will simply
close options,'' said Mr Dewar. ''It will leave parents and children
struggling in even more depressing circumstances. Increased misery is
hardly an effective incentive.''
Mr Dewar said Mr Redwood -- who this week launched a new think-tank,
Campaign 2000 -- needed publicity to survive.
</TEXT>
