<HEADLINE>Components distort economic picture</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALF YOUNG, ECONOMICS EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830466</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish economy should grow by 2.7% both this year and next,
according to an average of independent forecasts included in the latest
half-yearly edition of the Government's Scottish Economic Bulletin.
Industry Minister George Kynoch expressed pleasure at what he called
very respectable rates by historical standards. However, the 1995
forecast is inflated by a 3.5% forecast (made in March by the Fraser of
Allander Institute) which might prove over-ambitious.
The economic review contained in the Bulletin is somewhat dated. All
the data used in it stop at the beginning of June, effectively excluding
first quarter output figures, second quarter export figures, two
business opinion surveys in July, and revisions by two of the
independent forecasters, also in July.
Scottish Office economists admit that the delay in publication is
unsatisfactory and are exploring ways of giving the review a more
contemporary impact.
That said, there is a wealth of other information in the Bulletin
including, this time, an attempt to explain apparent inconsistencies in
the Government's output data from manufacturing industry and independent
figures on Scotland's export performance, produced by the Scottish
Council.
The export data suggests growth of 10% in 1992, 19% in 1993, and 22%
in 1994. But manufacturing output grew by just 0.2%, 2.7% and 5.6% in
the same three years.
Of course the two sets of data measure different things in different
ways. But the Scottish Office has now done more detailed analysis which
reveals that the computer industry, Scotland's largest single exporter,
effectively distorts the picture.
Because around 75% of the components that go into computers assembled
here are imported, and computers account for more than 30% of total
exports, it emerges that the value added by Scottish employees and
companies accounts for less than 50% of the total inputs used to create
our exports.
The Bulletin says the challenge still facing Scottish industry is to
improve the proportion of domestically produced goods and services which
go into exports.
</TEXT>
