<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mackay sees some sense in federalism</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830469</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Lord Chancellor, Lord Mackay of Clashfern, has backed the
principle of federalism, ironically during a strong defence of the
Union.
In an interview at his home in the Highlands, Lord Mackay gave his
personal views on the constitutional question and the family unit.
He said: ''I think it would be a retrograde step for Scotland and
England to separate. At this stage in our history, we have had this
quite long period of union with England and I do not myself believe that
destroying that union would do anything to help the Scottish people.
''I believe the way forward for Scotland is to build on what we have,
rather than to turn round and go back on it. If England and Scotland
were in real competition, outwith the Union, I don't think it would be
to Scotland's advantage.
''I don't say that Scotland couldn't survive but I don't think it
could survive better and that is what counts.''
However, he endorsed the principle of federalism, adding: ''Now, if it
was a federal system we were talking about, that might be all right
where you had a group of equal states which had a central parliament
that legislated for them all.
''The trouble about that system in the United Kingdom is that one
nation group is so much larger than the other three -- Northern Ireland,
Wales, and Scotland. In the central parliament, England would be bound
to dominate.''
Lord Mackay also made a strong plea for the return of marriage as the
''fashionable'' thing to do rather than the present-day trend for young
people to set up home without a long-term commitment.
He said: ''The family unit is an important one and loyalty to the
family requires commitment from parents as well as children. We should
do everything we can to strengthen it.
''I have been putting proposals forward on divorce and I haven't come
out with them without a good deal of thought and discussion -- but it is
very difficult.''
</TEXT>
