<HEADLINE>Compromise likely on Scots parliament</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830470</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Labour Party is likely to disagree with Britain's largest
unions over what size a future Scottish Parliament should be.
Unison has written to Labour backing proposals that a parliament,
which Labour pledges to set up if it wins the next election, should have
145 MPs.
That is what the Transport and General Workers Union has proposed and
there is considerable support from the Scottish Liberal Democrats.
Others in the Labour Party believe the figure should be 112 MPs. That
would help Labour gain an overall majority in the parliament but would
limit attempts to make the parliament more representative of all the
parties.
A compromise will probably be decided upon before the executive of the
Scottish Labour Party takes a decision on September 9.
The Constitutional Convention, the all-party group overseeing
proposals for a parliament, meets less than three weeks after that, to
agree a final scheme.
The 145-member scheme involves 73 constituency MPs, based on
Westminster seats but with separate seats for Orkney and Shetland, plus
a further 72 members elected from regional lists, based on European
constituencies, to top up parties so that there is a form of
proportional representation and also to equal out the genders as much as
possible.
Mr Bob Thomson, Unison's associate Scottish secretary, argued
yesterday: ''A parliament of 145 members would not be excessively large.
It would only be slightly bigger than the 142 member assembly as agreed
by the Westminster Parliament in the 1978 Scotland Act.''
However, some Labour officials argue that with Westminster having only
650 members, 145 in Scotland is excessive and could lead to the charge
of politicians simply trying to get their snouts in the trough.
Unison will put up a tough fight for 145 within the Scottish Labour
Party executive where it has four representatives, plus as least another
three elected from elsewhere who are Unison members.
It will not accept 112 but as one Unison member on the Labour
executive conceded: ''We are a trade union and a trade union is used to
negotiations.''
</TEXT>
