<HEADLINE>Two more leading Conservatives say they'll quit Commons at next General Election. Patten and Wiggin join Tory exodus</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER, POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830471</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE announcement by Mr John Patten, former Education Secretary, and
Sir Jerry Wiggin, a senior Tory and former Minister, that they are to
retire at the next General Election brings to 42 the number of
Conservative MPs who have declared their intention of standing down.
Several more are expected to do so, and another significant number are
abandoning their present constituencies to look for safer ones at the
next election -- branded by Labour as ''the chicken run''.
Some marginal Tory seats, such as Basildon, have been made virtually
unwinnable for the occupants by boundary changes. In others the
incumbents have calculated their chances of holding on and have decided
to seek pastures new.
A decision is expected soon from Tory Party chairman Dr Brian
Mawhinney, who has to choose between the greater part of his
Peterborough seat, made more marginal by boundary changes, and moving
into the new seat of North-west Cambridgeshire which includes part of
his present constituency.
A factor thought to be influencing some Tory MPs is the tighter
restrictions on MPs' ability to earn from parliamentary consultancy work
which are likely to be imposed in the next Parliament as a result of the
Nolan Committee report on standards in public life.
Current opinion polls indicate that a Tory MP with a majority under
2500 stands little chance of keeping his seat, and majorities of 5000 or
under look almost as precarious.
Some 20 Labour MPs have also said they will quit. A few others are
believed to be delaying an announcement to try to block selection of
their successor through women-only shortlists. Three Liberal Democrats
are also to stand down.
Mr Patten, MP for Oxford East and Abingdon, with a slim 3539 majority,
insisted he was going for family reasons.
He was sacked from the Cabinet a year ago after a stormy two years at
education, when he clashed with teachers and governors over reforms.
Sir Jerry Wiggin was embroiled in a sleaze row after admitting having
used the name of a colleague, Mr Sebastian Coe, to promote an amendment
to legislation in which he had a financial interest.
The Tory MPs who have announced their retirement are: Michael Alison
(Selby), Kenneth Baker (Mole Valley), John Biffen (North Shropshire),
John Butcher (Coventry South West), Sir Kenneth Carlisle (Lincoln), Paul
Channon (Southend West), Sir Julian Critchley (Aldershot), Sir Anthony
Durant (Reading West), Dudley Fishburn (Kensington), Sir Anthony Grant
(Cambridge South West), Sir John Hannam (Exeter), David Harris (St
Ives), Sir Terence Higgins (Worthing), Sir Peter Hordern (Horsham), Sir
Ralph Howell (North Norfolk), Sir John Hunt (Ravensbourne), Douglas Hurd
(Whitney), Michael Jopling (Westmoreland and Lonsdale), Dame Elaine
Kellett-Bowman (Lancaster), Dame Jill Knight (Birmingham Edgbaston), Sir
Michael Marshall (Arundel), Sir Patrick McNair Wilson (New Forest), Sir
David Mitchell (Hampshire North West), Sir Hector Monro (Dumfries), Sir
Fergus Montgomery (Altrincham and Sale), Sir Cranley Onslow (Woking),
Sir Geoffrey Pattie (Chertsey and Walton), John Patten (Oxford West and
Abingdon), Tim Renton (Mid Sussex), Wyn Roberts (Conwy), Sir Tim
Sainsbury (Hove), Sir Giles Shaw (Pudsey), Roger Sims (Chislehurst), Sir
Trevor Skeet (Bedfordshire North), Sir Keith Speed (Ashford), Sir James
Spicer (Dorset West), Patrick Thompson (Norwich North), Peter Thurnham
(Bolton North East), Neville Trotter (Tynemouth), George Walden
(Buckingham), John Ward (Poole), Sir Jerry Wiggin (Weston-super-Mare).
Retiring Labour MPs are: Jeremy Bray (Motherwell South), Jack Thompson
(Wansbeck), Don Dixon (Jarrow), Roland Boyes (Houghton &amp; Washington),
Max Madden (Bradford West), Peter Hardy (Wentworth), Harold Walker
(Doncaster Central), Terry Patchett (Barnsley East), James Callaghan
(Heywood &amp; Middleton), Stan Orme (Salford East), Ken Eastham (Manchester
Blackley), Bob Litherland (Manchester Central), Bob Parry (Liverpool
Riverside), Eddie Loyden (Liverpool Garston), Gordon Oakes (Halton),
Greville Janner (Leicester West), Andrew Faulds (Warley East), Roy
