<HEADLINE>EXCLUSIVE: McCoist plans his career after Rangers. Super Ally ready to move into the world of sports agents</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>48</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830472</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WALTER Smith shook his head in disbelief and John Greig heaved a weary
sigh. Ally McCoist, aka Super Ally, Coisty, and The Greatest Living
Ranger, never fails to surprise people.
He did precisely that last night when he indicated he could ''switch
camps'' and move into the world of sports agency.
''Given the chance, I could be the best agent in the country,'' he
said, ''and I have considered forging out on my own in that sphere. The
greater part of my life has been spent in professional football and I
know everyone of any significance in the game.
''I don't think there could be many better qualified than myself to
look after the needs of people involved in sport.''
McCoist also is intrigued by the rapid developments taking place in
the world of rugby union and feels he could play a major part in
securing the correct deals for those who are about to relinquish their
amateur status. ''A whole new world is opening up in that sport and soon
players will be moving from club to club, continent to continent.''
The striker, whose goal which won the European Championship qualifying
tie against Greece at Hampden the other night could be the most crucial
in the entire series, was addressing his public via the media and he
stressed that he will go out while still at the top of his profession.
''Palmerston Park on a regular basis is not for me,'' he said.
A press conference had been called yesterday at Ibrox, although no-one
was quite certain who sanctioned such a gathering.
The suspicion was McCoist, who is allowed more leeway than just about
any other player on the planet, felt it would be appropriate. ''He's
called a what?'' asked Smith on return from training.
''Ally McCoist has called a press conference? Here?''
The Rangers manager, who all these years had thought he was the one
who called press conferences, disappeared to have words with the man
himself and returned to say McCoist knew nothing of the meeting.
The player himself appeared, shrugging his shoulders and behaving like
one of the Hollywood stars of old who were adept at feigning
astonishment whenever they entered a room to be confronted by a battery
of photographers.
''You've all come to see me? What can I say?''
Immediately, he proceeded to say a great deal, talking about his
dramatic goal, the heartache of two years of injury, and his fear of the
day the balls stop hitting the net and the cameras focus on someone
else.
McCoist has many interests, many friends, but his appearance as a
substitute for Scotland reminded him the thing he loves doing most is
playing football.
He lives to score and his sixteenth international goal gave him great
satisfaction, although, he says, it will not be enough to ensure his
place in the Rangers side to play Anorthosis Famagusta in Cyprus next
midweek.
''With all respect, I think it is fair to say that getting into
Rangers' first team is slightly harder than getting a game for Scotland
at the minute,'' he said. ''However, while I enjoyed the goal and can't
begin to describe the feeling, because it was like the release of two
years' frustration, I am not sitting here for a minute thinking that I
have turned the corner.
''Probably I'm just hitting the bend of the corner and I have a long
way to go yet in terms of fitness and sharpness. The last two years have
been the most difficult I've ever known and after I broke a leg playing
for Scotland I then had two operations, a hernia and an ankle, and two
torn muscles.
''There were times when I was down, and when I pulled a calf muscle in
the first game of the season against Motherwell last year I though to
myself, 'when is all this going to end', but that's when people close to
you really help.''
Smith had warned the conversation might get become a touch emotional.
''He'll come in here and thank everyone for having helped him through
these last two years. In fact, he'll probably have you all in tears,''
the manager said.
The football family, which is very close knit, can also be an
extremely sarcastic one, but McCoist is appreciative of his time in the
game and said: ''My dread is the day when I can't play any more, you
now, the day when I won't be able to walk into the dressing room at
Ibrox and enjoy the banter.''
The end of the line, he believes, is a long way off yet and it is his
immediate aim to regain all of his sharpness and start scoring for
Rangers and Scotland again.
Although Craig Brown is slightly cautious about qualification, it
would seem Scotland, who play Finland at Hampden next month, will go
through and, certainly, McCoist believes the place in England has been
more or less secured.
''We would want to beat the Finns, but a draw would be all right,
too,'' he said. ''Naturally, I hope to be part of the next squad.''
When most football supporters think of McCoist they think of someone
who was born to enjoy more than one man's fair share of luck, but that
isn't quite true, either.
McCoist makes much of his luck in that he has a sixth sense which
directs him to the right place at the right time, and he pointed out:
''I hear people saying that so and so may be a better striker because he
gets three chances and takes two of them. Well, my argument is that I
get six chances and score three.
''So what do you want? A player who scores two or one who gets three?
That's my logic, anyway, and I've done not too badly on the strength of
it.''
He had just about convinced everyone when the door opened and Greig
entered.
''Can I borrow someone's pen? I want Ally to choose six numbers for my
lottery ticket.''
The McCoist smile was back in place, bright as a beacon and ready
again to tackle the world.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
