<HEADLINE>Cosmopolitan McGuire makes a first impression in Europe</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND JACOBS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>48</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830473</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MARNIE McGuire is certainly a rarity in golf. The 26-year-old New
Zealander comes from impeccable Scottish stock -- her father from
Motherwell and mother from Strathaven emigrated three decades ago -- yet
she and three Australians are the only caucasians on the Japanese LPGA
Tour, to which in three years she has settled contentedly and with
success.
Winner of the British Amateur championship in 1986, McGuire has had
victories in Japan in each of the last two seasons and with 43,056,500
yen (or more believably #28,700) is currently third on the money list.
In hot sunshine at Woburn yesterday in the first round of the Weetabix
Women's British Open the Auckland-born player made her first serious
impression in Europe.
A score of 68, five under par over the 6257-yard Duke's course -- made
hard and fast running by the recent drought and in colour, if not in
texture, bearing a decided resemblance to the sponsor's product -- gave
McGuire a share of second place with Marie-Laure de Lorenzi of France
and Australia's Shani Waugh, a stroke behind the defending champion,
Sweden's Lotta Neumann.
Three substantial putts and two of no distance provided birdies in an
outward half of 21, smudged only by three putts at the short fifth. The
rest for McGuire was a holding operation by the slightly-built player,
whose clothing affiliation reinforces the Scottish connection. Her shirt
carries the name Musselburgh, in fact that of a Japanese manufacturer.
Neumann began her five-and-a-half-hour round as if intent on holding
her title. She pitched dead at the first, also birdied the next two, and
in completing her score of 67 included in her seven gains four at long
holes which the run on the ball made agreeably vulnerable. They yielded
Laura Davies the only four birdies she had in her 74, a severe famine in
contrast to recent feasts.
Swing changes made in the 1993 took some time to work their way
through de Lorenzi's elegant method. The Frenchwoman won the first of
this season's events, her sixteenth victory, and third-place finishes in
Ireland and Scotland recently gave her the confidence to trust her
driver. Her most rewarding shot, however, was the 35-foot chip she hold
for an eagle 3 from behind the fourth green.
Waugh, who also almost exclusively relied on her driver, had two
fortunate breaks, shots at the long tenth and thirteenth holes passing
unhindered through trees. At the former, she made the fifth of her seven
birdies on quick greens to which her Australian upbringing accustomed
her more than the shortening effect of the conditions.
Elsewhere, Annika Sorenstam, the US Open champion, and Davies,
respectively on the European order of merit first and second and on the
American equivalent sixth and third, had contrasting experiences as they
began the tournament which would give the Swede her fourth success this
season and Davies her sixth.
Sorenstam put struggles on the first nine holes behind her in her 70,
but Davies took four strokes more and she may have left herself too much
to do. After winning in Ireland she began the Scottish Open with 72,
seven strokes off the lead, and could not catch up and having just won
in Wales, again to give seven strokes of a start could prove as
insurmountable.
Leading scores (British or Irish unless stated):
67 -- L Neumann (Sweden).
68 -- S Waugh (Australia), M-L de Lorenzi (France), M McGuire (New
Zealand).
69 -- K Webb (Australia), J Forbes, L Brooky (New Zealand), P Hammel
(USA).
70 -- A Rogers, A Sorenstam (Sweden), M Spencer-Devlin (USA), S
Prosser, C Pierce, A Gottmo (Sweden).
71 -- L Irvine, S Croce (Italy), J McGill (USA), E Orley
(Switzerland), N Lopez (USA), E Klein (USA).
72 -- N Fink (Austria), P Wright, K Orum (Denmark), H Kobayashi
(Japan), D Barnard, J Morley, B Burton (USA), J Geddes (USA).
Other scores included: 73 -- A Nicholas, 74 -- L Davies, G Stewart, C
Matthew. 76 -- D Reid. 77 -- K Marshall. 79 -- C Panton-Lewis.
</TEXT>
