<HEADLINE>Brown's men in sight of finish line</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER, CHIEF FOOTBALL WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>48</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830474</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE was a relaxed air about Scotland manager Craig Brown yesterday
as he surveyed the immediate footballing future of his country. You
could sense that while Brown would not make plans for the European
Championship finals -- because points are still required to make
participation certain -- he knew that the most difficult work has been
done.
Indeed, it could well be that a draw with Finland, followed by victory
over San Marino, would be enough to take us to England next summer.
Brown will not see things that way, however. He will look for two more
victories before he begins his planning although he did say yesterday:
''I now believe that we will qualify. I would be very disappointed if we
were to falter at this stage.''
Brown admits that his team are short on skill in certain areas but
knows that there are other attributes they have in abundance.
Yesterday he mentioned professionalism, fighting spirit, commitment,
and team understanding: ''The purists may want to see superior skills
but they are not readily available. What we do possess are honest,
hard-working professionals mixed with several players of proven ability.
So far the mix has worked.''
It has worked to such an extent that the Greeks, who reached the last
World Cup finals, were sent homewards the other night to think again of
the next World Cup qualifying matches, knowing that the European
Championships now seem to be outwith their reach.
And it has worked even better for Brown who, along the way, has
managed to unearth fresh talent, unused at international level until he
took over from Andy Roxburgh.
Colin Hendry, of Blackburn, has become of huge importance at the heart
of the defence as has Spurs' Colin Calderwood.
Chelsea's Craig Burley, despite a couple of rash tackles, is a
maturing talent who moves up and down the right flank tirelessly and
still finds his way into the penalty box.
Also, Celtic's Tosh McKinlay slotted in as if he was a regular member
of the squad instead of having joined up on the morning of the game.
Brown knows that because of the men who have emerged while others have
been unavailable, he now has real competition for places in the Scotland
set-up.
It is a happy position for the manager as he contemplates an invasion
next summer across the Border.
Rangers goalkeeper Andy Goram could be back in place for the match
with the Finns next month. Brown would not be drawn into any debate on
the man who called off from the game with Greece. However, he stressed:
''I will select the men who are in form. There will be three goalkeepers
named and the fittest and best will be there.''
It is clear that he has immense respect for the veteran Jim Leighton,
who made one superb stop in the second-half against Greece, but,
diplomatically, he pointed out that Goram had been equally effective for
his club in the European Cup tie against Cypriot side Anorthosis
Famagusta a week earlier.
</TEXT>
