<HEADLINE>After a season of unprecedented spending . . . Expensive reputations on the line</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEVE TONGUE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830475</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
* The Herald's man in England, STEVE TONGUE, looks at the players who
will be making the news south of the Border when the new Premiership
season kicks off.
AFTER English football's walk on the wild side in season 1994-5, how
Lancaster Gate would love a season of tranquility and a quiet run-up to
the European Championship finals next summer.
It won't happen, of course. Bad publicity is already guaranteed from
the forthcoming court case involving Bruce Grobbelaar, Hans Segers, and
John Fashanu, whatever the verdict.
The Premier League's 'bungs' inquiry team are due to deliver another
report to follow the one that did for George Graham, who is still minded
to appeal against his ban from the game.
Eric Cantona, having famously made his mark on a spectator last
January, will be a marked man himself if, and when, he finally returns
to Manchester United's colours. And, however restrained the thuggish
element among the nation's football followers may be, the feeling is
that there will be ample opportunity for them to do their worst once
thousands of fans from the Continent (and Scotland?) begin to arrive
next June.
All the more important, then, that players and managers set an example
with principled behaviour and positive play. There is certainly no
shortage of performers with expensive reputations to live up to
following a summer of unprecedented spending.
For all the anxiety generated by that spree, notably among the
players' union, the influx of foreign players, in particular, has
increased interest and anticipation.
Like last season, there are four or five teams with genuine
championship prospects, and, while it would have seemed unthinkable a
year ago that two of them, Blackburn and Arsenal, would now be under new
management, that is no reason to discount either club.
Seeing Kenny Dalglish sitting on the front bench at Wembley for
Blackburn's Charity Shield match last Sunday was a literal illustration
that he will not be taking a back seat.
The club is sensibly moving towards a Continental system of
delegation, but Ray Harford will certainly make use of all his
predecessor's knowledge and experience.
Defeat by Everton last weekend was a useful reminder, however, that
nothing comes easily to reigning champions, and with a minimum of six
Champions' League matches to distract them, the Lancashire side could
easily fall between two stools.
Manchester United, following their runners-up double last May, have
suffered a traumatic summer, losing Paul Ince, Mark Hughes, Andrei
Kanchelskis almost certainly, and very nearly Cantona, too.
Alex Ferguson has spent so much time dealing with that quartet that
promised signings have not materialised. A cup of some sort next spring
looks more likely than a third championship in four seasons.
Fitting a complex individualist into a team pattern is a problem
Liverpool face as well after paying Nottingham Forest a record #8.5m for
Stan Collymore.
There is a lot of talent at Anfield and, if Collymore does blend in
harmoniously, on and off the pitch, Roy Evans' side will be up with the
best.
The England captain, David Platt, will contribute guile and goals to
an Arsenal midfield previously lacking in both. Paul Merson has fully
regained his appetite and Dennis Bergkamp's class will tell, as long as
he quickly learns to play closer together with Ian Wright, rather than
dropping off and leaving the latter isolated.
Graham's replacement, Bruce Rioch, will stand no nonsense and Arsenal
ought to be in the top three.
So should Newcastle, who looked formidable last Saturday in winning
2-0 at Tottenham in Gary Mabbutt's testimonial match. Kevin Keegan
responded to last season's disappointments (missing out on a place in
Europe after leading the Premiership for four months) by spending #14m
on forwards Les Ferdinand and David Ginola, full back Warren Barton, and
Trinidadian goalkeeper Shaka Hislop.
Leeds, Chelsea (with Ruud Gullit as sweeper), Forest and, perhaps,
Everton should be among the chasing pack and the cup contenders.
</TEXT>
