<HEADLINE>Chance to own shares in Dons</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BROADLEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830476</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABERDEEN yesterday launched their share issue and left manager Roy
Aitken in no doubt that he must break Rangers' monopoly.
The move to go public by selling two million shares is expected to
raise around #3.5m, and most of the money will go towards buying new
players.
But Aberdeen chairman Ian Donald, whose board has underwritten the
launch for #750,000 to ensure there is no repeat of the Hearts share
flop, insisted: ''We must be winning trophies and championships.
''Everything done over the last five years here has been geared
towards providing success on the field. The share issue is a unique
opportunity for our fans to be a part of the club with full voting
rights.
''I believe it will kick-start this club into a new, exciting era.''
Aitken has been promised funds immediately to help make Aberdeen a
power once again, but he stressed: ''If the right player to improve the
squad becomes available I will bring him in, but it may be wiser to wait
and see exactly what money is available to me after the share launch is
completed.
''I look for three things in a player -- professionalism, quality and
reliability. I must be sure that any player who comes in will improve on
what is already here.''
The Pittodrie club have offered several different share packages,
ranging from #455 to #10,000 blocks with bank loan facilities available.
This will entitle supporters to a variety of discounts and facilities in
return. The share launch will close at the end of September.
</TEXT>
