<HEADLINE>Tyson is master of King</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830477</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORMER world heavyweight champion Mike Tyson has shown the world just
who is boss in his new multi-million-dollar heavyweight operation.
And if Don King had a forelock, instead of his trademark shock of grey
hair, he would probably have touched it at the MGM Grand's gathering of
fighting and media men, camped in Las Vegas for tomorrow's comeback
appearance against the Boston ''Hurricane'', Peter McNeeley.
Twice Tyson interrupted King's usual noisy and amusing rhetoric, and
the king of promoters admitted: ''I shall serve the master with my
heart, my soul, and my mind. Everything righteous and just, I will do.''
Tyson sat expressionless for almost two hours, flanked by his equally
poker-faced co-managers John Horne and Rory Holloway, as King held
court. But when King announced he would be paying him #16m plus #300,000
training expenses. Tyson protested: ''Don't tell 'em my business, man.''
When Tyson was occupying the microphone, he sharply told King not to
interrupt him.
The man who converted to Islam during his Indiana incarceration for
rape said: ''I'm ready to fight. This is my calling. This is what I do.
''I'm back. My religion is Islam. It's a way of life. It's a way of
maturity. I'm more conscious of my involvement in life.''
Then came a verbal blast at a New York fight writer. Dealing with the
journalist's question, Tyson accused him of being ''a character-killer''
and said of the media: ''These guys did a number on me for three years.
People wanted to see me crumble, but I'm not going to let it happen.''
Later, on the Larry King show on CNN, he again showed resentment at
his press treatment during the three-year period when the other
contenders slugged it out, only to bring about the tangle of the current
world heavyweight scene.
</TEXT>
