<HEADLINE>FA to arbitrate in Kanchelskis row</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830479</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Andrei Kanchelskis affair took a new turn last night with the
Football Association poised to intervene.
Manchester United had cancelled the Russian internationalist's #5m
transfer to Everton after a dispute with his previous club, Shakter
Donetsk, over a #1.14m sell-on fee.
That left the winger, United's top scorer last season, in no man's
land and Everton furious, demanding the matter be settled through
arbitration.
Last night Everton issued a brief statement through their solicitor
and director Keith Tamlin. It read: ''In accordance with the rules of
the FA, Everton has referred its differences with Manchester United to
the FA for arbitration.''
''This will now lead to an arbitration hearing. This has been
confirmed by the FA.''
FA spokesman Mike Parry agreed that this was the case, but no-one at
United was available for comment.
Having come on as substitute in Russia's 6-0 European Championship win
over Finland in Helsinki on Wednesday, Kanchelskis flew back into
England yeserday and said he would be training with Everton today.
He is still registered with United, but has said he will not play for
the club again as long as Alex Ferguson is manager.
Tottenham manager Gerry Francis, who was unsuccessful with a bid for
the winger last month, admitted he was closely monitoring the situation.
Meanwhile, Wales finally settled their managerial problems by
appointing Bobby Gould. The former Wimbledon, West Brom and Coventry
boss agreed a two-and-a-half year deal, taking him up to the end of the
1998 World Cup qualification series.
</TEXT>
