<HEADLINE>Van Basten finally decides to quit</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>PROFILE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830481</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AC MILAN'S Dutch internationalist Marco van Basten finally admitted
defeat yesterday in his battle against a chronic ankle injury that had
kept him out of action for more than two years when he was forced to
retire.
The three-times European footballer of the year told a news
conference: ''The news is brief -- I've decided to quit.''
He explained: ''I took the decision after speaking to my doctor in
Belgium two weeks ago when we realised the situation with my ankle is
exactly the same as it was a year ago.''
Van Basten began his career at Ajax Amsterdam and won the Dutch title
three times, also helping them to the Cup-winners' Cup in 1987 before
joining AC Milan.
His partnership with compatriots Ruud Gullit and Frank Rijkaard
powered the Italian club to European Cup successes in 1989 and 1990. The
trio also inspired Holland to their European championship triumph of
1988.
Van Basten has not played since the May 1993 European Cup final in
Munich when Milan lost 1-0 to Olympique Marseille.
That appearance was part of an abortive three-match comeback following
an operation on his troublesome right ankle in December 1992.
More surgery followed but the specialists were unable to repair the
damage done by more than a decade of heavy tackles from defenders
determined to halt the skilful star.
Milan have asked the Dutchman to stay on and work with them in an
off-the-field capacity but van Basten said he had not yet made up his
mind.
</TEXT>
