<HEADLINE>All Black captain kicks rebel circus into touch. Paris meeting must face professionalism issue</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS CHIEF RUGBY WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830482</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE International Board meeting in Paris next week must come to a
positive decision on professionalism otherwise its future will be in
serious doubt, Scottish Rugby Union IB representative Freddie McLeod
declared yesterday.
McLeod also pronounced the rebel World Rugby Corporation and its
attempt to hijack the game not quite dead and buried, but certainly
''limping heavily towards the exit.''
Details of the WRC plan to buy the world's top 1000 players, and then
to franchise its professional game to traditional administrators like
the Scottish Rugby Union, were revealed yesterday in The Herald.
The WRC scheme was dealt another blow yesterday as All Black captain
Sean Fitzpatrick signed a contract with the NZRFU and the expectation is
that most of his World Cup team-mates are set to follow suit. WRC have
already failed to sign the Springboks and the Australian Test squad, and
this means that the coup attempt, which to be successful had to sign up
all of the world's top players, seems virtually certain to fail.
Fitzpatrick said ''99%'' of the squad which reached the final of the
World Cup earlier this year would officially declare their allegiance to
the NZRFU today. ''We're thrilled this has been resolved. It has been
very stressful, both for the players and the administrators,'' he said.
With the likely demise of the rebel circus, the focus is now back upon
the traditional unions with a vengeance. The Scottish Rugby Union --
alone of the northern hemisphere administrations -- has already shown
its hand by declaring that it is ready to embrace professionalism with
all its ramifications, like contracted players, when the IB meets in
Paris for three days next week.
It would be a major shock if the IB did not concur, but yesterday
McLeod said: ''We don't yet know what is going to happen. A number of
people are still very frightened of the word professionalism. The
pay-for-play situation alarms a lot of people. However, I would hope
that something positive will come from the meeting. If it doesn't, then
I would think that the future of the International Board is in very
serious doubt.
''If the issue is fudged again, then the Board would have absolutely
no credibility with the players.''
McLeod added that the game's administrators had taken the WRC threat
seriously. ''Much of what was in The Herald today was not entirely new
to us and suffice to say that we did not treat the threat lightly,
because it had amazing connotations, not least of which was the
ludicrous position whereby they would franchise our game back to us.''
The WRC plan was said to be bankrolled by Australian media tycoon
Kerry Packer and was fronted by fellow countryman Ross Turnbull.
McLeod said: ''We know Mr Turnbull. He was at one time vice-president
of the Australian RFU and chairman of New South Wales. Then they parted
company. I think anybody who knew him would have been extremely wary of
becoming involved.''
Yesterday WRC said that it would now work with the rugby
establishment, without explaining how. McLeod said: ''I would be
interested to know just exactly what this means because, knowing the
history of Mr Turnbull's relationship with the Australian union, I would
be amazed if this were to happen.''
As part of the deal which keeps the Australian Test squad with the
ARFU, player-representatives will sit on union committees. McLeod said
the SRU was unlikely to follow suit but it was not outwith the bounds of
possibility that a mechanism could be put in place which would take
account of any player concerns.
''So far as players coming on to the committee is concerned, I'm not
sure if that is the correct way to go,'' he said. ''It might be better
if there was a communications group involving the players. We had a very
good meeting with some of the international players earlier this week on
the professionalism issue, and the players have indicated that they are
keen to ensure that misunderstandings do not happen.
''Maybe we have to find a proper vehicle for communicating with them.
It might not be practical for players to sit on the general committee.
They are there to play rugby at the top of the game and, in any case, we
have tried to involve recently retired players in the non-playing side
and, for one reason and another, they are often too busy elsewhere to
become involved.''
Meanwhile, Will Carling has been drafted on to the working party
negotiating a cash deal with the RFU following the withdrawal of Rob
Andrew and Brian Moore.
England captain Carling has joined Tim Rodber and Mike Catt on the
team attempting to treble the squad's income for promotional activities
from #16,000 to #50,000 amid reports that Andrew and Moore had withdrawn
because they had lost the confidence of the players.
RFU secretary Tony Hallett said: ''Moore and Andrew are unable to take
on this task any more. It is not the case that either has lost
confidence of the squad. But Carling will take up the reins and we are
trying to get the deal completed as quickly as possible.''
</TEXT>
