<HEADLINE>Lomu keeps his options open</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830483</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALL Black wing Jonah Lomu, who is being chased by Leeds rugby league
club, is still undecided whether to continue playing rugby union or to
switch to the 13-a-side code.
All Black captain Sean Fitzpatrick yesterday signed contracts with the
rugby establishment and has stated that the majority of the New Zealand
World Cup squad would do likewise by the weekend.
But Debbie Tawse, Lomu's agent, said she had been ''frustrated'' by
negotiations with the New Zealand Rugby Football Union.
She said: ''He wants to continue in rugby and if we can get a fair
deal from rugby, he'll stay, or we'll pursue other options we've got.''
The NZRFU's current offer to All Blacks is about $150,000 (#100,000)
per year, but offers from Leeds and Australian rugby league side Sydney
Bulldogs are reported to be much higher. Tawse declined to say what
offer from the NZRFU would satisfy Lomu.
In an interview with Rugby World magazine Lomu reveals that money is
not what motivates him. He says: ''I'm just like any other 20-year-old.
I want to meet lots of people and travel the world and play rugby. I'm
not bothered about the money -- that's not why I do it.
''Fame is highly overrated. I could do without it all really. It makes
me feel very uncomfortable.''
</TEXT>
