<HEADLINE>Progress is slow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDI ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830485</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SNAIL'S pace -- by ocean racing standards -- continues to prevail on
the first leg of the Teacher's Around Britain Challenge, with the 10
identical Five Nations' yachts managing to cover only 80 miles in the
past 30 hours.
The biggest lottery of all remains during the night, when the wind
always dies to nothing. The fleet, which at one point was spread over a
nine-mile stretch, was compressed to within a two-mile radius again
yesterday after a fretful night in the doldrums.
Scotland's Jon Fitzgerald, Chris Nichol, and their crew on Glendronach
had climbed four places up to second yesterday evening, while the second
Scottish boat, Lord Inverforth (Paul Jeffes and Chris Owen), remained
fifth -- but the boats placed fourth down to ninth were virtually
parallel off Start Point by Plymouth.
The organisers' latest plan is now to finish this leg at Land's End --
about 75 miles away -- leaving the fleet to motor to their original
landfall, Cardiff.
Biggest problem for all the skippers is that most of their mobile
phones -- the only sure means of secret communication between skippers
-- are not functioning. Results:
1, Dream of Erin (David Harte, Ireland) 238 miles to finish; 2,
Glendronach (Jon Fitzgerald, Scotland) 239; 3, Positively Belfast
(Dickie Gomes, Ireland) 239; 4, Spirit of Hartlepool (David Allan
Williams, England) 241; 5, Lord Inverforth (Paul Jeffes, Scotland); 6,
Celtic Dragon (Colin Lyons, Wales) 241; 7, Pride of Cardiff (Richard
Tudor, Wales) 241; 8, Coeur de Paris (Didier Nicholas, France) 241; 9,
Belle Helene (J P Saliou, France) 241; 10, Spirit of London Docklands
