<HEADLINE>Pierce has no mercy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830486</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FRANCE'S Mary Pierce humiliated Martina Hingis 6-0, 6-0 yesterday,
taking just 40 minutes to dispatch the Swiss teenager and advance to the
quarter-finals of the Canadian Open women's championships in Toronto.
Pierce, the fifth-seeded Australian Open champion, dominated from the
beginning, hammering winners from the baseline. By the second set,
Hingis looked grim and appeared like she couldn't wait to get off the
court.
In other third-round play, seventh-seeded German Anke Huber outlasted
Romianian Irina Spirlea, the No.16 seed, 1-6, 6-3, 7-5. Her reward is a
quarter-final date with joint-top seed Monica Seles today.
No.6 Gabriela Sabatini, of Argentina, looked impressive in defeating
Japan's Yone Kamio 6-1, 6-0.
BRITAIN'S Miles Maclagan reached the quarter-finals of the ATP
Challenger tennis event in The Bronx, New York, yesterday.
The No.4 seed from Scotland avenged a defeat at last week's Binghamton
Challenger to beat Australian James Sekulov 6-4, 6-2. He now takes on
fifth seed Hicham Arazi, of Morocco.
