<HEADLINE>Robertson enjoys pressure-free day</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>43</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830487</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DEAN Robertson, the 25-year-old former Walker Cup player who is in the
midst of an outstanding rookie year on the European Tour, was one behind
leader Ronan Rafferty after an opening five-under-par 66 in the Chemapol
Czech Open yesterday at Marianske Lazne.
The Gleddoch-based Scot, a former Scottish amateur champion, fired six
birdies and only one bogey. His iron shots were so accurate he had many
more birdie chances, but said: ''I'm not under any pressure here this
week. I'm not in the Ryder Cup running and I'm just looking forward to
playing well and having a good time.''
Robertson is currently No.49 in the Volvo Order of Merit with winnings
of #81,776 -- including a second place finish in the Jersey Open -- but
is #17,000 behind Swede Michael Jonzon at No.33 in the race to be top
tour school graduate. Jonzon shot 74 yesterday.
Also on 66 was Sam Torrance, the current European No.1 who is assured
of his eighth successive Ryder Cup spot, and there were six other Scots
in the sub-par zone -- Sandy Lyle and Gary Orr (both 68), Ross Drummond
(69), and Paul Lawrie, Gordon Brand Jr, and Stephen McAllister (70).
Rafferty, joint second in the Austrian Open last Sunday, is only No.43
in the Ryder Cup points table but if he carried off the first prize of
#125,000 here he would be right back in contention. He would also clinch
a place in the Irish Dunhill Cup team.
Rafferty, who had seven birdies and only one bogey on his card, played
with Torrance, who has his eyes fixed on finishing top of the order of
merit. ''I've been second once and third twice but never first,'' he
said. ''I'm in front at the moment and if I could win here that would be
fantastic for me.''
