<HEADLINE>Young on course to be best of British</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GILLIAN DORRICOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>43</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830489</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE dream ticket for Steven Young is now well within his reach after
he secured a spot in the final of the British Boys' championship at
Dunbar yesterday with a semi-final win over Stewart Whiteford of Lundin.
Having won the Scottish title three times, 36 holes with Birmingham's
Sam Walker is the only obstacle remaining in an unparalleled boys'
career before the 18-year-old heads off to America to take up a golfing
scholarship in two weeks time.
It would add the finishing touches to an amazing year for Scotland on
the British amateur scene should he become the first Scot for 11 years
to win the title.
''I was thinking about Gordon Sherry winning the Amateur Championship
and Scotland winning the internationals and how great it would be if one
of us won here,'' said the Inverallochy golfer.
No matter what Walker produces today, Young has every right to expect
an easier match than he had in yesterday's semi-final with fellow Scot
Whiteford, a 16-year-old who gained his first cap only last week.
Whiteford fought back from two down and took Young to the fourth extra
hole before an 18-foot putt for a birdie gave the favourite victory.
Had Whiteford pulled off the unthinkable, he would have been the first
Scottish boy to beat Young in a competition for five years.
Walker, aged 17, who gained his first English cap last week, put paid
to two Scottish internationalists.
Scottish Boys' Strokeplay champion Craig Lee was his first victim in
the morning, when he won 2 and 1. He then ended hopes of an all-Scottish
final when he put out West Kilbride's Graham Fox by one hole in the
afternoon. Results:
