<RECORDNO>976830490</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND claimed second place with a 7-2 victory over hosts Wales at
Northop Park yesterday in the girls' home internationals. Hopes of a
fourth successive title had been shattered by the opening 9-0 defeat
against England.
However, they recovered with victories over Ireland and yesterday's
win against the Welsh.
Scotland led 2-1 after the foursomes with Laura Moffat and Shona
McEwan beating Eleanor Pilgrim and Louise Davis on the eighteenth green.
The other morning victory was provided by Claire Hunter and Karyn
Burns, who overpowered Hannah Fitzpatrick and Ann-Louise Worthing 7 and
6.
At the top of the singles order, Moffat was never in front against
Welsh girls' champion Pilgrim until the match reached the eighteenth,
where a par 4 snatched the honours.
Elsewhere, Heather Stirling, McEwan, Hunter, and Leslie MacKay all
reeled off comfortable wins. The only Scottish loser in the singles was
Burns.
In another tight match against twice Welsh girls' champion Kate Stark,
Burns was level with only four holes to play, but then lost three on the
trot.
England defeated Ireland 6[1/2]-2[1/2] yesterday to clinch the
championship for the first time since 1991. Results:
