<HEADLINE>View of Rockies revives Els</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>43</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830491</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ERNIE Els bounced back from last week's disappointment to grab an
emphatic lead after his opening round at The International tournament
here in Denver, Colorado, yesterday.
Els took a three-stroke lead into the final round at the US PGA
championship last Sunday, only to finish tied for third behind champion
Steve Elkington and play-off loser Colin Montgomerie.
As upset as Els was at the time, the sight of the majestic Rocky
Mountains, which form a backdrop to the Castle Pines course, helped to
take the South African's mind off what happened at Riviera.
''Last Sunday is completely forgotten. With the beautiful views out
here, it didn't cross my mind,'' Els said after recording nine birdies
and one bogey.
He shot eight-under-par 64 which translated to 17 points in the
modified Stableford format which awards five points for eagle, two for
birdie, zero for par, minus one for bogey, and minus three for double
bogey or worse.
With half the field back in the clubhouse, Els led by six points from
Americans Davis Love, Craig Stadler and Tom Kite.
Els, starting his round at the tenth, made four successive birdies
from the eleventh as he struck beautifully-judged approach shots in the
thin mountain air.
He birdied the eleventh and twelfth holes from 10 feet, the thirteenth
from 15 feet and the fourteenth from eight feet, before adding another
birdie from three feet at the seventeenth.
After four more birdies on the front nine, he made his only bogey at
the par-4 ninth, where he rifled his approach shot over the green.
