<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830493</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ross Finlay goes into Africa where Toyota has a strong force
SEVERAL car manufacturing
companies began as bright ideas within firms whose principal field of
operation was something entirely different. Wolseley is a prime example,
an offshoot of a business which made sheep-shearing machinery. As a make
name, Wolseley may be lying dormant, but Toyota is anything but. It is
celebrating the 60th anniversary of the first prototype vehicle to be
built within what was at that time a factory devoted to making textile
looms.
Saloons, estates, sports cars, vans, trucks and 4x4s all bear the
Toyota name. The company also has an interest in Hino and Daihatsu. As
well as operating subsidiaries building cars and components in the UK
and elsewhere, it still runs the Toyoda Automatic Loom Works -- the
founding family's name being spelled differently from the name of the
vehicles. They still provide the chairman and president of the board of
directors.
Toyota is particularly strong in 4x4s, not just in recreational
vehicles like the RAV4, but especially in the big, robust class of
off-roaders where the Landcruiser, in many markets, is the dominant
force. When I was in Zimbabwe last year, driving from the Eastern
Highlands via the Hwange National Park to Victoria Falls, it was
noticeable that, in a country where currency controls make new cars very
difficult to come by, Landcruisers of various vintages ruled the
four-wheel drive roost.
One of the reasons for the Landcruiser's success is that the model
line was established very early. The first generation Landcruiser was
built in 1951. It has always seemed to be a tough, no-nonsense vehicle,
with a strong chassis, good ground clearance, better passenger space
than many of its rivals, and the ability to batter on over the worst
Third World roads it encounters. It also offers, in the easier
conditions here, fine towing performance when hauling a trailer,
caravan, horse box or boat.
Landcruisers usually have big, powerful engines with beefy torque.
That is particularly true in the case of the latest long-wheelbase
versions, the petrol-engined 4477cc VX automatic at #38,689 and the
corresponding manual version, which comes only with a 4164cc turbo
diesel at #39,120. Those prices show that Toyota is hoping to tap into
the luxury end of the 4x4 market, but the same diesel engine is also
fitted to the more simply specified Landcruiser GS at #29,630, while the
short-wheelbase Landcruiser II at #20,394 comes with a smaller
three-litre diesel power unit.
The 4.4-litre straight-six 24-valve petrol engine pushes out 202bhp
and reaches a peak torque figure of 266lb ft. With the standard
four-speed automatic transmission, which features traction control, high
and low ratio ranges as well as front, centre and rear differential
locks, that engine allows the bulky VX to reach 60mph in about 12.5
seconds, reach a notional top speed of 106mph, and provide fuel
consumption returns like 28mpg at 56mph, 20 at 75 and 15mpg around town.
The slow-revving turbo diesel has less ultimate power but even meatier
torque -- 280lb ft as low as 2200rpm of engine speed. It matches the
petrol version in off-the-line performance and top speed, has absolutely
stump-pulling traction and gives notably better fuel consumption figures
at 56mph and on the urban cycle.
A short introductory test drive in the latest VX and GS Landcruisers
showed that these fairly massive vehicles can inch their way easily
round a sinuous off-road course, and handle well, for their class, on
ordinary roads. Up-market details on the VX include such features as air
conditioning, leather upholstery and burr walnut fascia trim, and it is
worth bearing in mind that, if you count the ''occasional'' seating
right at the back, it will take a driver and seven passengers. However,
although some luxury items may have crept in, like the other
Landcruisers the VX will also do a real job of towing, rough-road or
up-country work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Frustration of technology's missing link</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALF YOUNG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830494</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ISEE that IBM is to set up a multi-lingual helpline call centre for
European customers at its Spango Valley plant in Greenock, creating some
200 jobs. No reflection on Big Blue, but our household's experience with
computer helplines to date has been decidedly frustrating.
Earlier this year we bought a modem and associated fax software for
the personal computer we run at home. When the package arrived we
plugged in, loaded up, and stood expectantly round the screen to witness
the results.
Part of the object of the exercise was to allow two busy people to
send and receive faxes at home. A greater part was to allow my partner,
Carol, to communicate, computer-to-computer, with a work colleague 400
miles away in the south of England. She has the same computer model and
had purchased the same, recommended (and pricey) communications package.
What happened was weeks of unresolved aggravation as the software
failed, failed, and failed again, to deliver what it promised. The modem
worked fine. The software did not. Error code after impenetrable error
code was logged up on the screen.
Just occasionally, a test fax would actually make it to a friendly
destination, like this office. Would that they had not. Each small
success simply prolonged the agony as the frustrating failed attempts
multiplied.
We engaged in extended dialogue with the dealer who had supplied the
equipment. We tried to engage in dialogue with the Californian software
company to discover what all those error codes meant. The dealer tried
to help, even to the extent of setting up a link and attempting,
unsuccessfully, to exchange fax messages. The software company's
helpline could not have cared less. They were on to newer versions. If
we wanted to talk upgrades, fine. But problems? Forget it.
On a business trip to New York, I even unburdened myself of our woes
to a Manhattan computer store sales assistant. Buy a much cheaper
alternative, he advised, naming a particular package. It doesn't have
all the bells and whistles, but it does what is says it will.
Eventually two expensive boxes of less-than-satisfactory tricks were
returned to the supplier. One of his people confided that we were far
from alone in experiencing the problems. We went out and bought a
conventional telephone fax machine. Carol's dreams of communicating
computer-to-computer and the boys' plans to graze the further reaches of
the Internet are currently on hold.
I should add that IBM played no part in this domestic drama. But, ever
since the first personal computers started appearing less than two
decades ago, the customer-support area has always seemed to me the one
where most of the PC and software suppliers could do very much better.
They can hit us with a new model every six months and a new-generation
chip every other year. But old-fashioned customer support is not their
best suit.
The early computer manuals were written by engineers for engineers.
For the broad mass of users they were impenetrable gobbledegook. Some of
the documentation in our fax/modem package suggested little progress has
since been made in communicating meaningfully with customers.
So will the proliferating call-centre helplines transform the
situation and banish the kind of frustration we endured? The call-centre
concept is itself a product of rapid advances in computer technology. In
areas as diverse as catalogue shopping, debt recovery, service inquiries
in the utilities and selling insurance or mortgages and solving Baffled
of Balfron's computer problems, it looks like the sales and customer
care tool of the future.
The technology already allows operators to identify you, by name,
before your call has been answered. They can also throw up details of
your entire business history with them on screen at the flick of a key
or two. Built-in software protocols can also impose a large measure of
uniformity on the way each and every call operator responds to a
particular kind of call.
But, of course, the same technology can be and is used to control the
productivity of call-centre staff. I listened on radio, the other day,
to a description of an American trucking company which has satellite
computer links with each and every one of its cab units.
Headquarters can log and control where each unit is at every hour and
minute of the day and night. So sophisticated is the system that the
company can monitor the engine revs and speed at which each driver
changes gear. Similarly, in call centres, call frequency, sales success
rates and myriad other performance indicators for each individual
operator are logged and assessed. Management can even tell how long, in
minutes and seconds, your comfort breaks take.
Does that lead to a satisfying working environment for the staff
involved? I talked recently to someone intimately involved in
call-centre technology. He was blunt about the impact on staff. Staff
turnover in call centres, he told me, is unusually high. ''I would
not,'' he added candidly, ''want to manage a large call centre with 200
operators. I can think of a lot more pleasant places to work.''
That is, of course, only one man's view, albeit an informed source.
Glasgow has attracted a number of such centres in the past few years and
the Glasgow Development Agency is keen to promote the city as a place at
the leading edge of call-centre development.
Are they the silicon equivalent of the Victorian dark satanic mills or
a striking example of how computer technology can transform the art of
selling and keeping the customer happy? I don't know. But isn't it
interesting that our main economic development body is out touting for
more of them without any debate at all about that rather intriguing
question?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000030</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000030</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JACK MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830495</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DOUBTLESS the weans and the young people have been enjoying the first
genuine heatwave for 20 years in this country. Who am I to be such a
curmudgeon as to suggest that we would all be better off with a nice wee
wintry summer?
How well I remember the days when summer was Pacamacs over the khaki
shorts. Actually springs and summers were rather good in my childhood
and boys and girls ran about for months in frocks and shorts and ankle
socks and sandshoes and it was quite sunny and very nice really. I think
1976 had a bumper year of summer heat when the grass went the colour of
Italian coffee and the Government told us all to bathe in two
millimetres of Loch Katrine water.
But this summer has been dreadful. Forget about the tanned bodies of
children and the sort of thick young female office workers who prefer to
have themselves practically blinded by nightly sun-bathing sessions,
like something out of the ''Four Feathers''. Most able-bodied building
workers are cracking up because they can't work in heat like that. They
can work in howling gales at the top of the sort of scaffolding high
enough for Chicago's Sear's building but they will drap doon deid in
heat like this summer's. And I hate the heat myself.
How I hate the heat. I have spent the last month sweating like a child
molester. D'you see, the heat has got to me and I am now writing prose
so unacceptable for a family newspaper that it has to be the Sun getting
to me. Gad this heat, damn these flies. It could be east of anywhere
Somerset Maugham had ever visited.
All I need is a solar topee, a wrinkled linen suit, a sweaty hankie in
one hand and a gin-sling in the other; the next thing you know I shall
be committing hara-kiri in Java having slaughtered the Portuguese trader
in the next bungalow. Here. I can get used to this. Dashed good idea.
Carruthers I shall call myself.
So I am sweating enough pints of whatever it is I drink to slake the
thirst of Gunga Din's little pal and do I not bump into a young lady
friend of mine, a Doctor O'Neill. I am not sure I am allowed to name a
doctor, like advertising, really, but that's her problem and not mine.
She is a GP and shatteringly lovely and worse, rather caustive when she
wants to be.
''How are you'' she asks. ''Terrible,'' I retort, ''the heat is
driving me to distraction. I am ill, I tell you, ill.'' Her attitude
left a lot to be desired coming from a young and lovely lady doctor.
She wanted to know what I expected. I have, she pointed out,
pointedly, liver disease, sugar-level problems, severe hay-fever
symptoms, arthritis, and I am overweight and take no exercise, unless
you count the physical process of shoving fags and booze down my throat
at such regular intervals that she was surprised, she said, that I was
displaying any sort of life at all. ''I hope you don't imagine you will
join our practice,'' she told me coldly, adding, ''We can't afford
you.''
A bit miffed I was; told her I intend to leave my organs for
unfortunates in need. She more or less intimated that the Messiah
himself couldn't come back from the Dead if he was supplied with a
McLean transplant. Well I ask you? And then she told me that part of my
problem was that I was fat.
Well, Dr O'Neill, I hope your time comes as well. Should I live so
long I will positively crow, my dear, at your sudden expansion from a
size 10 to a size 16.
The heat is bad enough; the men in shorts are worse. I might look
surrealist enough in a floral frock but Salvador Dali couldn't come up
with anything more bizarre than a Glaswegian over the age of 20 in
shorts, and no socks.
Not so the modern Scots lass. She looks horribly well and the shorter
the shorts, the higher the skirt, the more splendidly chaste, confident,
haughty, and lovely she seems to look. Sunshine is designed to make
ducklings look swans.
I may say my physical capabilities, as that of any male, are truly
diminished by the heat of a heatwave, but my ardour isn't. The reason
why suddenly the most beautiful women and girls emerge when the sun
takes its hat off is because the sun transforms them all.
Sadly it transforms men as well. Only the very young males can cope
with this. Middle-aged fellows take upon them paunches held in in the
calm of winter and their natural tumescence can be held back by the
weather. It is not the weather for chaps at all really. And don't the
Young and Female know it. Good luck to them at that.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
