<HEADLINE>A close-up of village life between the covers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM SHIELDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>DIARY</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830496</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE sleepy East Neuk fishing village of Anstruther emerges in a new
book as a hotbed of sex and sin. Keeping up with Magda, a first novel by
local writer Isla Dewar, is set in the mythical village of Mareth ''a
noisy, seething place where everyone knows everything about each other
and what they don't know they assume.
''From Granny Moran who can never escape her raunchy past to Ginny
Howard, who is wasted chairing the Mareth Improvement Committee when she
should be sorting out the Middle East, the villagers live against a
constantly changing backdrop of elaborate scheming and sexual
activity.''
We asked around and this seems like a pretty fair description of life
in Anstruther. Isla Dewar, being diplomatic, insists that while she has
taken the setting and the mood of Anstruther for her novel, none of the
characters are based on locals.
She said: ''It could be any small town. Parochialism is fairly
international.'' Isla tells us she has also lived in Kirriemuir and
Forfar. This could either be a hedging of the bets or an attempt by her
to have the good folk of these places buying the book, as well as
Anstrutheronians, in attempts to put real names to fictitious
characters.
The book is published next month by Headline at #14.99 who are so
confident it will be a success that Isla Dewar's second novel,
provisionally titled Women Talking Dirty, will be out next spring.
* The Diary must apologise that due to pressure of deadlines we were
unable to fillet Ms Dewar's book and pass on the, er, highlights.
Hamish lives on
THE Regional Directorate of the BBC has a new financial database.
Thank you for reading on.
The database has been given the name Hamish. It has been called Hamish
after a regional directorate person's Scottie dog which died recently,
which shows a nice human touch for people who run financial databases.
But the BBC being such an acronymic place, people have been asking
what Hamish stands for. (The TV industry is full of acronyms such as
ENCA, editor news and current affairs, and HOLE, head of light
entertainment.)
Anyway, a prize of a bottle of champagne has been put up by BBC high
heid yins for whoever can come up with the best meaning for the acronym
Hamish. Our chums at BBC Scotland are in with a shout with their version
-- Half-Arsed Management Information System for Headquarters.
For the record
THERE are some stories which, we feel, are better told exactly as they
come to us. John I. Thomson of Glasgow writes: ''I earn a living as a
freelance radio producer. Recently I was in Govan to do some tape
recording. I was walking along a street between Govan Road and Golspie
Avenue when I noticed a strange creature, dead, lying on the ground. It
reminded me of the creature from Aliens.
''I was about to move on when I was joined by a man and a woman. 'Do
you know what that is?' asked the woman. I shook my head. 'It's a
lizard. Something's went and ate a lizard. Still,' she continued,
'that's Govan for you,' and walked on.''
See Govan? See encounters?
Field of conflict
DEPT of Seeing Oursels As Ithers See Us: The scene is the train from
Glasgow to Edinburgh where four very unquiet American tourists are
dominating proceedings. The train stops near Murrayfield whereupon one
of the Americans points to the stadium and announces: ''That's where
they hold the soccer riots.''
A gay gargle
THEY say it doesn't make you a bad person, so the Diary was willing to
try GL Gay Lager. This brew is sold in Route 66, a pub which claims to
be Edinburgh's sole stockist of gay lager.
It is produced by the Pride Brewing Company of Manchester and comes in
a black and pink tin with the motto ''The spirit to defeat the
prejudice''. We outed a couple of the tins at #1.80 each for 500ml and
tried it on some colleagues.
Rugby writer Derek Douglas gave it a bad review (we will not quote him
exactly) but that's what these macho oval-ball people are like. How
would you like to face the Scottish XV after admitting that you quite
liked gay lager? Photographer Mike Wilkinson thought it tasted a bit
like Skol.
As they also say, don't knock it till you've tried it.
*THE above sign was snapped for our delectation by Senga Deans of
Glasgow while on a trip to Kent in southernmost England. It transpires
that this is a genuine if not entirely official twinning between the
tiny hamlet of Pett Bottom, near Canterbury, and the wee Scottish toun
best known for its football team, Stenhousemuir Nil.
The man behind the scheme is Ron Brown, mine host of the Duck Inn and,
by public acclaim, Mayor of Pett Bottom. Mr Brown was impressed to see
on TV that Stenhousemuir had an Oslo supporters club and decided that
Pett Bottom should become the southernmost outpost of fans of the
Ochilview team.
Their enthusiasm became even greater when Stenhousemuir scored that
kenspeckle Scottish Cup victory earlier this year over Aberdeen.
The Pett Bottom Stenhousemuir Supporters Club will take in their first
game in October when they travel north -- about 40-strong -- and will
even sponsor the match ball. Paul Tewkesbury, barman at the Duck Inn,
has ben appointed archivist of the supporters club.
His task is to dig out information on Stenhousemuir. ''All I know so
far is that they have never won a trophy,'' he told the Diary. ''We have
a Scot who is a regular at the Duck Inn. He is a Dundee fan but we hope
to bring him north to act as an interpreter.''
</TEXT>
