<HEADLINE>Taking a poolside view of a long-lost resort</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JULIE DAVIDSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830497</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE VIEW from the top of the chute, a precipitous funnel which only
just accommodates my middle-aged hips, has scarcely altered in four
decades. I see the landscaping round the new sewage-treatment plant
tunnelled into the cliffs of the East Bay, and a recent housing
development above Coo's Green; the pool itself has got bluer, apeing the
azure of the Caribbean in a doomed effort to achieve the allure of a
brochure sunspot, but otherwise little has change.
It's a view which belongs to the simplest and most blameless part of
my life: the sandy scoops on either side of the Platcock Rocks, the
rough red boulders of the harbour with the ambient percussion of its
yachts, the grave guest houses and stately villas on the edge of the
links, the volcanic hump on the town's back and the breezy glitter of
the Forth estuary at its front. I pick off the islands west to east, by
names which are fixed on an early map of memory: Fidra, the Lamb,
Craigleith, the Isle of May on the sea's horizon and the big Bass Rock,
whiter than ever in its skin of guano, a misplaced iceberg.
North Berwick is a national treasure. It should be protected by
Historic Scotland, although that would almost certainly ruin it. It's
one of the few places left in Scotland which can give children (and
adults) the experience of an old-fashioned seaside resort, but it's
about to lose the soul of its summer identity: the huge outdoor swimming
pool, one of three East Coast survivors of its kind, which closes for
good at the end of the month.
The timing is cruel. Not only has the summer been sublime but the
municipal swimming-pool is only a year short of its centenary. Its
thrilling seawater cavity was hacked out of the Platcock Rocks in 1896
when the site -- an old rubbish dump -- was developed by some of the
Victorian investors who turned North Berwick into the ''Biarritz of the
North''. By 1913 instructors had been appointed to teach people to swim,
and for the next 50 years the pond and its esplanade were the nerve
centre of the summer season.
There were galas; therer were diving displays; there were ''the
pierrots'' in the harbour pavilion was built in 1930. Now the pool's
esplanade neighbour is moribund, too, despite community efforts to keep
it open for the local operatic society. Yet their site is magnificent
and their potential challenging. Oh for some visionary Victorian
investors . . .
East Lothian District Council sure don't fit the bill. As regards
North Berwick's status as national treasure (and consequent ornament to
a tourist industry which, if predictions about warmer summers are
accurate, will be more and more home-loving) they have thrown in the
towel. They're building a new indoor pool at the top of the town --
nothing special, no Wet 'n' Wild -- and say they can't afford to
maintain the seasonal outdoor one, too.
Their engineers are investigating, but they haven't yet decided what
to do with the site, the esplanade and the Harbour Pavilion, although
the option of extending the harbour has been -- ahem -- floated; which
will almost certainly kill two with one planning proposal, as the
existing harbour, built of russet porphyry stone from the quarry on
Berwick Law, couldn't be repeated and deserves its own protection.
Only the most sentimental would deny that the pool itself needs
investment. Its facilities are primitive, and (apart from a heating
system which barely takes the chill off the water and a fence of flashy
perspex windbreaks whose opaque cobalt blue is designed to exclude
spectators who haven't paid for seats) they haven't been updated since I
lived in North Berwick as a child in the fifties.
Yes, my children, we were tough as Arctic seals in those days. We
started swimming in the unheated, unfiltered seawater at the beginning
of May and didn't stop until mid-September, tutored first by Pondmaster
McCracken, whose custodian's eye and severity with rules made his
aquatic fief the safest of playgrounds. We only stopped swimming on
cleaning days, when the pool was emptied and task forces of
holidaymakers joined the staff to scrub it down.
We undressed and dressed in communal changing rooms, one for Ladies
and Girls, one for Boys and one for Gentlemen, who presumably couldn't
be trusted with the boys. They are all still there. The damp, concrete
floors are still there, and the worn, wooden benches and the white
tiles. You still store your clothes in heavy wire-baskets and hand them
into the Basket Room for safekeeping, and there's a paucity of hot
showers which surely weren't there in the fifties, otherwise we wouldn't
have needed our ''chittering bites.'' But my 11-year-old and her chum,
who joined me in my last splash, were beguiled by the quaintness of it
all.
These are children who have bathed in some of the most sophisticated
waterparks in the world. They are flume-wise from Stingray through River
Rapids to Geronimo's Leap, but they judged North Berwick Outdoor Pool
''brilliant.'' They loved the sheer scale of the pond, the exhilarating
views from the chute, the little waves whipped up by the breeze, the
sense of ''safe'' sea-bathing.
We signed the petition. North Berwick has been slow to respond to the
death-throes of its pool, which have been known for some time, but a
campaign of opposition is now underway; almost certainly too late.
A few years ago I met a long-standing resident whose husband's nanny
had also been nanny to the Ethiopian royal family when they were exiled
in Britain during the war. Ruth Tweedie told me that the Emperor Haile
Selassie sent his grandson to the resort every summer, ''because Nellie
Wood said no child should be brought up without spending his holidays in
North Berwick.''
It's an idea worth cherishing, along with the pool.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
