<HEADLINE>Fly way to drive off midges</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANVAR KHAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>TRIED TESTED</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830498</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
With the help of an able-bodied volunteer, Anvar Khan puts some insect
repellent to the test on Scotland's perennial scourge.
WHEN hiking two weeks ago in the Highlands, my partner's walking
stick, a brontosaurus thigh no less, was spotted by some fellow
travellers.
''Is that for the midges?'' asked the extra from The Sound of Music.
Scotch midges are horrible, bumbling and determinedly stupid. To them,
you're just one big landing zone. They and the weather alone are
responsible for off-putting tourists.
For miles and miles of pure, virgin scenery is marred by black, blurry
and buzzing raisins ducking and diving within vision. It's probably
because theirs isn't so hot that they bump into you in the first place,
and it was with this theory in mind, that I volunteered my boyfriend for
The Herald Great Midge Repellent Experiment. He's nearly 6ft high and
3ft broad (muscle not fat) so they couldn't miss him. He agreed. He's
such a gentleman.
''All you have to do,'' he said, ''is spray each of the repellents on
me, stand back, and watch to see what happens''.
It is, during such occasions, for there are many, that I regard myself
as a lucky girl, having a personal Rambo. My mission was to test the
effectiveness of four brands of beastie-killer to bum them completely
from my personal space.
Some might say it was nasty of me to take advantage of my boyfriend's
good nature, but I say it was survival. Japanese-style torture tests are
not written into my contract.
Folklore is responsible for a horde of silly acts and deeds which
precede the triumph of hope over experience. A pot of sweet gale ensures
a bite-free zone. Crofters used to put it in the straw beds they slept
on. A Scottish plant by the glamorous name of Bog Myrtle is said to be a
remedy, as is cigarette smoke.
Other mythological measures include local dirt. If a person covers him
or herself with village earth the midges will stay away, because it is
only alien smells that they are attracted to.
As it was, David was not bitten but he was chased. The closest he got
to being spiked was when a wasp tried to get down the back of his neck
in the car. Yes, we nearly crashed. Road safety, it seems, is as good a
reason as any to stamp out the little suckers for ever.
MOSI-GUARD NATURAL
* BRAND: Mosi-Guard Natural
Contents: 75ml
Price: #4.45
Smell: A mixture of eucalyptus and cedarwood.
Effectiveness: A good wasp deterrent.
Marks out of 10: 5
Anvar: This claims to be non-toxic, and approved and recommended by
the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine. No adverse effects
on fabrics and surfaces.
David: When I sprayed it on a whirlwind of midges they moved off to
the side until the air cleared, and then they moved back. It's stinking
on the skin. Very oily. So strong in fact, that it stripped the dye off
the container on to my hands. The blue blotches eventually came off with
detergent and a nailbrush.
SHOO! INSECT REPELLENT
* BRAND: Shoo! Insect Repellent
Contents: 30ml
Price: #2.60
Smell: A mixture of pink bubblegum and dentist's mouthwash.
Effectiveness: It says ''Apply before imminent attack''. Don't,
because it doesn't.
Marks out of 10: 2
Anvar: Made in Argyll, Scotland, so you'd think that having a great
experience of Highland beasties, the makers would concoct a strong,
merciless cure. Allegedly water-resistant.
David: Weak and greasy. They used to issue this stuff in the army. The
only time you put it on is when you sweat, after running, because
insects want your salt. But either the sweat just washes it off, or the
repellent just attracts them because they come at you in swarms.
BOOTS REPEL PLUS
* BRAND: Boots Repel Plus
Contents: 100ml
Price: #3.35
Smell: A strong gin and tonic or a vodka and bitter lemon with an
undernote of French furniture polish.
Effectiveness: The midges took their time but they went.
Marks out of 10: 6
Anvar: CFC-free, and contains 20% Diethyl toluamide to ward off
insects and 0.5% Permethrin to help prevent insects from biting. The
toluamide, however, is now known to cause side effects such as skin
irritation.
David: Sticks to the skin like hairspray. When directed into the air,
this attracts a bigger and better class of bug. It drives wasps crazy,
it produced a kamikaze effect, they started diving into each other in a
frenzy. They don't bite you but go on to bite each other instead.
X-GNAT SKIN GEL
* BRAND: X-Gnat Skin Gel
Contents: 100ml
Price: #4.45
Smell: A milder version of Mosi-Guard, but less potent.
Effectiveness: For 6-8 hours allegedly, but who'd take the chance.
Marks out of 10: 6
Anvar: Says it does ''not contain harmful Diethyl toluamide (deet)''.
Contains ingredients from flowers and aromatic oils. This product is the
only one not tested on animals, but tested on people. It doesn't says
whether it's been tested on midges.
David: The cream disappears into the skin quickly. Flies and wasps
appeared in their hundreds to smell me, but none landed. They were very
curious about my body odour. If you get it on your lips, however, it
burns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
