<TEXT>
* WOULD you have the nerve to offer a credit card for a 50p train
fare? For anyone who shares anxieties about rail safety voiced this
week, toughing it out at the ticket office could be a smart move.
According to the credit card companies, not everyone realises they
qualify for free accident insurance each time they pay plastic. Royal
Bank of Scotland, for instance, offers a #50,000 benefits package for
death or serious injury while travelling by train, airliner, coach and
ship, or a car hired for up to 30 days. Cover extends to spouses and
dependent children.
Even on long-distance train journeys, many cardholders still opt for
cash or cheques, so the chances of their buying a local ticket with Visa
or Access are even more remote. In fact, most recent fatalities have
taken place on suburban services.
ScotRail say they will accept a credit card for even their cheapest
fare -- a 50p single, although they wouldn't claim to be ecstatic at the
prospect. To learn more about playing your cards correctly, ask the
payment centre shown on your monthly statement.
* WANTED: Scotland's most dedicated child carer. Baby product
manufacturer St Ivel is offering a #1000 prize to the winner of their
1995 competition, plus #250 for the nominator.
As well as standard skills, judges will be looking for someone who
keeps junior entertained in a ''fun but educational way'', pays
attention to diet, health and welfare -- and comes up smiling while
wiping baby's bum. To enter your child carer, send a 250-word pen
portrait and recent colour photo to St Ivel, Cavendish House, 33
Margaret Street, London W1N 7LA by the end of the month. An SAE is
needed to return photos.
* ANYONE who sympathises with ex-Far East POWs' pleas to boycott
Japanese goods will find it hard going. When Check-out examined product
information at electrical supermarkets like ScottishPower and Currys,
the country of origin wasn't indicated. If sales staff are to be
believed, shoppers care more about interest-free credit and cashbacks
than where their washing machine, fridge or camcorder comes from.
John Lewis customers seem more discriminating: at its branches in
Edinburgh and Aberdeen labelling provides full information about the
country of manufacture for those who care about such things.
* GET HIPP is the advice for mothers concerned about what goes into
baby foods. Europe's leading organic baby food, HIPP, is now on sale in
Scotland.
All the fruits and vegetables used are guaranteed free from pesticide
residues and the synthetic chemical fertilisers used in conventional
farming. Ingredients come from accredited organic farms, regularly
checked to ensure soil and seeds meet rigorous quality standards.
Of the 24 varieties available, 15 are suitable for vegetarians.
Stockists include Boots, Safeway, Tesco and Co-ops, health food shops
and pharmacies. For a leaflet and money-off voucher, write to HIPP
Nutrition, 169 New Greenham Park, Newbury, Berks RG 15 8JH.
</TEXT>
