<HEADLINE>Out of town, beyond reach</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH WESTCOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830500</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ELIZABETH WESTCOTT marvels at the convenience of out-of-town
superstores, and their remoteness from some of the most disadvantaged
communities.
What could be more convenient than one-stop shopping, where all
consumer needs from the supermarket to the post-office are housed in one
spacious, shining complex?
In Scotland, 70% of food is bought in superstores, many of which are
located out of town, on purpose-built sites, where you can buy clothes,
have them dry-cleaned, have your prescriptions dispensed at a pharmacy,
withdraw extra cash from the till where you pay for your groceries, and
stop for coffee at a nice cafe when your feet hurt.
What does it matter if the local shops have a narrow range of goods
and are more expensive? It doesn't, if you have a car or access to a
good public transport.
But for the elderly, who depend on not having to travel far for their
needs, for mothers encumbered with young children or for people stranded
in poorly-serviced housing estates, these shopping developments are not
accessible. Often, low-income consumers end up paying more.
The recent launch of the Government's Draft National Planning Policy
Guideline on Retailing, emphasising the protection of town centres, has
been welcomed by the Scottish Consumer Council. It believes that
low-income consumers should have access to the same shopping facilities
and competitive prices enjoyed by the more affluent and mobile, says SCC
director Ann Foster.
''If you are without access to private transport then you are
disadvantaged in lots of ways,'' she says. ''You can't buy in bulk or
take advantage of special offers. You are paying high prices in smaller
shops. While you're dealing with a local trader who knows your needs,
for many people there is no match for low prices.''
Out-of-town developments are not a bad idea in themselves, Foster
says. In addition to providing wide choice and quality they have other
effects, such as easing inner-city congestion created by heavy-goods
vehicles.
''However, they can take away from an area that was previously
thriving,'' said Foster. ''Normally you find an anchor store like a
supermarket in a shopping development, and once that is taken away it
has a knock-on effect for other stores. There are bits of Glasgow that
have become dead that were once thriving.''
Part of the problem is the increasing domination of multiple retailers
who do not have outlets in poorer areas, as some disadvantaged
Glaswegian estates have experienced.
''Large multinationals have extremely sophisticated area profiles;
they simply won't go there. These people will have local retailers but
they won't get the multiples.
''It's a very competitive market, so groups like Safeway, which
recently reported a reduction in profits, are not likely to display a
sudden outburst of community spirit if it is not going to keep the
shareholders happy,'' claims Foster.
This last point was disputed by both Tesco and Safeway. Tesco says
that while it would not discriminate against poorer areas, it was
''obviously looking for prime locations''. Safeway spokeswoman Odette
Sullivan, says that the relative wealth of an area was not part of its
criteria for site selection.
''Safeway will go quite happily into housing estates . . . It more
depends on where stores can be built. Safeway is trying to generate
one-stop shopping and the minimum size for a new store is 25,000sq ft,
so that's what guides us where to go.''
The fact remains, as one Glasgow health worker pointed out, that
multiple retailers will choose the most economically viable areas, and
community spirit is hardly going to influence those decisions.
Professor John Dawson of Edinburgh University, who wrote a report on
retail development trends for the Scottish Office in 1994, sums up the
problem in one neat question: are retailers providing an economic
service or a social service?
''There's a trade-off between consumers being provided with a local
service which isn't economically strong or accessibility to something
with a wider choice,'' Professor Dawson says.
''The same issue applies to remote rural areas. Is a person's right to
have access to a shop the same as the right to have access to a library?
Policies don't address those specific problems.
''Low-mobility people become disadvantaged if there are no changes in
public transport, but if they are services then it shouldn't pose a
problem.''
The guideline stresses the need to site new developments where they
are accessible by public as well as private transport.
While this does not solve the problem of the elderly or mothers with
children travelling home with shopping, it will allow access to those
without cars.
Recognising some of the problems that have occurred with shopping
developments is an important step, but the SCC believes that a public
commitment should be made to following the guidelines, so that
low-income consumers are less disadvantaged.
''They do take account of regional structures and there is much more
emphasis given to sustainable development,'' says Ann Foster. ''However,
the problem with guidelines is that it takes take a long time to see any
effect.''
</TEXT>
