<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Going by the book for trusted friends</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830501</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
William Russell looks at festive present ideas from the National Trust
for Scotland.
THE clootie dumpling is rapidly becoming the National Trust for
Scotland's trademark. Last year the Trust sold 600 of the things through
its mail order service. This year the dumpling in a presentation tin
costs #6.50. Food is always welcome, and the Trust, ever seeking
something new in the cut-throat world of the mail order Christmas
catalogue has produced its first ever Taste of Scotland hamper -- a
basket of goodies rather than one of those things with lids -- a snip at
#13.99. From Pettigrews of Kelso, the basket contains a 14oz Christmas
pudding, cranberry sauce, hot gooseberry chutney, lemon curd, and a box
of butter shortbread rounds.
Add a giant mince pie made in Dundee (#2.25), a whisky fruit cake
(#6.50), and some of the Trust's sought after after-dinner mints (#2.95)
and you could be this year's favourite giver of presents. On the other
hand the people you love may prefer to make and bake their own, in which
case give them either the Haute Ecosse pack of 40 Scottish recipes for
everything from Cullen Skink to Black Bun (#7.95) or The Laird's
Kitchen, which documents 300 years of Scottish cooking and gives recipes
for some fine feasts (#18.95).
The NTS Christmas mail order catalogue is a cut above the rest. The
nightcap set -- two dram glasses and a miniature decanter engraved with
a leaping salmon design -- is just the thing for insomniacs, and comfort
could also be found in the bag of marbles with booklet of instructions
(#9.95), ever so much more enthralling than a computer game. You can get
the catalogue for yourself from The National Trust for Scotland -- 0131
243 9393.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
