<DOCNO>GH950818-000037</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000037</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Umbilical Brothers, Gilded Balloon</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976830502</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YON fabulous Umbilicals begin at the gates of Heaven and end by
tilting the Gilded Balloon's very fabric first 180 degrees one way and
then 180 degrees another.
In between, they race across a richly-realised cartoon soundscape,
Wile E Coyote versus Wile E Coyote, in high-powered cars and thundering
juggernauts, on skateboard and on horseback. Lunar weightlessness is
explored and exploited. Chainsaws buzz and gizzards are extruded.
It's like being sucked into a blockbuster movie starring Bruce Willis,
Bruce Lee and Bluto -- all of it miraculously created on stage by two
skinny blokes in red singlets. I clapped till my hands exploded in a
cascade of blood and bone-shards. Almost. See the Umbilicals and learn
that an imaginatively-propelled human body has no limits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000038</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000038</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Yanks are soldiering on. Tete en L'air, Churchill Theatre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830503</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A GIANT pinball table towers on its end. Wriggling and squirming
between the prongs are bodies in army fatigues. Sounds of amplified
rapid-fire nick our eardrums. This is D2R (Descent 2 Return or Detour)
and the vertically dangling bodies belong to American company Diavolo
Dance Theater.
Diavolo's work seems to centre on bizarre tests of endurance. They
could craft assault courses for Green Beret wannabes. AWOL finds a
hapless female (white-shirted among black-balaclava'ed hordes) pursued
through flying tackles and acrobatic scrums.
The light relief of Bonjour! gives way to the commando antics of D2R
before new horizons descending from great heights arrive headlong down
the huge wooden steps of Tet en L'air. It doesn't just defy gravity, it
eventually defies watching -- seriously pleased with itself, I'm afraid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000039</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000039</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Enveloppes et Deballages, Theatre Workshop</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MINTY DONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976830504</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A POSTMAN, unmistakably French in his chic-but-shabby uniform, wheels
his ramshackle bicycle on stage, its load of exotically stamped parcels
and packages hinting at foreign travel and faraway places.
With engaging humour, which makes light of the skill and precision of
his performance, the postie lovingly unpacks a miniature fantasy world
from his mysterious brown parcels, leading the audience on a journey of
dream-logic; from tropical island, complete with baby dinosaur and
smoking volcano, through sea voyage to circus tent.
For anyone who's ever struggled to build their own ''Tracey Island'',
collected Brittan's plastic animals, or delighted in show-domes, this
Velo Theatre production is a must. A theatre-of-the-dinky, steering just
the right side of the cutely whimsical.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000040</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000040</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Drouth, Acoustic Music Centre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ADAMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976830505</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE new line-up of an old band, they promised. But it was really It
Ain't Half Hot Mum, with said parent greeted from the stage, and even
Windsor Davies's doppelganger on keyboard. Alongside stood four
colleagues, a credit to any concert party. Or perhaps a village hall
because, judging from the familiar, two-way badinage, it seemed the
whole village was there to hear the boys' triumphant return.
Well, it's better to travel in hope etc. What they actually got were
workmanlike singalongs, an instrumental medley that will ensure Altan
sleep soundly in their beds, and the spectacle of a grown man going for
notes he hadn't sung since he was in the Cubs. The Drouth -- catch them
before they make it big. You've plenty time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000041</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000041</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pattullo and Turner, Leone Cockburn Gallery</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CLARE HENRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976830506</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO west coast painters are selling well here. Helen Turner's big
breezy skies and white sands of Rhum, Eigg and Skye are inspired by the
Colourists. Cadell is obviously her hero, and even Loch Ken comes in for
Mediterranean treatment.
Mussel Beds, Prestwick (acquired by Flemings) has a nice vigour. I
also like The Picnic, a more casual composition where you can feel the
sand in the cucumber sandwiches. A Spray of Gold Forsythia is another
noteworthy small picture, so too At Anchor, Tarbert where limpid wet
sand is captured with a sure touch.
Lin Pattullo weaves all her scenes into patterns, be they Venice or
Troon. She can overdo it but Seat in the Sun keeps this to a minimum, so
too Noon Doorways, Greece. Leone Cockburn's gallery at 21 Dean Park Mews
is the perfect setting for domestic pictures. You can see what they
would look like at home.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000042</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000042</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Greg Proops, Assembly Rooms</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976830507</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IS The Shark going soft and gumsy on his E-burg crowds? ''Do you
realise, the more seriously you take it, the more evil I become?''
That's what the legendarily-cruel Greg asked us, sensing a certain
uneasiness in the stalls when the Queen Mom seemed about to get hers.
But then what happens? Greg lets the old royal gimp off, that's what.
Same as he does with the woman in the balcony who keeps saying ''Wuh''
at inopportune moments. Having vaulted from the stage, Greg simply ends
up wagging a metaphorical finger at her. But when it comes to bigger,
more culpable targets, Greg's comic insights remain deeply wounding.
David Copperfield, John Major, Kevin Costner, supermodels, Tories,
Republicans: all were tortured and then killed by Greg Proops's barbed
tongue, a weapon as sharp as ever it was.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000043</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000043</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mel and Sue, Pleasance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976830508</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FROM last year's triumphal cast of skewed characters, there are but
two survivors: Mariella and Petra, the energetically-vapid Dutch MTV
presenters. Thankfully, Mel and Sue's trenchant powers of observation
remain wholly intact. Emma Thompson and Liz Hurley get theirs, along
with targets ranging from organic aristos in Tuscany to Home Counties
hip-hop home-girls.
Would it be accurate or fair to hail Mel and Sue as a latter-day
French and Saunders? No. They're much faster and fresher, zappier,
snappier. It might be more instructive to label them a post-feminist
ambient-techno re-mix of Joyce Grenfell and Victoria Wood. Or it might
not. Either way, when you see them, you'll say: ''Wham-bam, thank you,
ma'ams.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000044</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000044</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Storm in a Teacup, Pleasance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DANIELLE NAGLER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976830509</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
''IT was OK,'' said Tommy and Davey, ''but there was too much story.''
They have a good point, for instead of concentrating on the magic in
Shakespeare's Tempest, Intimate Exchanges decided that they were going
to try and retell the whole story, in a child-sized lump, with a few
random glances at the original text. The result was rushed and at points
misunderstood, with too much meat and only a couple of chips.
There was too little Ariel, although his few appearances and songs
went down well, unlike Prospero's magic cagoul which didn't seem to
impress. The audience participation was popular, but a little hurried.
The younger members of the audience did come out with opinions about the
characters they had seen on stage, but they weren't captivated. They
were never offered  a chance to leave this world of flesh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Curious Seeds, St Bride's Centre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976830510</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COOL, controlled strength is the hallmark of Ricochet's first piece,
Re-Coil. Choreographed by Russell Maliphant to a throbbing, drilling
soundscore (Andy Cowton), it deals in images of sustained composure shot
through with spasms of fast, dynamic movement. Almost sculptural in its
lines, this is complex, absorbing -- beautifully performed -- dance.
In complete, and gorgeous, contrast is E Muoio Disperato by Javier de
Frutos. Everyone -- men too -- dressed in short, flirty scarlet frocks.
And as Puccini's Tosca pours out anthems of passion, the five dancers
throw themselves into a malestrom of avid sex, jealousy and death where
resurrection comes in suctioning kisses that hoover bodies off the
floor. Wow! Brilliantly extravagant stuff, full of wit and clever,
clever movement all danced with feisty panache..
Ends Saturday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ivor Dembina, Pleasance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DANIELLE NAGLER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976830511</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HE'S a Jewish comedian who happens to be Jewish. And Jewish jokes are
funny. And he's talked to his lawyer brother, so he's ready to be sued
if the audience leaves without laughing.
Ivor Dembina is celebrating a decade in Edinburgh and has brought his
family and rabbi along to share it with him. He ambles over Israeli
politics, Jewish prostitutes, and his Bar Mitzvah, and lets the audience
be funny too.
Playing off the Jewish stereotypes, Dembina tells a good story, and
most of the time it's repeatable. And the audience laughs. Quite a lot.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dan Freedman, Pleasance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976830512</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHY, apologetic and understated, Dan Freedman teeters prettily on the
deconstructionist tightrope, creating a form of comedy which is mostly
about comedy itself.
In other, plainer words, while Dan's act echoes that of many
contemporary stand-ups in lampooning kitschy seventies TV shows, his
does so with a knowing half-smile which seems to say: ''Isn't it a bit
sad that so many contemporary stand-ups are content to go for the easy
laugh by lampooning kitschy seventies TV shows?''
This is a difficult trick to pull off. Dan manages it, though. Yet
it's also one with an in-built tendency towards disappearing up its own
fundament. See him and you'll hope Dan doesn't vanish.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Don't Start Me, Gilded Balloon II</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SARA VILLIERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976830513</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IS Tasty McDade Glasgow's answer to Archie Rice? Not quite, but
writers John Paul Leach and Ford Keirnan have certainly crafted a
memorable and richly-characterised entertainer in Tasty, so named
because of the slang for nice he picked up after two years ''shovelling
shit'' in London.
The two-hander is a polished production from Castlemilk People's
Theatre, with Pat Welsh subtly suggesting all the bottled-up resentments
of Tasty, a Scottish stand-up, emanating real menace. The play traces
his rise, inevitable fall and various dodgy dealings through the sixties
to the eighties, with Stephen McCole offering solid support in diverse
roles, from Mrs McDade to a Glasgwegian henchman.
The dark undertones of the piece are most obviously realised in the
spotlighted segments of Tasty's act, cruder than anything you'll find on
the Fringe -- perhaps more Glasgow's answer to Bernard Manning.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>NFUS could engage Scottish Office in legal battle. Union set to challenge sheep quota rule change</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS, FARMING EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830514</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Office could face a legal challenge from the National
Farmers' Union of Scotland if it decides to adopt the same stance as the
Ministry of Agriculture south of the Border and change the rules
governing the allocation of sheep quota from the national reserve.
The industry was thrown into confusion on Wednesday night when the
Ministry, with no prior warning, announced it proposed to revise the
criteria for the ''developers'' category of the 1993 sheep and suckler
cow reserves.
The NFU in England and Wales has been involved in a long-running
dispute with the Ministry over the way in which the regulations covering
allocations from the national reserve were being applied.
Farmers who claimed to have given prior notice of their intention to
increase their flocks found they were not qualifying for a full
allocation. This meant that some of their ewes would not qualify for
sheep annual premium payments, currently worth more than #20 a head.
After failing to reach any agreement with the Ministry, the NFU in
England sought a judicial review and won its case when Mr Justice
MacPherson ruled that the UK quota regulations determining eligibility
for developers quota were unlawful.
The result is that the Ministry has decided to start again from square
one, which could mean some farmers being allocated less quota so that
others, who were unsuccessful in their original applications, can get an
allocation.
Scottish Office ministers were said yesterday to be urgently
considering the implications of all this for Scotland. Scottish
Agriculture Minister, the Earl of Lindsay, was in discussion with his
counterparts at the Ministry of Agriculture in Whitehall and promised a
further announcement as soon as possible.
The Scottish NFU, which did not take court action in Scotland over the
intitial complaints, announced yesterday that it was now consulting its
lawyers about developments south of the Border.
It seems unlikely that the Scottish Office would fail to fall in step
with Whitehall on this issue.
Mr John Ross, president of the NFUS, warned that the statement issued
by the Ministry of Agriculture in London could have serious implications
for some quota holders in Scotland. '' We are taking advice about
whether or not these moves can be challenged,'' he said.
''We fear that Scottish producers who hold quota quite legally could
face a frustrating period of uncertainty, with no firm guarantee of
compensation. This is unacceptable to us and the Scottish Office have
been told of our attitude.
Our aim is to see to it that all those with legitimate claims for
quota are satisfied without putting in danger the allocations already
made.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Over-producing dairy farmers are warned of #2.8m penalty</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830515</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Milk has warned its dairy farmer members that those who were
over quota in the last ''milk year'' will face penalties totalling
#2.8m.
The company said the liability for levy would be shared among 750
members of the co-operative. It had not yet calculated individual
liability, which would be applied according to the degree of
over-production in each case.
An estimated threshold of 4.5% of quota will apply, which means that
levy will only become payable by individual producers once they have
exceeded quota by by that amount.
This is possible because some producers will have failed to use all
their quota allowance. At Scottish Milk the over-quota figure was 12,600
litres. At a UK level the total liability for levy has been
provisionally calculated at just over #48m.
There are indications that some over-producers in Scotland could be
facing bills in the region of #15,000.
Andrew Macfarlane of quota brokers Hayes, McCubbin Macfarlane,
Aberdeen, said the figures showed how important it was for farmers to
try to stick to their quota allocation.
''I was surprised at how many Scottish Milk members were over-target,
but I imagine that many of them would be only fractionally over. ''
Those who were more than fractionally over quota would come to realise
that it could be a risky policy, he said. Some of those who had a close
shave should be considering buying extra quota now while prices were
about the 60p a litre mark.
In England, Milk Marque, the dominant co-operative, has warned that it
may have to break some of its supply contracts because of a fall in milk
production due to the continuing drought.
Scottish Milk has also noted a drop of between one and two per cent
this month and say it is monitoring the position on a daily basis.
Meanwhile, Scottish farmers can expect payments of more than #148m
under the Arable Area Payments Scheme.
Despite an overshoot of 3.8% in the non-less favoured areas sector,
leading to the application, of penalties, payments will be #33m up on
last year.
Concessions negotiated by the Government mean that penalties will be
imposed at 50% of what would be the normal rate, but Agriculture
Minister the Earl of Lindsay warned this would be the last opportunity
for farmers to get their claims down to base area figures before full
penalties begin to be applied next year.
He expressed disappointment at the failure to get production aligned
with base area figures. There was no overshoot in the less favoured
area.
Scottish NFU cereals convener David Jack responded that it was wrong
that Scottish producers should be penalised at a time when the grain
market was seriously under-supplied.
''A permanent solution must be found which will allow Scottish
producers to fulfil market demands without the threat of penalties,'' he
said.
The Scottish Office Agriculture Department expects to make the first
tranche of oilseeds payments to some 2000 farmers within the next few
weeks.
The final payment for oilseeds will be made next spring, based on
figures laid down by the European Commission. The vast majority of
payments for cereals, protein crops and set-aside will be made over a
period of weeks beginning in mid-November.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
