<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hoechst profit nearly doubles</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830517</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GERMAN chemical giant Hoechst said yesterday that strong volume sales
and higher prices helped half-year pre-tax profit to nearly double to
DM2100m and forecast 1995 results will top 1994.
''For 1995 as a whole we expect clearly higher results than in the
previous year,'' Hoechst said in its interim report. A year ago, when
the industry began roaring out of recession, Hoechst posted a DM1360m
net profit.
First half group pre-tax profit, excluding all business from newly
acquired US drugs group Marion Merrell Dow, surged 96% and was an
improvement on 1989's record half-year result, Hoechst said. The return
on sales jumped to 8.1% from 4.4%.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Don &amp; Low in #8m expansion</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830518</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DON &amp; Low Nonwovens has announced an #8m investment to double the
production of non-woven fabrics at its Forfar factory.
The company produces a range of tough polypropelyne fabrics under the
Daltex trade name. These materials are used for a variety of purposes
such as protective clothing, roof underlay and covering horticultural
crops.
The new investment should create more than 20 jobs at the Forfar
factory, which currently employs 70 people.
Don &amp; Low is a wholly-owned subsidiary of Montell Polyolefins, a joint
venture between Shell and the Italian chemicals giant Montedison which
is based in the Netherlands.
It manufactures the Daltex range of materials by feeding polypropylene
granules into machinery that converts them into long fibres. These are
are then bonded into sheets by heated rollers.
Once the new machinery becomes fully operational next year the
company's turnover should rise to about #20m.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Murray VCT is launched</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830519</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MURRAY VCT yesterday became the first venture capital trust to be
launched under new legislation announced in last November's Budget.
The launch date of the #30m fund, the brainchild of Glasgow-based
investment trust management group Murray Johnstone, was brought forward
from September 12.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000055</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000055</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Amerada-Hess brings oil ashore</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830520</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AMERADA-HESS has begun commercial oil production from its Fife field
in the North Sea. Oil started flowing on Wednesday night and output is
expected to peak at more than 40,000 barrels per day within a few
months.
The Fife field, located 211 miles South-east of Aberdeen, is expected
to yield 34 million barrels over its planned seven-year life.
Instead of being piped ashore, the crude will be pumped into a tanker
moored permanently alongside the production platform. This has been
converted to serve as a Floating Production and Offloading Vessel.
US-based Amerada Hess is the third largest oil producer in the UK
after Shell and BP, with gross output of 300,000 barrels per day.
It has an 85% stake in the Fife field. Premier Oil of the UK holds the
remaining 15%.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000056</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000056</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>July retail prices drop but pressure builds in pipeline</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>R E DUNDAS, CHIEF FINANCIAL EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<FLAG>COMMENT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976830521</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FALL in the retail price index had been expected in July, the main
month for summer sales in the High Street. But prices fell by more than
had been expected, largely because of the large drop in seasonal food
prices, which knocked 0.2% off the RPI for the second month in a row.
All the main measures of inflation were unchanged, but the annual
rates were sharply higher than last summer. Headline inflation is now
3.5% against 2.3% in July last year. Over the same period, underlying
inflation has risen from 2.2% to 2.8%, taking it into the upper half of
the Government's target range of 1% to 4%.
A number of factors suggest that inflation will rise further between
now and the first half of next year, though it may taper off thereafter.
The recent sharp drop in seasonal food prices is likely to reverse
itself with the exceptionally hot weather threatening to restrict
supplies. Potato prices, which fell by almost half in July, are rising
again.
So yesterday's benign figures may have to be paid for later in the
year when prices will come under pressure from other factors, such as
higher prices at the factory gate and an easing of competitive
pressures.
Figures earlier in the week showed that the core rate of factory gate
price inflation, excluding the food, drink, tobacco, and petroleum
industries, was running at 5%, its highest rate for four years, and
substantially above the headline rate of inflation.
It takes time for factory gate price increases to feed through to the
High Street, but the expectation is that in the first half of next year
underlying inflation will be around 3.25% or higher. Some economists
fear that it could continue rising until it is above the 4% upper limit
of the target range, but at this stage they are in a minority.
Headline inflation could hit 4% within the next few months. As this is
the measure generally used in pay bargaining it could result in second
round inflationary effects through higher labour costs, which would
frustrate hopes that inflation would peak next year and then gradually
decline.
This is the Bank of England's big fear and explains the persistance of
the Governor, Eddie George, in pressing the Chancellor of the Exchequer,
Kenneth Clarke, to raise interest rates.
The argument has been going Mr Clarke's way, however. Yesterday's
unchanged inflation rates followed the first rise in seasonally adjusted
unemployment for 23 months. The partial recovery in sterling, sparked
off by the new-found strength of the dollar, has mitigated one of the
Bank of England's biggest concerns.
To some extent both inflation and unemployment data are lagging
indicators as they reflect economic events that have taken place. For
this reason the most significant figures this week were those for retail
sales.
For most of the period since last autumn retail sales have been
falling away gently, but have picked up smartly recently, with rises of
0.4% in both June and July. In the latest three months sales were 0.7%
higher than in the previous month.
Discounting in the summer sales and the warm weather, which has
boosted trade in clothing and footwear, have been positive factors, but
even after allowing for these influences it does seem that the consumer
is coming back to life.
The effects of the National Lottery, which ate into traditional areas
of retail spending, are beginning to be absorbed, and the tax increases
and higher interest rates, which have held back spending, will soon
become part of economic history.
Most independent economists envisage consumer spending picking up over
the next two years and the first signs of this may be in evidence.
Welcome as this will be to the sorely tried retail trade, it will have
the effect of reducing competitive pressures. More of the factory gate
price inflation in the pipeline will be passed on to the consumer as a
result.
The evidence of yesterday's inflation data was that discounting in the
summer sales was shallower than last year, except for clothing and
footwear, where there may have been a weather-related overhang of stocks
from the spring. Discounting of household and leisure goods were
noticeably less this summer than last.
Goods sector inflation picked up from 2.4% in June to 2.8%. Food price
inflation was a little easier, thanks to the sharp fall in seasonal
foods.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000057</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Inflation rate stays at 3.5%</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>R E DUNDAS, CHIEF FINANCIAL EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830522</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE retail price index fell by 0.5% to 149.1 (January 1987=100) last
month, the first time that it had dropped since July of last year. As a
result, the headline inflation rate was unchanged at 3.5%, a slightly
better outcome than the City had expected.
Underlying inflation, which excludes mortgage interest payments, was
also unchanged at 2.8%, as was the new RPIY rate at 2.3%. This measure
of inflation, favoured by the Bank of England, excludes indirect and
council taxes as well as mortgage payments.
Though benign, the figures had little impact on financial markets
where it is recognised that activity indicators and movements in
sterling are likely to be the main determinants of interest rate policy
in the short run.
The July figures benefited from a further sharp decline in seasonal
food prices, which fell by 6.6% after a drop of 7.7% in June. This had
the effect of reducing the RPI by 0.2% for the second month in a row.
Potato prices, which had risen sharply earlier in the year, fell by
the better part of 50% between June and July. Overall food prices fell
by 0.8%, but there was a slight increase in the price of non-seasonal
foods.
Housing costs dropped by 0.3% between June and July, mainly because of
the fall in house prices. Household service costs declined by 1.1% on
the back of lower charges for telephone calls.
The summer sales were a major factor in reducing the retail price
index. Clothing and footwear prices fell by 4.6%, their largest fall in
any July. Last year prices declined by 4.2%.
But overall discounting in the High Streets was shallower than last
year. Household goods prices fell by 1% against 1.7% last year.
Moreover, leisure goods dropped by just 0.2% compared with 1.4% last
year as prices of books and newspapers rose sharply in contrast to falls
last year when the price-cutting war was getting under way.
The main increases came in alcoholic drinks, fares, and travel costs,
leisure services, and personal goods and services.
Underlying inflation is currently in the upper half of the
Government's 1% to 4% target range and is expected to rise between now
and early next year before falling gradually.
According to the Bank of England, the Government will miss its target
of reducing inflation to 2.5% or less by the end of the current
Parliament in the spring of next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
