<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000059</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000059</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Independent in rate cut attack</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830524</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INDEPENDENT Insurance electrified the insurance sector yesterday with
its attack on the rate-cutting now taking place with scant regard to the
quality of risk or the source of the business.
Chief executive Michael Bright said it was his firm view this will
result in casualties in the market, so Independent is prepared to work
only with those brokers and clients looking for a consistent approach,
and who are prepared to take responsibility for controlling their risks.
He is speaking from a position of considerable strength, with the
Glasgow-registered company chaired by former Ivory &amp; Sime director Garth
Ramsay increasing half time profits by 58% to #16m.
Even if investment gains and losses are excluded, the underlying
improvement is 48% on a 53% rise in gross premium income at #201m.
Almost all the motor account business is non-standard, such as
insuring the Stagecoach and Greater Manchester Buses fleets, multi-axled
transporters and specialist cars where the rate is less important than
service and advice as far as the purchaser is concerned.
It also insures the Williams Formula One motor racing team for
everything apart from the track driving.
As for general car insurance, Independent reckons rates will fall
until this time next year, with the market confused by the emergence of
about 50 direct selling companies.
This contradicts what the industry majors are saying, although on
Tuesday the largest insurance broker Sedgwick was inclined to be on
Independent's side of the fence.
It acquired the UK business of Aegon last autumn, which brought in
valuable affinity group insurance such as static caravan business which
brings in a useful #15m of annual premium business.
Property insurance again is at the specialist end, although there was
a heartstopper earlier this week, but Government House in Bermuda was
unscathed by the hurricane.
Full year profits should increase by #10m to #33m. The interim
dividend has been raised 15% to 4.6p with 11p likely as a total for a
4.2% yield, with the shares at a new peak of 328p.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000060</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000060</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Beans for busts</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830525</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEUCHATEL: A Swiss company today confirmed it planned to introduce
breast implants made of soya bean oil. LipoMatrix said the implants are
less liklely to be rejected by the body's immune system, and also allow
the detection of breast cancer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SNP to seek inquiry into parks sale</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH, LOCAL GOVERNMENT CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830526</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Opposition SNP group on Falkirk District Council is to ask the
Accounts Commission to investigate the proposed sale of four
council-owned business parks by Labour-controlled Central Region.
Earlier this week, a judge at the Court of Session refused to grant
Labour-controlled Falkirk District Council and the new Falkirk Council
an interim interdict to stop the move to create a joint-venture company
with John Laing Property Ventures Ltd.
Under the deal, the region would own 50% of the new company and
councillors would be represented on a new joint-venture board.
SNP group leader Councillor David Alexander said the private company
concerned had been very closely associated with Central Regional Council
in the past, having done major projects such as the extension of the
Thistle Centre.
''It concerns us that it was the only company invited to participate.
We believe that may be in conflict with the principle of tendering and
if it is not outwith the letter of the law, it is certainly outwith the
spirit,'' he claimed.
The two councils had argued in court that the change of status for two
of the parks, in Falkirk and Larbert, could limit significantly the
freedom of the new unitary authority..
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000062</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000062</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Strategic groups put Fife above in-fighting</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH, LOCAL GOVERNMENT CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830527</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FIFE Council will have a management and decision-making structure
which its leaders believe is unique in Scottish local government.
A full meeting of the 92 members of the Labour-controlled council is
expected to approve the proposals in outline later today.
The structure is designed to end empire building and in-fighting
between different service departments. To achieve this, it puts them in
various strategic groups headed by corporate managers.
For example, social work, housing, education, and leisure and
recreation will be pulled together by a social strategy. The new
council's Labour leader Alex Rowley said they had taken their time to
draw up a new model and had consulted very widely because they were
determined the new council would not be a re-vamped version of the
regional council with the district services bolted on.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cummings moves in as bank's corporate guru</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN MCCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830528</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BANK of Scotland has replaced corporate finance guru John Berry, who
was poached by the Clydesdale Bank, from its own ranks.
Dumbarton-born Peter Cummings, 40, has moved from Carlisle to take up
the post of director of corporate banking (west) at Bank of Scotland's
Glasgow chief office.
He will head one of the bank's three structured finance teams. The
teams, established in 1990 in Glasgow, Edinburgh and London, allowed
Bank of Scotland to become the market leader in the provision of bank
debt for management buy-outs.
Mr Cummings, who joined Bank of Scotland in 1974, spent 10 years with
the UK banking corporate division in Glasgow, working on the larger
credits as well as management buy-outs and buy-ins.
He was also responsible for the bank's special duties department in
the West of Scotland, which involved him in major corporate
restructurings and receiverships, as well as substantial property
transactions.
Most recently, he was a regional manager in Carlisle, where his remit
included business development in Cumbria, with particular emphasis on
the medium and large enterprise sector.
Stewart Henderson, head of branch operations at Bank of Scotland's
Glasgow chief office, said: ''We are probably fortunate to have someone
as strong as Peter to replace John Berry.''
Mr Cummings said: ''It is indeed a privilege and a challenge to be
working with the structured finance team in Glasgow, who have earned
Bank of Scotland the reputation in the market for projecting a
pro-active, sensible and commercial approach to getting the deal done.''
During Mr Berry's time, the nine-strong structured finance team in
Glasgow participated in more than one deal a month. The average deal
size was about #3m.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Southern's share plan in hot water</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830529</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOUTHERN Water is risking the wrath of its drought-hit customers by
planning a share buy-back campaign, when they would undoubtedly want to
see the money spent on further improvements to their water and sewerage
systems.
Chairman William Courtney pointed out to shareholders at the annual
meeting that two-thirds of Southern's post-tax profits had been ploughed
back into the investment programme.
Through innovation and financial control the group had made savings in
investment spending which would produce a customer dividend of extra
works, such as reducing the risk of foul flooding of homes.
This would be balanced by the buy-back of up to 10% of the group's
shares to benefit shareholders.
Southern's decision follows a trend by other water companies.
Anglian Water bought 10% of its equity this week for #162m, and
Yorkshire and Severn Trent have obtained shareholder permission to do
so.
Southern shares gained 10p to 688p and the water sector as a whole
moved ahead.
But customers are likely to take a dim view of the proposed buy-back,
even though Southern's investment plan calls for the expenditure of
#1200m over the next five years.
Sussex has seen the driest summer since records began in 1727, and
Southern says demand for water has been three times the previous peak. A
hosepipe ban is in force.
Mr Courtney said current year trading had started well and he was
confident for the future.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000065</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000065</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tarmac director in housing move</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830530</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXECUTIVE director and chief operating officer of Tarmac John Lovering
is leaving the group to develop plans to buy its housing division.
Last month, the Wolverhampton-based minerals to construction group
disclosed plans to sell or float off the business as it no longer
regarded housing as a core division.
Tarmac yesterday expressed its appreciation of Mr Lovering, who joined
the group in 1993.
Chief executive Neville Simms said: ''John has helped me in the
re-alignment of the group and in improving its performance.
''Our decision to divest the housing division clearly offers the
opportunity of a fresh challenge for him to pursue, and we wish him
well.''
Mr Lovering said: ''I have thoroughly enjoyed my spell at Tarmac. I
came to help Neville Simms set a new strategic direction for the group
and to contribute to a real improvement in performance.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000066</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000066</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Data handed over</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830531</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BAGHDAD: Iraq handed over new information on its nuclear and germ
warfare activities yesterday, the UN envoy charged with disarming Iraq
under the 1991 Gulf War ceasefire said. However, Rolf Ekeus, fresh from
a high-level meeting with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz, said
he needed to assess the information before passing his judgment.
</TEXT>
