<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000071</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000071</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Slow trade forces holiday companies to reduce prices</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830536</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITISH holidaymakers will have to pay less to find a place in the sun
this winter.
Several top tour operators yesterday launched a price war by
drastically cutting the cost of overseas holidays.
The Thomson group admitted it is having to make the price reductions
to attract business.
But even with big discounts, holidaymakers are booking at the last
possible moment.
''While Thomson Tour Operations expects to achieve a modest increase
in bookings for the summer 1995 season as a whole, in a market which is
unlikely to show any growth, a higher-than-expected level of price
discounting in the market is proving necessary to achieve late sales,
resulting in significantly lower tour operating margins,'' said the
Canadian-based parent group Thomson Corporation.
The company said winter bookings had started well and were 7% higher
than those for the winter of 1994/95 at this time last year.
The group's travel agent Lunn Poly was faring well and Britannia
Airways was operating at near-maximum capacity.
Lunn Poly, Britain's largest travel agency, is offering a 10% discount
on anyone who registers for a 1996 summer holiday before brochures are
released on September 1.
For a #5 deposit, customers can tell the travel agent where they want
to go, when, for how long and whether they want a hotel or self
catering.
Then when the tour operators like Airtours and First Choice release
their brochures, Lunn Poly will fix a break according to those details.
AT Mays, the UK's third-largest travel agent, also pitched itself in
the summer 1996 price war yesterday with discounts of up to 10%.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Move provides a boost to the share price of Murdoch-owned broadcaster. Pearson to sell BSkyB stake</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830537</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PEARSON provided a boost to British Sky Broadcasting's share price
yesterday after it confirmed it is preparing to sell all its directly
owned shares in the satellite broadcaster. This represents 9.75% of the
equity and is worth #577m at last night's closing price of 345p.
The end result will be that the BSkyB shares will be included in the
FTSE-100 Index and be automatically bought by investment funds tracking
the index.
The publishing and entertainment group has brought its half-time
figures forward to this morning. Pearson's share price yesterday fell
11p to 622p in anticipation of a disappointing outcome.
BSKyB's own pre-tax profits for the full year jumped 67% to #155m on
turnover 41% ahead at #778m. While the impetus at present is coming from
rising subscriber income with another 686,000 signing up in the year to
June for a total of 4.16 million, the medium term will see increasing
benefits from new products such as digital satellite broadcasting and
joint ventures with other companies including cable operators.
Chief executive Sam Chisolm said he was looking at extending services
beyond entertainment into business areas such as banking.
He took a swipe at Channel 5 aspirants. ''I would be feeling a little
queasy at present. It will be a test of their bottle to pay a lot for
the franchise when we pay nothing.''
Because of past losses, BSkyB can accumulate well over #450m of
pre-tax profits before it need pay mainstream UK corporation tax -- not
bad for a foreign-owned company deriving almost all its income in
Britain.
Revenue per subscriber rose 20%, helped by last October's price
increase. Mr Chisolm would not comment on to whether there will be
another rise this autumn on the back of a hefty promotional push
including a plethora of sports programmes where Sky has acquired the
rights. These include rugby tours and Scottish football.
Programming costs jumped 42% to #328m although this is an area which
can provide a substantial amount of profit flexibility.
The churn rate or the proportion of subscribers dropping out has been
reduced to under 13% which compares with almost 40% for cable users.
Income was boosted by an overall 19% rise in advertising revenue with
second-half growth increasing by 23%. The quality of earnings is
underlined by subscriber income amounting to 75% of the total at #582m
and having made the investment in a dish, people are usually reluctant
to give up.
Cash generation is substantial and this has enabled the company to cut
debt by #120m to #780m in the last six months and, as well, it supports
the contention that BSkyB will have a high payout ratio to the benefit
of the parent company, Rupert Murdoch's News Corporation.
There is a first final dividend of 2.5p following last December's
flotation at 256p.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000073</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000073</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Carjack shooting</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830538</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NAIROBI: The wife of a British diplomat is stable in hospital after
being shot by gunmen trying to steal her four-wheel-drive vehicle. Mrs
Margaret Bagnall was attacked in the city's Karen district. Diplomats
said her 10-year-old daughter was also in the car but escaped injury.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000074</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000074</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots computer firms share #180m order</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830539</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH factories have won the lion's share of a massive BT order for
computer equipment worth up to #180m.
Compaq's Erskine factory near Glasgow will supply up to 30,000 DeskPro
desk-top personal computers and servers to BT over the next three years,
worth an estimated #60m.
IBM's Greenock factory picked up a #50m order for 25,000 Pentium
desk-top computers and 13,000 Thinkpad lap-tops.
Toshiba won a third order for 22,000 notebook computers worth more
than #30m. These will be supplied by its factory at Regensburg in
Germany.
Computacenter -- an information technology services company which
arranged the BT order -- said it was ''potentially the largest of its
kind in Europe''.
The deals with US-based Compaq and Japanese-owned Toshiba are the
largest contracts ever signed by these companies.
But the #110m of new orders for Compaq and IBM will not automatically
create more jobs at their Scottish factories.
''We have no plans to increase our head count as a direct result of
this order,'' a Compaq spokeswoman said.
She noted that the Erskine plant had already taken on 300 staff over
the last six months, boosting its total workforce to 1300. The factory
produces 80% of Compaq computers sold in Europe.
A spokesman for IBM's Greenock plant, which employs 3000 people, also
ruled out the automatic creation of new jobs as a result of the BT
order.
The Greenock factory is the main supplier of IBM computers to Europe,
Africa, and the Middle East. IBM is based in the United States.
BT launched a tender for desktop computer equipment to serve both
front office and back office functions in January, and eventually
ordered equipment from three different suppliers in order to serve a
variety of needs.
''No single manufacturer could supply the best product in technical
and value terms across the board,'' said Marina Hinchcliffe, the head of
BT's Desktop Project.
''We did not want to compromise our standards and therefore chose the
supplier we thought best for each of the different ranges,'' she added.
Computacenter said the overall BT contract was potentially worth #60m
per year over three years -- a total of #180m.
But the three equipment suppliers were more conservative, estimating
the total value of the deal at about #140m.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sun shines as #5m expansion creates jobs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN MCCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830540</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COMPUTER giant Sun Microsystems, which is gearing up to satisfy the
clamour for access to the Internet information superhighway, yesterday
announced its biggest-ever expansion in Scotland.
It is investing #5m in state-of-the-art technology for the manufacture
of printed circuit boards at its European headquarters at Linlithgow.
Sun is taking on another 150 employees at the plant -- the largest
single increase in staff since the California-based company came to
Scotland six years ago.
Linlithgow, Sun's sole supplier of the European and Japanese markets,
made nearly $3000m (#1952m) worth of products in the year to end-June.
It is responsible for about half of Sun's worldwide production.
The manufacture of Linlithgow's two main products, desk-top
work-stations and servers, will be boosted by advances in the production
of their component printed circuit boards.
Powerful ''gateway'' servers, which allow users to access the
information superhighway, are made at Linlithgow.
Sun's recruitment of engineers, materials specialists, and technicians
during the next few months will allow the plant to ramp up production to
meet increased demand. Linlithgow is also moving to seven-day working.
The group as a whole has produced more than half of the gateway
servers in use around the globe. Three-quarters of all Internet
applications rely on Sun technology.
Because of the Internet's nature, its rapid growth is almost
impossible to chart. However, according to one estimate, 27.5 million
people could send an e-mail message on the Internet at the end of last
year. By the spring, this figure was believed to be in excess of 32
million.
Sun employees generate more than one million messages each day on
their internal Net.
California-based chief executive Scott McNealy credited the Internet
and its associated technology with driving much of Sun's current
momentum.
Sun recently announced an 81% increase in annual net profits to $356m
(#232m), on turnover which was 26% higher at $5900m (#3838m). The
average revenue generated by each of Sun's 14,500 employees was more
than $400,000 (#260,230).
Bob Coe at Linlithgow, who is vice-president of European operations
and worldwide manufacturing, said: ''This is the kind of performance
which gives us confidence to keep investing in our future.''
The latest #5m technology upgrade will take total investment in the
Scottish plant to more than $75m (#49m).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000076</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000076</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gould 'attack' written by Howard's son.    Wrong by-line makes the news as paper gets its faxes crossed over anti-Blair article.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER, POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830541</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A VERY embarrassed newspaper yesterday admitted an article highly
critical of Mr Tony Blair's leadership, purporting to be by former
Shadow Cabinet member Bryan Gould, had in fact been written by the son
of the Tory Home Secretary.
The London Evening Standard offered profuse apologies and launched ''a
full-scale inquiry'' to discover how the mix-up of articles came about.
The apparent attack by Mr Gould was all the more wounding because it
coincided with expressions of discontent about the Blair leadership from
other parts of the Labour Party.
The article that appeared on Monday under Mr Gould's by-line was the
work of Mr Nick Howard, the 19-year-old son of Home Secretary Michael
Howard.
It appears his uncommissioned faxed article arrived in the offices of
the Standard before Mr Gould's office faxed over his commissioned
article and was taken to be it. So a fierce critique of Mr Blair's
leadership hit the streets under the wrong name.
Mr Nick Howard is waiting to go to Oxford University and has written
the occasional piece for the Standard about being young and living in
London.
Mr Stewart Steven, the Standard editor, offered a whole-hearted
apology to Mr Gould and said he wished to assure him and the Labour
Party that ''there was no malign intention''.
This first article had no name on it, according to Mr Steven. When the
genuine article arrived later it was never put into the system, as it
was apparently assumed that it was just a re-run of the earlier one.
Labour's deputy leader John Prescott suggested that Nick Howard
perpetuated the lie that his piece was Mr Gould's piece. However,
Conservative Central Office said the Howard family had gone off to
France on holiday before the article appeared and did not know about the
mix-up.
Mr Gould, back from New Zealand where he now lives, to speak at
various venues including the Labour party conference fringe, went on
radio and television to complain: ''There is not a single word that I
wrote.''
Mr Steven said it was a genuine mistake but ''during the flurry of
edition time with faxes flying in every direction there is always the
risk of this sort of thing happening''.
He added that the Nick Howard piece showed ''something of the
political maturity of his father''.
Labour leadership sources who have not had a great week, with
complaints about the Blair style of leadership emanating from various
quarters in the party, were jubilant and referred the media to the first
paragraph of Mr Gould's genune article: ''Tony Blair has had a brilliant
first year as Labour's leader. He looks like a racing certainty to take
Labour to their first General Election victory in over 20 years.''
However, later, he writes about ''a more serious underlying
dissatisfaction'', not so much with the leader as with his ''safety
first'' strategy and asks: ''How much reason would there be to celebrate
a Labour victory if it were won by abandoning anything recognisably
Labour and by pretending to be a sort of sanitised Tory Party?''
*The report on the attack on Tony Blair which appeared in Tuesday's
Herald was based on information supplied by the Press Association news
agency and was published by The Herald in good faith.
</TEXT>
