<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000077</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000077</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Johnson Cleaners take a fall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830542</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE drycleaning business remains slack and reorganisation costs have
again bit into Johnson Group Cleaners. The company is the largest
drycleaner in the UK and US and one of Britain's leaders in textile
rental.
Johnson, whose Scottish drycleaning outlets operate under the Pullars
banner, disappointed the market with half-year profits down from #8.23m
to #7.2m before tax after a #863,000 charge for reorganisation in the
US.
Interest charges also took their toll, rising from #473,000 to
#592.000. Aside from this, though, the drycleaning businesses, which
have been rejigged on both sides of the Atlantic, continue to be flat.
Textile rental, in contrast, is performing well but, overall, sales
rose only 1.9%. Operating profits ahead of costs and interest barely
crept ahead from #8.59m to #8.68m and then only with the help of
#463,000 from Stalbridge Linen Services, acquired in March 1995.
Chairman Tony Greer and his team are working to improve the return
from dry cleaning but said there is no sign of any ''feel good factor''
returning to the High Street. The interim dividend stays at 2.8p.
Johnson had hoped for better things but goals for the drycleaning
sector at home and in the US remain stubbornly unfulfilled. There was a
reasonable start in the UK in the early part of the year but, as was the
experience of many retailers, it proved to be a false dawn though UK
profits at the operating level did advance from #7.2m to #7.65m.
</TEXT>
