<DOCNO>GH950818-000081</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The mark-up</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830546</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I DECIDED to trade in my soon-to-be five-year-old car and a month ago
went to my local dealer from whom I had purchased and had my cars
serviced for the last 15 years.
Over a cup of coffee I wept with him as he described how his margins
had been cut over the last years.
As a ''loyal and valued customer'' he offered me top price of #5000 as
a trade-in. Out of curiosity I visited another two dealers who offered
#6300 and #6500 respectively.
Taking the latter, I subsequently collected my new car on August 1 and
noticed my previous car in his forecourt at #6995. No complaints about
this #495 mark-up, but at how much would my original dealer have priced
it?
Donald A Grant,
14 Tylney Road,
Oldhall, Paisley.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lib Dems' target</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830547</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STUART TROTTER'S article on the Labour Party's chances in the next
General Election contained references to the possibility of Lord James
Douglas-Hamilton losing his seat.
Two elections have been fought within the boundaries of the new West
Edinburgh parliamentary constituency in the past two years. On both
occasions all four parties fought every ward.
In the 1994 regional elections the Liberal Democrats polled 36%
compared to the Conservatives' 25% with Labour in third place on 20%.
This April, with the Labour Party at an all time high in the opinion
polls, the Liberal Democrats once again outpolled the Conservatives
while the Labour Party remained in third place.
From the glum look on Lord James's face at the count on April 6 there
was no doubt that he realised the threat in his seat was from the
Liberal Democrats who have been a close second at the last three General
Elections and now hold five of the council seats in the new West
Edinburgh compared to the Conservatives' two.
Labour Party claims that they can leapfrog the Liberal Democrats to
take the seat have been shown to be without substance in the past and
should have been dismissed in this analysis of possible gains under new
parliamentary boundaries.
John Barrett,
3 Traquair Park West,
Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000083</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000083</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Veterans drop call for Japan goods boycott</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830548</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORMER Far East prisoners of war yesterday called off an appeal to the
British public to boycott Japanese goods as they prepared for a sombre
weekend of commemorations to remember those who never came home.
The historic apology by Japanese Prime Minister Tomiichi Murayama this
week has given hope to the 16,000 survivors that a compromise on
compensation payments can be agreed.
The veterans called on Mr Murayama to set up a compensation fund so
that Japanese companies which benefited from Allied slave labour can
contribute.
In a letter to Mr Murayama, solicitor Martyn Day, representing the
Japanese Labour Camps Survivors' Association and the Association of
British Civilian Internees Far East Region, suggested that the Japanese
Government pay a large sum into the fund, which victims could claim
against.
''If you were to set up such a fund, there would be no question, in my
view, that the world community would see this as an appropriate
gesture,'' he said.
''With the events of the last few days, the PoWs and internees had
thought of encouraging a boycott of Japanese goods here in Britain to
try and press you into resolving the compensation issue.
''Having thought more about this, and having considered further the
strides you have taken to have your government and country come to terms
with its past, it has been decided that such a step would be
inappropriate.''
Meanwhile, Scotland's biggest commemoration of the end of the Second
World War 50 years ago takes place in Edinburgh on Sunday.
The Sunset Ceremony on the Esplanade of Edinburgh Castle will be the
climax of events north of the Border and will be attended by 9000
veterans.
Preparations for this and many other events in Scotland have been made
by a dedicated team at Army HQ Scotland at Craigiehall, South
Queensferry.
Major Selby Macduff-Duncan, projects officer, and his staff of six
have overseen participation from all three Services in 166 events
throughout Scotland to mark the anniversary of VJ Day.
One of the unit's biggest tasks has been issuing all the tickets for
the Sunset Ceremony. There has been a huge demand and there is a reserve
list.
Major Macduff-Duncan says it was not as simple as going to the theatre
and paying for a ticket. Veterans were asked to complete a form in which
they gave their former units.
The result is that veterans with a common bond will find themselves
with old comrades. Associations have been grouped together.
Typical of the problems the team is having to deal with are details of
medals. A wife cleaning her husband's medals called frantically because
she got the ribbons confused. Some medals have been lost and need to be
replaced; ribbons have become frayed and some veterans are struggling to
get into the uniforms they wore during the war.
A Tartan Jumbo airlift has been organised to take 373 veterans to
London on Saturday for the ceremonies there and bring them back to
Edinburgh that evening.
The Tartan Jumbo travellers will then attend the national service at
St Giles' Cathedral on Sunday afternoon and the Sunset Ceremony. Both
events on Sunday are to be attended by the Princess Royal and Commander
Tim Laurence.
More than 600 serving soldiers will take part in the musical
commemoration on the Esplanade and it will be followed by a fireworks
display.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Where the buck must stop in the rail sell-off</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRIAN WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830549</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I NOTICED the junior Transport Minister, Steven Norris, informing us
the other day that questions of rail safety are ''a matter for
Railtrack''. As a streetwise fellow, Mr Norris at least knows when he is
talking nonsense.
We are used to the Tories hiding behind quangoes and agencies which
they have created largely for that purpose. I object, for instance, to
writing to Michael Forsyth about a serious problem in Scotland's prisons
and getting the reply instead from a civil servant whose vested interest
is in defending the record of the service which he runs.
Similarly, complaints to Peter Lilley about the crassness of the Child
Support Agency -- and of which he is the single parent -- are replied to
by the chief executive of the agency itself. The idea of the Minister
initiating inquiries about the effects of his own policies is a thing of
the past. Nothing to do with us, guv, is the standard response.
But I draw the line at rail safety. No quango, agency or
pre-privatisation PLC can carry the can for the dreadful things that are
now going on in the railway industry. Even bungling Bob Horton, chairman
of Railtrack and disappointingly absent from our screens this week, is a
target scarcely worth shooting peas at.
Tory Ministers alone have fragmented the railways, with all the risks
to services and safety which that entails. And if, heaven forbid, the
chickens come home to roost before this madness is called off, then only
Tory Ministers will be held accountable. They are playing for high
stakes and it is too late for them to leave this table.
The leaked Railtrack documents which Henry MacLeish has been
publicising this week add up to an indictment which soothing words do
not begin to counter. The rhetorical question is whether we should give
credence to what alarmed railway managers are telling one another, as
opposed to what their bosses are now telling the public. Take your pick.
It is the language of these documents which is so startling. Senior
managers involved in safety are accustomed to speaking and writing in
measured tones. To find one asking his colleagues ''whether at some very
short time in the future they really want to stand in the dock following
a major disaster'' is extraordinary. A cri de coeur, I would say.
If I were Steve Norris (or Sir George Young or Brian Mawhinney), I
would listen to that cry rather than bluster or buck-pass. The dock will
be big enough for all of them.
Most of the problems which are identified in the documents were
foreseen and described in a seminal report by the Health and Safety
Executive on rail privatisation in 1993. It was this crucial issue, the
fragmentation of ownership and therefore responsibility, which deeply
concerned its authors.
Their conclusions were chilling: ''There can be no confidence that
risk will be effectively controlled right from the start and that
important matters do not fall between the safety arrangements of the
various parties. The consequences of failing to achieve adequate systems
of control will be seen in increased risk on the railway system and the
likelihood of an increase in the numbers, and possibly also the
severity, of accidents.''
A bigger man than John MacGregor might have been sufficiently alarmed
by that warning to reconsider the wisdom of creating a fragmented and
therefore inherently less safe network. But MacGregor saw the report as
a political irritation, accepted its 38 recommendations -- he could
hardly have done otherwise -- and claimed this as an exoneration of the
safety case for rail privatisation.
It was no such thing. The continuing truth is that these 38 measures,
and probably quite a few more, are required in order to make the new
fragmented railway as safe as the former integrated railway. Where is
the gain in that? Even then, accepting these crucial safeguards in the
House of Commons is a lot easier than implementing them on the ground.
The difficulties are compounded by the zeal to privatise just about
everything. So we find, in the case of the potentially disastrous
incident at Hitchin, that the maintenance project was not being managed
by railway personnel (as in the past) but by a company called Alistair
Graham Associates which none of the people I know in the railway
industry has hitherto heard of.
To railway professionals, details of the Hitchin report makes almost
unbelievable reading. ''The Project Manager does not have a full rule
book . . . His understanding of operational safety is in doubt (to say
the least)'' . . . There were three different versions of the times on
which the contractors would have possession of the track.
As every railway manager knows from his first day in the job, the
question of ''possession'' -- the formal taking over of the track by
contractors -- is fundamental to the running of a safe railway. Everyone
involved has to be absolutely clear about where and when it begins and
ends.
''The advice of the Solicitor has been sought,'' the report continues.
''His opinion is that although agency personnel are employed by their
agency, they are controlled and directed by Railtrack . . .
Consequently, the Solicitor is of the opinion that it is Railtrack's
duty to ensure that the personnel they use are totally competent . . .''
That, along with much else in these reports, should give potential
investors in Railtrack a good deal to think about. Less than nine months
before the Tories intend to sell off Railtrack lock, stock and
signal-box, one of their own managers is ''strongly suggesting that you
take immediate and professional safety advice from competent safety
professionals''. Very reassuring!
I also wonder how many incidents there have been that we don't know
about. One report states for instance: ''We have already had two very
serious incidents at Bow which, but for the final link in the chain,
could have been another Clapham. Recent incidents in Scotland, among
other places, add to the above list of near misses.''
Details please -- from Ministers, preferably, rather those in
Railtrack who are merely implementing the daft and dangerous dogma of
fragmentation for privatisation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>New heart warning for smokers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830550</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MIDDLE-AGED smokers are far more likely to suffer heart attacks than
had previously been thought, according to a major new report.
Five times as many smokers in their 30s and 40s suffer heart attacks
as non-smokers, it was claimed. Doctors had believed smokers in this age
group faced a three-fold greater risk.
The findings, published in the British Medical Journal, emerge from
the largest study of heart-attack survivors yet carried out in the UK.
More than 10,000 hospital patients who had suffered heart attacks were
questioned about their smoking habits.
Smokers in their 70s had twice as many heart attacks as non-smokers,
the study found, and heart attacks were three times as common among
smokers in their 50s.
However, there were five times as many smokers in their 30s and 40s
who had heart attacks as non-smokers, with the figure more than six
times at the lower end of the scale.
Smoking low-tar cigarettes did not diminish the risk of a heart
attack, the study found.
Dr Rory Collins of the British Heart Foundation, a senior research
fellow at Oxford University, said: ''The risk of a heart attack in a
young middle-aged smoker compared with a non-smoker is much greater than
we had previously thought.
''We are talking about a five-fold increase and, because the study
involved very large numbers, the estimate is a reliable one.
''It is particularly important in middle age. In terms of years of
life lost, smoking has an enormous effect.''
The research was conducted jointly by the British Heart Foundation,
the Imperial Cancer Research Fund, and the Medical Research Council.
Dr Collins, who helped organise the study, said an estimated 20,000
people under the age of 50 suffered heart attacks in Britain each year.
He warned that the figures for smokers suffering heart attacks in
future may be even more alarming.
''It could get even worse than this,'' said Dr Collins. ''In 20 years'
time, when we see the effects of smoking among the young today, the risk
factor could be even greater.''
He said it was now more important than ever to educate people about
the dangers of smoking, adding that he was in favour of raising tobacco
tax and banning tobacco adverts.
''The good news is that, if you give up, the risks drop away very
rapidly. In five years, you are some way back towards the risk level of
a non-smoker,'' he said.
Professor Richard Peto, of the Imperial Cancer Research Fund's unit at
Oxford, said: ''If you happen to survive your first heart attack, then
stopping smoking still makes you much less likely to have another.
Stopping before you have had a heart attack is even better.
''Overall, about half of all persistent cigarette smokers eventually
get killed by tobacco. But those who manage to stop smoking before they
have developed any serious disease avoid most of their risk of being
killed.''
The findings showed that between the ages of 30 and 39, heart attacks
were 6.3 times more common in smokers as in non-smokers. At ages 40-49,
the ratio was 4.7; at 50-59 it was 3.1; at 60-69 it was 2.5; and at
70-79 it was 1.9.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>In defence of the truth</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830551</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE public archives are secret, at least for 30 years, and even then
some documents remain unavailable. The arguments for such a policy are
often rehearsed but it is not just designed to cloak the state's
activities in secrecy (or frustrate historians): civil servants might
not be as free with their advice if it were soon to be open to public
scrutiny, something which might, for similar reasons, apply to private
volunteers. The 30-year rule did not apply before to the documents
concerning the Information Research Department, first established in
1948 by Clement Attlee, but many have now been released, though some are
still suppressed or suffer from deletions, so sensitive are their
contents.
What they show is how lively the post-war Labour Government and its
successors were to the challenge of Soviet propaganda and techniques of
infiltration of British institutions, notably our unions. The British
Communist Party itself was almost as spectral as Marx's famous
description in the Manifesto of 1848. It had fewer than 40,000 members
(a total swollen in the 1940s by respect for the achievements of the
Russian people against the Nazis) and won only two seats in Parliament
out of 21 contested in 1945. Yet, according to the findings of the IRD,
it controlled two of the largest unions in the country, the Engineers
and the Electricians, and was very strongly placed in the Transport
Workers, the miners, railwaymen and the main teachers' union. (The other
bodies' vulnerability to communist penetration was well known but that
the teachers were too is something of a surprise.)
The IRD sought to make such facts known, as well as the existence of
the enormous chain of Soviet slave labour camps -- the notorious Gulag
authoritatively and comprehensively exposed later by Solzhenitsyn. Its
efforts were aided by distinguished individuals like Stephen Spender,
Bertrand Russell, Vic Feather and particularly Denis Healey, whose own
left-wing credentials meant they could not easily be dismissed as
''lackeys of the capitalist class''. Many were still misled by communist
lies, now exposed beyond doubt by revelations from Russia itself. It is
good to know that they were well-countered at the time by the truth,
though not all ears chose to hear it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>America in Gulf build-up</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830552</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington
US forces have started building up in and around the Gulf after
unusual Iraqi military moves toward Kuwait.
A Pentagon official said: ''We cannot afford to delay action in
response to what we perceive to be challenges by Iraq.''
The official line was concern but not alarm at what was called a
pattern of unusual training and other movements. It began five weeks
ago.
The Pentagon said that the pattern was continuing and it involved
elements from all of Iraq's armed forces, including air force, army, and
elite Republican Guard units.
The US is moving pre-positioned equipment closer to the Gulf and
heightening readiness in case of a need to deploy quickly to counter any
''escalation of the challenges'' from Iraq.
Home-based troops who would be the vanguard of any sudden Gulf
deployment are being told to stay aware of developments.
''We're not putting forces on alert,'' a senior military official
said. He would not estimate how many personnel were involved.
The US already has about 20,000 troops in the Gulf region, including
2000 Marines on a training exercise with Jordanian troops near Jordan's
border with Iraq.
The Pentagon was said to be shifting closer to the Gulf shiploads of
equipment kept permanently afloat in the Indian Ocean.
The ships have enough tanks, ammunition and other equipment and
supplies to sustain a Marine Expeditionary Force of about 17,000 plus an
Army combat brigade of up to 5000 soldiers, the official said.
Kuwait said it knew of no unusual troop movements despite the US
reports.
''Until 20 minutes ago there was not anything unusual in the south of
Iraq,'' defence minister Sheikh Ahmad Hamoud al-Sabah said in brief
remarks to Reuters.
''The usual forces which are there were already there some time ago.
We have not seen anything (unusual).''
''We are keeping our eyes open but we have not seen anything. They
have not come (across the 32nd parallel),'' he added.
Kuwait's government shares American S. satellite and other
intelligence information on Iraq, according to diplomats.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000088</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000088</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Brazilian scientist offers to help fight Forth pollution</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LYNNE ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830553</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN eminent world environmental chemist has backed an Edinburgh group's
fears over industrial pollution in the Firth of Forth.
Ms Tania Tavares said after meeting Pilton Environment Group that she
was ''surprised'' to find such a problem in the city.
She also expressed fears about the apparent traces of cancer-causing
chemicals on the beach at Pilton, which the group blames on a local
chemical plant.
''This is quite unacceptable,'' she said.
Ms Tavares offered the support of her internationally recognised
Interdisciplinary Environmental Centre at the Federal University of
Bahia in eastern Brazil in the group's fight for action.
The centre is recognised as the first major source of independent
evaluations of industrial pollution risks.
The Brazilian scientist is on a three-day visit to Edinburgh as a
guest of the Scottish Education and Action for Development (SEAD) group.
She also plans to meet members of Friends of the Earth Scotland during
her stay.
Meanwhile, Friends of the Earth Scotland claimed yesterday to have
further evidence to prove a link between toxic pollution of the Firth of
Forth and a company at Western Harbour, Leith Docks, writes Christopher
Reekie.
The group said it had located several chemicals which could be related
directly to the activities of British Pipe Coaters Ltd.
By studying public records, they had found notes of the disposal of
substances including butoxylethanol, toluene, xylene, and naphthalene.
The records showed also that the company had no consent to discharge
any trade effluent into the waters.
In June, Friends of the Earth used canoes to obtain samples of an
outflow from a pipe at the works. Analysis showed the samples contained
toxic substances.
An investigation into the complaint by FoE Scotland was begun by Forth
River Purification Board.
Dr David Holloway, the board's chief pollution prevention officer,
said yesterday the investigation was continuing. The company had stopped
discharges from the pipe on July 10 when the matter was raised and they
had not been restarted.
No-one from the company was available for comment yesterday.
* Mr Alasdair Paton, currently director and chief engineer of the
Scottish Office's Engineering, Water, and Waste Directorate, yesterday
was named chief executive of the new agency which will regulate all key
forms of industrial pollution in the country from April next year.
The Scottish Environment Protection Agency, with an annual budget of
more than #22m and a workforce of around 600, will bring together the
functions of HM Industrial Pollution Inspectorate, river purification
authorities, and councils in respect of waste regulation and some air
pollution controls.
Mr Paton, will receive an annual salary of #70,000 with scope for a
performance related bonus of up to 10% of salary in the first year and
up to 15% for subsequent years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000089</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000089</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Briton 'serious' after Metro bomb injures 16</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830554</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Paris
A BOMB packed with nails and bolts injured 16 people, three seriously,
when it exploded today near the Arc de Triomphe, in an area crowded with
summer tourists.
A 60-year-old Briton was peppered with shrapnel. The unnamed woman was
said to be in a ''relatively serious'' condition in a Paris hospital.
Four children were among those injured by the bomb, packed with nails,
which rocked the heart of the French capital, a Foreign Ministry
spokesman said.
As well as the British woman four Hungarians, four Italians including
a four-year-old girl, and a German woman were caught by the vicious
blast.
Hospital sources said three of the 16 injured were seriously hurt, but
none was in a critical condition.
Police said the rush-hour blast appeared to have been caused by a
gas-canister bomb of the kind that killed seven people in a central
Paris metro station last month.
Today's device had been left in a rubbish bin just outside another
metro station at the corner of Charles de Gaulle Square and Friedland
Avenue, beside the Arc de Triomphe at the top of the Champs Elysees.
More than 100 police blocked off the area and red and white police
tape was put up to keep back crowds.
Four-inch-long nails were found scattered around the area as
ambulances rushed to the scene and doctors set up a field hospital in a
shop in a side street.
Dominique Kassongo said he was waiting for his children to come out of
the station when the explosion occurred.
''There was an enormous amount of smoke and people ran and screamed. I
panicked,'' he said.
Prime Minister Alain Juppe rushed to the scene, where blood was
spattered on the pavement.
He told reporters there were many foreign tourists in the area at the
time.
No-one immediately claimed responsibility for the attack, but police
suspect Algerian Muslim guerrillas of being behind last month's bombing
at the Saint-Michel underground station.
Two Iranian diplomats, held and questioned as witnesses, were later
released and police confirmed they had nothing to do with the bombing.
The Iranian embassy, located near the scene of the blast, denied any
involvement.
Controls have been stepped up in major French cities since the deadly
July 25 bomb explosion, with thousands of people stopped for identity
checks.
All rubbish bins situated on the Paris Metro have been sealed to
prevent more bombs being hidden.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000090</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000090</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pools winner denies making share promise</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830555</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A POOLS jackpot winner accused of turning on his friends and refusing
to pay their share of a #1.8m fortune told a court yesterday that he had
no gentleman's agreement with them.
Mr Paul Pitt, 28, denied he owed three former friends #25,000 each as
part of a deal to share the money if any of them won #1m or more.
Mr Martin Foulds, 27, Mr Graham Ware, 27, and Mr Andrew Sullivan, 30,
claim Mr Pitt still owes them their share after his Littlewoods payout
two years ago.
Mr Pitt told Portsmouth County Court yesterday: ''The only talk we
ever had about sharing money was in the syndicate. Nothing at any time
was said about splitting winnings on an individual coupon.
''
Mr Pitt said that his former workmates at the Pall Europe engineering
firm in Portsmouth, Hampshire, were either mistaken or lying when they
had told the court they knew about the agreement.
The three claimants, who are suing Mr Pitt for breach of contract,
claim that he won the #1.8m on a coupon which was covered by the
gentlemen's agreement they had all shaken hands on.
This meant any member of the group who won more than #1m would pay out
#25,000 to each of the other men.
The case continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Challenge of the mountains</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830556</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE unpalatable truth is that most of us spend our lives on our knees,
our horizons bounded by mortgages, the need to maintain a lifestyle or
the struggle to remain in employment. Urban life as the millenium
approaches has become, for most of us, a war of attrition. That is why
people like Alison Hargreaves attract us; they illuminate our own lives
with their raw courage, and their ability to break the pressing bounds
of convention. That, and her engaging personality, is why many people
this morning will feel an almost personal sense of bereavement if
reports of her death are confirmed. There is also immediately apparent
in the discussions following yesterday's breaking news a strong
undercurrent -- that Alison Hargreaves might have been better employed
at home looking after her children, that the world's toughest mountain
was no place for the mother of two vulnerable youngsters. That thinking
is, of course, flawed in that there is absolutely no difference between
Alison Hargreaves going to the high mountains and any of the tens of
thousands of men who climb and leave behind their families in the care
of their wives. Personal experience tells us that the men and women who
climb on the highest peaks are different and special and that these
mountains are special places. Many of us only reach the summits of the
high Alps by ski lift but that does not detract from the vaunting thrill
of such surreal beauty. And even at the level of the recreational skier
there is a considerable sense of achievement to be had from acquiring
and executing the techniques which bring exhilaration coupled with
safety. Each year tens of thousands of us expose our own children to the
attendant risks.
These are much the same for everyone from the humble hillwalker to the
tigers who can be seen every weekend in winter clinging like flies in
the snow gullies or on the ice walls of Glencoe. Much of the thrill
comes from practising a dangerous sport safely; even Ben Lomond can be a
nasty place in winter when the weather closes in and earlier this year a
man slipped to his death on Dumgoyne, the horn at the end of the Campsie
Fells, only yards off the main road. Safety was almost an obsession for
Alison Hargreaves. It was possible to detect from the way in which she
returned to the subject in interviews that she was concious of the
criticism levelled at her because of her two little sons back home. But,
of all people, she was acutely aware of the history of K2 and she was
fully attuned to the risks. If she perished, she died at the height of
her powers and instead of censure we should celebrate her memory. Her
achievements elevate all of us.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000092</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000092</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Vote of confidence</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830557</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE decisive outcome of the Bermudan referendum on independence will
seem quixotic to the world's anti-imperialists. By a huge margin --
easily surpassing a 40% rule similar to that affecting the famous
Scotland Act in 1979 -- the electors, nearly two thirds of whom are
black, voted to remain under British rule. It is a vote of confidence in
a very long-standing connection -- the 138 islands in the group were
originally acquired in the seventeenth century -- but the fact is that
the islanders for all practical purposes already govern themselves
through a very generous measure of home rule. Formal independence might
anyhow not really be on for a such a tiny population (just under 60,000)
and the alternative to the British link would probably be an American
one. Even the modest exotic element conferred by the British connection
helps the islands' tourist trade. Yesterday's vote was as much an
exercise in calculation as nostalgia and affection; though it is not to
be despised for that when hard-headed calculation has the habit of
surviving for longer than mere sentiment.
The islands enjoy the sort of off-shore status that makes for
financial havens around the globe. Their law is not lax, and it seems to
be firmly applied. Many companies find its attractions, and proximity to
America, appealing as well -- so that the islands have some claim to be
the fifth richest place in the world. But yesterday's three-to-one
majority for the status quo was composed of far more humble folk than
millionaires: at the very least an intriguing outcome.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000093</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000093</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Golf deal would not bring any benefit to town, claim hoteliers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830558</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A ROW over the recent signing of a #5m contract between St Andrews
Links Trust, which administers the town's golf courses, and a
London-based hospitality company, the Keith Prowse Agency, has taken
another twist.
The controversial deal, which involves the sale of starting times on
the Old Course, has raised objections from the tourist industry, local
hoteliers, and tour operators.
Now, after a meeting between senior officials of the St Andrews
Hotels' and Guesthouses' Association and representatives of the Keith
Prowse concern, the association's executive is recommending to its
membership not to participate in the scheme.
The organisation maintains that discussions with the company have
confirmed fears that the agency's executive packaged deals will contain
a substantial premium payable to the links' administrators -- plus the
company's own commercial profit.
The association, which has 35 members, considers that it does not wish
to be associated with the artificially inflated prices as a matter of
principle.
As a result, the association considers that it cannot endorse the
arrangement between the trust and the hospitality company, or recommend
participation in it by its membership.
The association's president, Mr Derrick Armitage, said yesterday: ''We
have already questioned the assertion by the trust that the deal will
benefit the town as a whole. We do not believe it will.''
He claimed that the deal had been aimed at the high-spending and
corporate management sector, which would have no incentive to spend
money in the town itself.
There are real fears from many sections of the golfing and tourist
trade that, as a result of the deal, St Andrews could be set to become
one of the most expensive places in the world to play golf -- a claim
already made in a golf magazine in the US after the announcement of the
deal.
Unconfirmed reports recently have highlighted costs of around #4000
for a deal with the agency, with a similar golfing package from local
operators at around one-quarter of that figure.
Hotelier Brian Hughes, who is the chairman of the golf group section
of the hotels and guesthouses association, said yesterday: ''The
corporate incentive packages will sell to companies and wealthy
individuals, who will pay an obscene amount of money for them.
''They will not be the normal golfing tourists and they will not use
local shops and restaurants.
''Instead, they will be chauffeur-driven to their hotels, play golf on
the Old Course, dine in the trust's new clubhouse, receive a free bundle
of goodies, and then leave St Andrews again.''
The golf administrators say that the 10-year deal will secure the
financial future of facilities at St Andrews into the next century.
The times purchased (amounting to several hundred and approximately 7%
of the starting times on the links' course) will all be taken from
existing visitor times. The trust has said that local times and the
traditional ballot will be unaffected by the new contract.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000094</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000094</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Vest research delayed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830559</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RESEARCH which could save police in Scotland from injury and death in
knife attacks has had to stop, it was revealed yesterday.
Lack of testing equipment is holding up the development of stab-proof
vests.
Scottish police forces are desperate to see production of protective
vests that are light and flexible enough to wear under uniforms.
Safety experts at Strathclyde University were confident that they were
well on the way to a breakthrough, but the project has been shelved.
''It's tragic that we've had to stop now,'' said Professor Tom Gray,
head of mechanical engineering, ''but it's just no longer economical for
us to continue without further funding.''
Since last November engineers have tested titanium, plastic and even
ceramic vests with the use of a ''knifing machine'' -- a contraption
simulating knife attacks in which a blade shoots into the vest at 30mph.
Further research is needed to make the vests ultra knife-proof. And
Professor Gray reckons that it could cost #100,000 just to get it off
the ground.
''The police weren't happy to see the vests going into operation
without passing some sort of test, but so far we've been unable to get a
proper standard,'' he said. ''Some pass the machine test but fail the
manual test, and vice-versa.''
In Strathclyde alone last year there were more than 3000 assaults --
many involving knives -- on police officers.
And in June last year Constable Lewis Fulton died from stab wounds in
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000095</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000095</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mensa admits three year old</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830560</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A GIRL of three has been admitted to Mensa, the exclusive club for the
brains of Britain.
Rhiannon Linington-Payne, from Farlow, Shropshire, was admitted after
undergoing special tests conducted by an independent psychologist.
She is said to have an IQ of 155 and a reading age of
seven-and-a-half.
Mensa could not confirm reports that she was its second youngest
member but revealed that her intelligence was in the top 1% for children
of her age. General manager Dave Chatten said about 2500 of the
organisation's 37,000 British members were under 16 and a few hundred
were under 10.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000096</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gloves come off in battle of the bands</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN MCGINTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830561</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Stephen McGinty writes that this weekend's pop chart figures will
decide if Blur or Oasis, who each released new singles last Monday, to
the surprise of the music industry, are the current champions of rock
IF IT was a fight, you would immediately assume it was fixed. But the
decision by pop bands Blur and Oasis to go head-to-head and each release
singles last Monday seems set to cause a real rammy. The Rolling Stones
and the Beatles were never so stupid. Mick Jagger would often meet John
Lennon to carve up calendar dates -- one for you, one for me -- knowing
that a fight was fine if you didn't have to climb into the ring.
It would seem that after only a year of good-natured, media-friendly
rivalry between Blur's middle-class boys from London and Oasis's
self-proclaimed working-class heroes of Manchester, the gloves have come
off.
Derogatory quotes will always secure column inches in the tabloid
press and papers like the New Musical Express, but a battle for singles
sales can produce only one winner, to be announced on Sunday's Radio 1
chart countdown.
Music industry analysts believe the battle resulted from the severing
of a rumoured gentleman's agreement between Andy Ross, who runs Blur's
Food Records, and Alan McGee, founder of the Creation label who signed
Oasis.
In the past the bands have avoided releasing singles at the same time
to prevent the hassle of a cluttered market. But it was the speed with
which Noel Gallagher of Oasis writes that ended the status quo.
Since January, Blur had scheduled a single for an August release as a
lead-up to their new album The Great Escape, due for release in October.
But as Oasis took only 18 days to record their latest album, Morning
Glory, also due for release in October, they decided to release the
single last Monday.
Both labels now claim it was a fluke, however Creation had to beat the
clock to deliver their properly-packaged single in time.
There is little doubt that with the failure to produce a climbdown by
either band, both record companies have made the most of a glorious
moment for the media.
Top slots in bulletins by ITN and BBC news, through to tabloid
coverage, Times leaders, and write-ups in the FT have followed this
battle of the bands.
Tommy Udo of New Musical Express said it was unintended hype that had
become a case of lads playing mine's bigger than yours. ''It's not
collusion as much as the breaking down of a consensus. Creation jumped
the gun and brought forward their release date by a week, and then Food
Records brought their's forward by a week and they decided to go
head-to-head.''
When Damon Albern, lead singer of Blur, heard the news he was quoted
as saying: ''It's that Manchester thing of 'come and have a go if you
think you're hard enough'.'' Obviously both bands feel rock hard.
In the blue corner Blur, who are classically trained, are armed with
four Brit awards and a recent number-one album. While Oasis, whose
songwriter Noel learned to play the guitar on probation after robbing a
shop during a glue-sniffing high, have one Brit award and a debut album
which was the fastest-seller ever in Britain, with current sales at more
than one million. The lucky horseshoe in their glove is Some Might Say,
their previous single which came in at No. 1, selling more than 250,000
copies.
Martin Talbot of Music Week said: ''It's not a hype because somebody
is going to lose. You would be daft to do this intentionally. It's going
to be a real blow for the loser. But the attitude of both bands is
bolshie, so neither one can be seen to pull out. In saying that, I have
never seen such coverage.''
Vanessa Cotton at Creation said: ''Whatever the outcome this week has
been great for singles.'' Singles are seldom successful money-spinners,
requiring the same promotion and artwork as an album with little
financial reward unless you're Wet Wet Wet or Take That. Today's bands
follow a prescribed pattern of releasing a single, followed by an album,
followed by singles lifted from the album. Oasis ignores this trend,
releasing new songs as singles every three months.
In 1994 the singles market had a retail sales value of #156.6m with 63
million singles produced, the biggest year since 1987. Singles sales in
1995 are expected to produce the most successful year in the past
decade. Singles now seem to be bucking the downward trend.
Between them Oasis and Blur have pressed about 600,000 of their
current two singles.
The recent shake-up in Radio One's play-list has been partly
responsible for the introduction of newer bands to listeners, who are
then more likely to purchase a single. In the past few months bands such
as Supergrass and Gene have achieved notable success with recent
singles. Statistics reveal that slightly more women than men buy
singles, and 42% of all singles are bought by those aged between 16 and
24.
Both Oasis and Blur have utilised databases, mailing information on
new singles to fans as encouragement to buy in the crucial first week.
It's thought that Oasis has the biggest database with more than 100,000
names and addresses but Blur's fan base extends further across the age
range.
A spokesman for Tower Records, Glasgow, said: ''On Monday morning
Oasis were outselling Blur four to one. Now it's evening up with Blur
nudging ahead. The whole thing can only be good for the industry.
Whoever thought it up is a genius. If the managers got together over a
beer, good luck to them.''
Of course, it will be Sunday at 7pm before Britain knows if it is Blur
or Oasis who are the champions of pop.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000097</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000097</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The First Years of Solitude, St Bride's Centre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976830562</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIS is storytelling for the eyes as well as the ears, with music and
movement helping to carry forward the narrative of a small pueblo and
the family at the heart of it.
The Brian Collective claim inspiration from the writings of Marquez,
Allende and Lorca and there is, certainly, a mystical whiff to their
account of a close -- even incestuous -- community destroyed by an
outside world which stamps its rule, roughshod, on their quiet lives.
There are some uneven patches in the performances, and the movement
doesn't always gel but the story itself has charm and humour as well as
an absorbing if sombre resonance, while the live guitar music with its
flamenco feel adds considerably to the atmosphere.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000098</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000098</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>It's a good result, home or away</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830563</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCULPTOR was reunited yesterday with a piece of his work he believed
he would never see again.
Valentin Znoba's #24,000 bronze statue, Football Supporters, was
stolen from an art gallery in Haddington, East Lothian, 14 months ago.
On Sunday, acting on information, police officers discovered it face
down and buried in grass in woodlands about a mile from the town.
Mr Znoba is mounting an exhibition of works during the Edinburgh
International Festival. Yesterday, he arrived from his home in the
Ukraine, accompanied by his wife Tatiana Golembievska, a painter, and
their son Nickola, 20, a student of sculpture.
They wanted to see the statue as soon as possible after touching down
in Scotland. They were ''overwhelmed'' to see the 26in bronze, which was
in good condition but ''a little bit scruffy''.
The work has three figures, two sitting on a bench and another
standing behind.
Mr Znoba, through Scots friends, paid tribute to Lothian and Borders
Police, as did Mrs Gill Bethell, the director of the Sands Gallery, from
where the statue was stolen. She had feared it might have been taken out
to the country to the Middle East or the United States.
Last year, there was a series of thefts involving statues in the
Lothians and police did not rule out the possibility that they were
''stolen to order'' raids.
After signing for the statue at Haddington police station, Mr Znoba
travelled with his family to Morningside in Edinburgh.
There they put the final touches to the exhibition in which Football
Supporters will now have pride of place. It is to move to London later.
The Ukrainian Ambassador, a friend of Mr Znoba, is expected to visit
the Edinburgh exhibition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000099</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000099</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Warning over move to switch tv event</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALLAN LAING, ENTERTAINMENTS WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830564</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE managing director of Scottish Television, Mr Gus Macdonald,
yesterday warned that any move to move the annual Edinburgh Television
Festival to Glasgow could lead to Scotland losing the event altogether.
Mr Macdonald, whose company is the major sponsor of the event, was
commenting amid suggestions that the organisers of the three-day
festival, which takes place next weekend, are considering pulling out of
the capital because of the soaring cost of hotel accommodation.
Glasgow, effectively the broadcasting industry's Scottish centre,
appears to be the favourite alternative and the city's tourism officials
have been actively courting the festival's administrators, offering
discounts and other incentives.
With some Edinburgh hotels currently charging premium rates of as much
as #160 a night and with many of the 1200 delegates on increasingly
tight budgets, the organisers will canvass those who attend and ask them
if they would prefer a change of venue or a change to a different time
of year.
However, Mr Macdonald, who is a senior member of the festival's
executive, urged caution. He said Edinburgh was the event's natural
home. It had started 20 years ago as a spin-off from the international
film festival and it always had been regarded as both an Edinburgh and a
Scottish event.
''I understand that the cost of accommodation has gone up and that it
is quite difficult to get,'' he said. ''But, on the other hand, the
festival belongs to Edinburgh and that has always been one of its great
attractions. I think it would be dangerous to move it away from the
city.
''If it went to Glasgow then it might be the beginning of a move which
would see it going to other cities outside Scotland.''
However, there remains a strong feeling that Edinburgh at festival
time is becoming too expensive. Full-time officials of the television
festival say this year in particular has proved to be, not only costly,
but particularly difficult to find sufficient rooms for delegates. This
is partly due to the fact that, with the official arts festival, the
Fringe, the book and the film festivals all experiencing record
attendances, the city can no longer cope with such a huge influx of
people.
Mr Tom Harvey, Television Festival director, admitted that there was a
very serious problem and that Glasgow was being considered as an
alternative.
''We battle to keep delegates' fees low so that younger programme
makers can come to the festival.''
Another option is to continue to hold it in Edinburgh but at a less
busy time of year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000100</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000100</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Russlan and Ludmila, Usher Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL TUMELTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976830565</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE were two supreme moments last night in the Kirov Opera's concert
performance of Glinka's opera, Russlan and Ludmila. One was the
overture, the only part of the piece that is well known today, where the
staggering virtuosity of the Kirov Orchestra -- with almost
indescribable articulation from their string section -- was utterly
breathtaking. And the other came just before the end, when the same
music returned, this time amplified by the robust, 80-strong Kirov Opera
Chorus at full belt.
That apart -- and this, given the ecstatic response of the capacity
house, will doubtless be a contentious statement -- the rest of Glinka's
opera never really measured up; basically it didn't amount even to the
sum of its parts, despite the committed and ceaselessly energetic
conducting of music director Valery Gergiev. Bluntly, it's not too
difficult to see why it has never become an established part of the
repertoire.
The story, about the quest of a knight to rescue his bride who has
been snatched by a couple of witches, is tosh. What opera isn't? That
wasn't the problem. The real problem lies within the composition, much
of which, from vocal writing to orchestration and including a couple of
sets of otherwise amiable dances, is pretty undistinguished.
It wasn't helped by some po-faced performances, from Alexander Morozov
as Russlan, cavernous-voiced, but wooden in delivery, and from an
anonymous-sounding Evgenia Tselovalnik as a faceless witch. In the
second act they were put in their place by the marvellous Georgi
Seleznev, who had a rollicking Russian-Rossini type number.
There were highlights too from the coloratura soprano Marina Shaguch
in the female title role, and especially from the gloriously
laser-voiced Galina Gorchakova as Gorislava. Again and again the eye and
ear were drawn to the orchestra, notably its cello section, which is
astounding.
But it was hard not to think that the real residency of the Kirov
Opera at the Edinburgh Festival begins tonight when the company moves on
to the stage of the Festival Theatre. What we could have done with,
instead of last night's Glinka, was a straight Usher Hall concert from
the fabulous Kirov Orchestra alone -- they have their repertoire with
them, and are performing it elsewhere in Britain. Ah well.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000101</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000101</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Football'sone-manfeelgoodfactor</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>PROFILE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830566</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
James Traynor talks to the hero of Wednesday's football international
against Greece, Ally McCoist, the Rangers ace who can transform a game
when he turns on the style and a smile
GROWN men from all walks of Scottish life rose with the thousands of
schoolchildren who were at Hampden the other evening to acclaim the same
hero. Businessmen, boxed in their hospitality suites, professional
people, office workers, and the unemployed joined forces and with one
voice chanted: ''Super Ally.''
There are times when Ally McCoist has to step back and catch his
breath. Sometimes he wonders how a plain, smart, but not uniquely
academic boy from East Kilbride could have scaled such heights of
achievement and made such an impact on the national psyche. Sometimes it
scares him that so many people rely on him every time he goes to work.
''It is almost like a power, but I have it and don't ask me how
because I'm not quite sure,'' he said. ''It is, though, a responsiblity
which can be heavy. Every time I play I know I have to do something to
please so many people.''
He is, after all, only a footballer, albeit one who happens to have a
penchant for scoring goals, and occasionally in the most dramatic style.
McCoist's fame and popularity are testimony to the country's almost
incomprehensible preoccupation with football, but also proof of his own
appeal. McCoist has been called the acceptable face of the people's
game, and his appeal is not confined to the male species, nor
significantly one set of supporters in a country divided by appalling
bigotries.
Perhaps in these harsh times when it isn't always easy to raise a
smile, McCoist can be seen as the feelgood factor. It can be one of his
off-the-cuff quotes which fly over the heads of many of his fellow
professionals, who converse through the cliches of the sporting arena,
or his unbridled enthusiasm.
Then again, maybe we are trying to analyse the McCoist phenomenon too
deeply. Perhaps his appeal is born out of a powerfully infectious
enthusiasm which can be transmitted in one of his floodlight-bright
grins, but whatever McCoist is about it is more than any of us think. It
could be something to do with the Scottish persecution complex which
makes us believe we are a downtrodden nation which one day will rise
again.
''I think patriotism has something to do with it,'' McCoist himself
will tell you, ''but maybe it is more basic. It could be that everyone
would love to score a goal at Hampden for Scotland and when I do it,
like the other night for instance, I was doing it for everyone in the
stands because we all want to see this country triumph.''
McCoist's re-emergence in the headlines after he had scored the
winning goal against Greece in a European Championship qualifying tie
marked the end of a frustrating spell of inactivity caused by a variety
of injuries which lasted more than two years. It was a long time without
the public's adulation, but his wife, Allison, knew he had scored even
though she hadn't heard.
She was asleep when he arrived home after the match -- it is perhaps
understandable that the partners of heroes become a shade blase after
time -- and over breakfast the following morning she asked: ''Did you
score? I think you must have because the phone has started ringing
again.''
McCoist says his wife has been a rock, a steadying influence
throughout his difficult times and she is about the only person allowed
to see the real man, the one behind the smile. Allison and their
seven-month-old son, Alexander, will be the ones who will have to live
with McCoist's next choices as he contemplates an existence off the
football pitch.
Money will not be a factor since he is not terribly far from being a
millionaire, although he would have been that twice over through
transfer deals had he wanted to move from Rangers. The resigning fees,
the pension plans of top footballers, and a testimonial year which
earned him approximately #300,000, mean he won't have to extend his
playing career beyond his sell-by date.
He may appear as something of an airhead -- joking with Dundee
United's Billy McKinlay minutes before he was given the nod to go on to
the pitch, he said that he would score and then, by way of celebration,
would jump the advertising boards and crawl from one end to the other
through the huge SFA tarpaulin behind the Greek goal -- but the
32-year-old is more than a joke.
Only one goal short of 300 competitive goals for Rangers, he wonders
when people will take him seriously. After all, no-one could be lucky
300 times and he asks when it will dawn on others that his work is all
about intelligent runs and sensing openings.
In the past few weeks, as he eased himself back into first-team
action, he has played 20 minutes against Steaua Buchrest and scored, 45
minutes against Sampdoria, scored again, and 20 minutes against Greece
-- and we know what he did during that time. These are top-class
football sides and skill is required to breach their defences.
McCoist has been bemusing defenders for the greater part of his life,
but all too soon it will come to an end. McCoist, the footballer will be
no more, and another function will have to be sought.
His wife planted the thought in his mind and the more he thinks about
it the more he wants to stop while still at the top, and his thoughts
already have turned to a second profession. Already he has a business
interest with Alan Ferguson, an influential figure in the PR world, and
the thought of becoming a sports agent appeals greatly.
There is no doubt he would attract footballers to his stable with
ease, but the developments in the world of rugby also interest him. He
could never become a football manager, the path many players attempt to
follow when they become too old to kick the ball, because he will always
be too much of a player.
He sees the game from their perspective; he always will, and contrary
to popular belief, he is the thinking man's player. Then he smiles
again, and you wonder.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000102</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000102</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Festival tickets are going like hot cakes</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LYNNE ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830567</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RECORD attendances are being predicted for Edinburgh's arts festivals
this year, amid the heatwave.
The International Festival, the Fringe, Film and Book Festivals have
already reported dramatic increases in ticket sales. Record ticket sales
have already been recorded at the book festival.
Figures for the first five days show some 22,000 visitors flocked to
the literary jamboree. A spokeswoman for the book festival said box
office sales were up by 35%, with many events already sold out, thanks
to the 40,000 tickets already sold.
Among the most popular attractions have been talks by Joan Lingard and
Trainspotting author Irvine Welsh. Children's activities, including a
Thomas the Tank Engine Tea Party and a storytelling session by Katie
Morag authoress Mairi Hedderwick, have also proved among the best
sellers.
The Drambuie Edinburgh Film Festival revealed there had been a 110%
increase on advance ticket sales, while 35% more tickets had been sold
since the festival was launched last weekend.
The International Festival and Fringe are also doing well, with an
increase of between nine and 10% on ticket sales.
The Fringe revealed it had passed the half-million mark on ticket
sales earlier this week. ''That was a couple of days earlier than last
year. The weather keeps bringing people in. Let's hope it continues,''
said a spokesman.
Meanwhile, Fringe organisers may have to consider a future no-smoking
policy on a number of venues, in the wake of an EC directive -- due to
come into operation next year -- which will ban smoking in all public
places.
The decision to issue a directive was taken amid concerns over the
dangers of passive smoking.
The Fringe, already at the centre of controversy over free cigarettes
being doled out by sponsors at one show, admitted the bulk of complaints
about venues tended to centre around the smoke-filled air.
Mr Stuart Buchanan, marketing manager of the Fringe, said: ''Most of
the complaints we receive are about mainly cabaret acts, which tend to
be in small, enclosed spaces.''
* Seventy extra cleansing staff have been recruited by Edinburgh
District Council to keep the streets of the city clean during the
summer.
The workers, who were taken on in April and will remain until next
month, are currently working flat out as a back-up to regular staff in
the battle to keep the capital tidy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000103</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000103</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Musica (The Fly), Richard Demarco European Art Foundation</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARK FISHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976830568</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OR The Midge, as it appears to have mutated into on its arrival in
Scotland from Belgrade. Not that the fly has anything but a passing
reference to do with this knockabout comedy by 16th century writer
Angelo Be Oclo Ruzzante, but it's that kind of a play.
Z Theatre is that rare thing, a company that looks like it knows how
to cope with commedia dell'arte in the 1990s. True, some of the jokes
are arch and -- distressingly -- the attempt at contemporary satire on
the war in the Balkans falls flat, but at its best, it is admirably
physical, and even the genitally-obsessed bawdy comedy gets good laughs.
A lively intermittent English translation keeps it spontaneous, and
vigorous performances keep it highly watchable elsewhere.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000104</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000104</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Premier resigns</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830569</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Hamilton
BERMUDA Premier Sir John Swan resigned today after residents voted
overwhelmingly to reject independence from Britain.
With 57% of Bermuda's 38,000 registered voters turning out, 73% voted
to keep their ties with Britain and 25% voted for independence.
Swan, who championed independence, had said he would step down if the
move was rejected in yesterday's referendum.
Deputy Premier John Irving Pearman, who is Minister of Labour and Home
Affairs, normally would step in for Swan, officials said.
However, a ministry official said Pearman also had pledged to resign
if Swan left office because of the vote.
Officials said an interim government would be established. Political
observers said C.V. ''Jim'' Woolridge, Minister of Tourism, was a
leading candidate to succeed Swan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000105</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000105</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Cheese Shop, Gilded Balloon</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976830570</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE'S a musty old aroma down the Cheese Shop: Essence de Student
Japery. It emanates from the Cheese Shop's six enthusiastic young
comedy-salesmen. They shout and run about a lot, making silly noises,
pulling faces, and singing songettes which advertise little beyond their
own cleverness.
Less-than-hilarious misunderstandings fail to enliven time-worn
sketches about police identity parades, police interrogation-rooms, and
western shoot-outs. You need understand only one thing about the Cheese
Shop's comedy-scent: it grates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000106</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000106</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The critical guide</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976830571</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
10.30am: Ten In A Bed, Theatre Workshop
* SNUGGLE up with Open Hand Theatre Company for some of the most
enchanting story-telling on the Fringe, with simple but striking
inversions of traditional fairy-tales. SV
11am: Panocha Quartet, Queen's Hall
* THE Festival's Dvorak theme takes hold this morning when the
Panochas play three of the string quartets, including the great
American, opus 96. MT
12.30pm: Joseph O'Connor, Book Festival Tent
* SHORTLISTED for the Whitbread Prize, O'Connor, one of several
exciting new Irish writers at the Festival, reads from his latest work.
AL
12.45am: Embarquez-les, Theatre Workshop
* THE petulant antics of these five female clowns, with their
precisely nuanced characterisations and subtle, silent slapstick, are
sure to delight. SV
3pm: The Pajama Game, Filmhouse 1.
* HEY, there, you with the stars in your eyes, its Donen time again.
This Adler and Ross show about trade unionism boasts a glorious score
and Doris Day in sparkling form as head of the pajama factory's
grievance committee. So come with me to Hernando's Hideaway. WR
3pm: Daughters or Blood's Muckier Than Water, Gilded Balloon
* NOT the most original of plot premises -- ghost of the deceased
eavesdropping at the wake but -- but crisp comedy, perceptive familial
observations and slick performances. SV
4.15pm: Enveloppes et Deballages, Theatre Workshop
* DISCOVER the child in you and thrill to the imaginative power of
this delightful piece by Velo Theatre; as a postman unwraps parcels and
discovers fantasy worlds. SV
6.30pm: The Legend of the Invisible City of Kitezh, Festival Theatre
* COLOURFUL fantasy in Rimsky-Korsakov's opera as the wondrous Kirov
Opera takes over the Festival Theatre for a residency. Four-hour show.
MT
7.30pm: Royal Liverpool Philharmonic Orchestra, Usher Hall
* SUPERB Dvorak programme from RLPO with their chief conductor Libor
Pesek. Includes the triptych of overtures Nature, Life,  and Love -- a
rare outing for them as a unit -- and the underestimated Sixth Symphony.
MT
7.30pm: I Was Looking at the Ceiling and then I Saw The Sky, Royal
Lyceum Theatre
* THE unique American genre of musical theatre is moved forward a step
in John Adams's amazing conception that takes in every aspect of musical
Americana over the decades, and weaves something quite new. (And the
band, Avanti, are absolutely astounding.) Penultimate chance to see it.
MT
7.30pm: Boys of the Lough, Queen's Hall
* THE veteran Shetland-Ireland- Northumberland folkmeisters have hit a
particularly strong seam lately which, with the addition of the
brilliant guitarist Chris Newman, makes their annual Fringe residency
far from a routine prospect. RA
7.30pm: Brian Patten, Don Paterson, Paul Durcan and Katherine
Pierpoint; Book Festival Tent
* ENGLISH, Scottish, and Irish voices get together in the Beck's
Spiegeltent for lovers of poetry, jazz, and German lager. AL
8pm: Look Back In Anger, Calton Centre
* AN innovative dance version by the highly accomplished Frantic
Theatre Company, who strut their stuff with sardonic style. SV
8.15pm: Carrington, MGM
* THE Bloomsbury set disport themselves in a variety of ways in this
account of the unconsummated affair between the homosexual writer,
Lytton Strachey (Jonathan Pryce giving a dazzling performance), and the
painter Dora Carrington (Emma Thompson). WR
8.15: Dolls, Festival Club
* PUPPETS, music and dance produce a taste of oriental ambiguity in
this Japanese tale of girls versus dolls. Beautiful, but odd. DN
8.30pm: Crack Up Canada, Gilded Balloon
* HOSTED by chirpy Phil Nichol, of Corky and the Juice Pigs, and
featuring slick sketch-dispensers Radio Free Vestibule and the
bear-like, gravel-voiced Mike Wilmot, a keen reporter from the front
line of the sex war. DB
10pm: His New Show, Gilded Balloon II
* PALLY Sarf Landan hard-boy-with-a-heart Kevin offers acerbic
thoughts on the 1950s  Ealing monochrome comedy into which this Tory
Government of ours has somehow mutated. When we all person the
revolutionary barricades, Kevin Day's the chap to have at our shoulders.
DB
11pm: Big Beat at La Belle Angele
* IF dance-floor jazz is your bag, then there are probably no better
proponents than the Thelonious DJs. A cool infusion of beat defusion. TD
11.30pm: Shaft at Adam House
* FLAIRING retro mania with disco-tastic (un)cool from the 70s and
80s. Nylon Paisley-patterned shirts not obligatory. TD
11.30pm: Mute Witness, Cameo 1.
* LOW-budget horror movie by writer-director Anthony Waller in which a
deaf mute girl is trapped in a Moscow film studio where the crew are
shooting a snuff movie after hours. Can she get help before they kill
her too? Laughter and terror. WR
12 midnight: Sir Bernard Chumley is Dead . . . and Friends!, Assembly
Rooms
* EVIDENTLY the son of a strange union between Harry Hill and John
Shuttleworth, Sir Bernard is a strangely-coiffed raconteur, man about
town, chuntering theatre-bore, porno-fan, and sufferer from Tourette's
Syndrome. Go and see him soon. DB
* Compiled by Michael Tumelty, Rob Adams, Thom Dibdin, David Belcher,
Alexander Linklater, William Russell, Sara Villiers and Danielle Nagler.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000107</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000107</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Envoy's second close call</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830572</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SPANISH Foreign Minister Javier Solana had his second close call in
Bosnia in two days when an airport was shelled minutes before he touched
down.
The UN said two shells landed within 500 metres of the airport at the
southern town of Mostar 15 minutes before Solana landed in a helicopter.
No-one was injured.
''The shells hit at 1400 (1200 GMT) and Mr Solana's helicopter landed
at 1415,'' said UN spokeswoman Major Myriam Souchaki in Sarajevo.
Mostar airport is within artillery range of Bosnian Muslim, Croat, and
separatist Serb forces.
On Wednesday, a vehicle carrying Solana, whose country is current
president of the European Union, was hit by small arms fire as it
entered Sarajevo and UN officials said Bosnian Serb forces appeared to
be responsible.
Solana was visiting Bosnia as part of a fresh international diplomatic
effort to broker a peace settlement.--Reuter
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000108</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000108</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Serb refugees turn on Hungarians</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830573</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Balkan conflict, and its consequences, spread alarmingly today
with a warning from Budapest that ethnic Hungarians in rump Yugoslavia
were being evicted from their homes by Serb refugees who had been forced
out of Croatia.
Hungary demanded that Belgrade act to stop the attacks.
''The government of Hungary calls on Yugoslavia to stop Hungarians
from being chased away from their homes, whether such actions are
spontaneous or organised,'' said a brief statement read by government
spokesman Elemer Kiss.
He warned of the damage to ''the relationship between our two
states''.
The United Nations reported earlier this week that the Serbs who had
fled Croatia after its army retook their homeland of Krajina were
forcing ethnic Croats in Yugoslavia from their homes.
The UN reported attacks throughout Vojvodina, the Serbian province
that has been home to Hungarian and Croatian minorities numbering nearly
half a million and about 200,000 respectively for a millenium. Rump
Yugoslavia is made up of Serbia and Montenegro.
The UN report said that the authorities were stopping some, but not
all, of the attacks against the Croats.
Budapest has been trying to keep out of the Balkan conflict since it
broke out in 1991.
However, Hungary recently stepped up its border guard forces along a
section of Croatia held by rebel Serbs because of increasing tensions
there.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000109</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000109</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>City plea over US consul</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH LOCAL GOVERNMENT CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830574</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COUNCIL leaders in Edinburgh are to appeal to the US government over
the proposed closure of the American consulate in the capital.
The district council agreed unanimously yesterday to write to Senator
Jesse Helms, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, to urge
a change of policy.
Congress is due to decide next month whether to close the consulate
and break a 200-year diplomatic link.
The reasons are said to be strictly financial and reflect the
rationalisation of US consulate services and the need to strengthen the
US presence in Central and Eastern Europe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000110</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000110</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>'No losers' claim over cash for gas staff</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830575</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Gas has claimed there will be no losers from a
multi-million-pound plan to hive off its computing services, saying both
customers and shareholders will reap the benefits.
Under the plan, 1500 British Gas computing staff will be offered
payments averaging nearly #20,000 each to do the same job, on the same
terms, for a new firm.
However, Labour Consumer Affairs spokesman Nigel Griffiths said Energy
Minister Tim Eggar must study the company's plans and it should not be
allowed to proceed until he was satisfied the customer would not foot
the bill.
''British Gas appears to have more money than sense and the money is
all the customers' money,'' he said.
''Plans to hive off key areas of work have come to grief in the past,
caused companies more work, and costs have been passed on to the
consumers.''
The 1500 staff -- who deal with all British Gas's computing needs,
including customer bills, from centres throughout the country -- have
until 5pm today to decide whether to accept the deal to transfer to
London-based computer services firm Hoskyns.
The spokesman said the move was part of a huge streamlining operation
which would see 25,000 jobs lost over three years and would benefit both
consumers and shareholders.
''It's bound to be a better deal for the consumer. It will be a good
service and it will be good in the long term for the people who transfer
to Hoskyns. There will be no losers in this,'' he said.
Staff who chose to stay with British Gas would be redeployed, he
added.
Some staff reportedly net pay-outs of up to #70,000 but a spokeswoman
for the public sector union Unison said the average would be less than
#20,000.
''It's a redundancy package and there are always risks attached to
redundancy packages,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wood shortage could close sawmill</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830576</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE last sawmill on the Isle of Arran is threatened with closure
because of the failure of the Forestry Commission to provide enough
timber to keep it in business.
Despite the fact that the island is almost one-third covered in trees,
sawmill owner Murray Boal has received just a fraction of the 400 tons
of timber for which he signed a contract in May.
The workforce at the Cladach sawmill, in the shadow of Brodick Castle,
has been cut from 10 to four, and financial advisers have said the doors
should be closed.
Mr Boal said: ''I can't believe it has come to this. I thought I was
dealing with an organisation that knew what it was doing, but now I have
my doubts.''
As well as the shortage which has seen customers waiting weeks for
orders of fencing and other wood supplies, and some looking to the
mainland for supplies, Mr Boal has seen costs rise due to the needs of
major customers like Caledonian Paper at Irvine for Sitka spruce to make
pulp.
He added: ''I could live with the high costs if I could just get my
hands on some timber. I have been offered wood which I have to go and
cut myself and transport it to the sawmill. But it is not of the
standard I need and with just the four of us it is time-consuming and
takes us away from the essential work of cutting and preparing the wood
for the customers.
''It will be a sad day if we have to shut up shop. There has been a
sawmill on this site for over 50 years.''
Mr Boal praised the efforts of local Forestry Commission workers to
help his business but added: ''It seems their hands are tied by the
people in offices far away from here who lay down the rules and
regulations. I have had less than 60 tons since signing the contract and
have been left scrambling around, sometimes getting timber which is only
good for firewood. I can't keep a business going selling bags of
firewood.
''I was even told at one point they would bring timber over from the
mainland to keep me going. With all the timber on Arran that's just
plain daft.''
After inquiries from The Herald the Forestry Commission stepped in to
offer Mr Boal an alternative supply of timber but by last night he had
been unable to view the areato see whether it met his needs.
He said: ''Things seem to be happening now after weeks and weeks but
until I can get a look at the area they are talking about I won't know
if we are any better off.''
A Forestry Commission spokesperson said that the contractor who had
been harvesting timber on Arran had pulled out unexpectedly and had
failed to complete the contract.
She added: ''We have already retendered the contract and hope to have
signed a new contractor by September 1. In the intervening weeks, to
ensure Mr Boal continues to get a supply of timber, we are arranging a
small standing sale of timber for him.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000112</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000112</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Minister hails Scots housebuilding rise</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830577</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEW housebuilding by the private sector this year has continued to
reflect the overall improvement shown in 1994, according to figures
released by the Scottish Office yesterday.
There were an estimated 4903 starts (the start of the construction of
a house) in the first quarter of 1995 -- a 22% increase on the
corresponding period last year.
Private sector completions (when a house is ready for occupation) also
showed an increase of 261 on the first quarter of 1994 to 4120.
Mr Raymond Robertson MP, the Minister for Housing at the Scottish
Office, said the increase in the number of starts indicated a growing
confidence in the Scottish housebuilding market.
Scotland was performing relatively well, compared to the rest of the
UK, he said.
However, the National House Building Council claimed the figures were
out of date and said the Government should do more to encourage people
to buy new homes.
NHBC records show there was a 10% reduction in starts and an 11% fall
in completions in the private sector in the first six months of 1995.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
