<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Two election reruns tell same story</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830581</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TORY who lost a one-vote election victory in the courts in June
swept to victory in the history-making rerun last night.
Frank Hodge, 70, took the Laurmont East seat at Polmont on the new
Falkirk unitary council with almost 200 more votes than Labour's Moira
Fitzpatrick.
The rerun was ordered after a sheriff court ruling that the first
result in April was void because of unfranked voting papers.
In that election, Mrs Fitzpatrick lost by one vote. Two of her voting
papers had not been stamped by polling station officials.
There were four recounts before the unfranked papers were discarded,
giving victory to Mr Hodge.
Mrs Fitzpatrick raised an action at Falkirk Sheriff Court, and Sheriff
Principal John Maguire made history by ordering a rerun. A similar
decision came 30 minutes later over the outcome of an election in
Jedburgh, and that too was resolved last night with the original victor
being returned.
The Laurmont East turnout of 1726, at 54.6%, was well up on the 40.9%
first time round.
Mr Hodge said: ''I'm immensely relieved that it's all over because
it's been a long slog since the last null and void election.''
Mrs Fitzpatrick, who attracted 100 more votes than April's 427, said
last night's defeat was a ''more acceptable way'' to lose.
She added: ''I don't regret the court action. This was the democratic
way to do it.''
The full result was: Frank Hodge (Tory) 721; Moira Fitzpatrick
(Labour) 527; Diane Williamson (SNP) 400; Jim Johnston (Independent) 46;
Ron McArthur (Lib Dem) 32.
The make-up of the new council which takes power next April is now
Labour 23, SNP 7, Independent 4, Tories 2.
In last night's rerun of the Borders council election, Mr Tom Dobson,
Independent, took the Southdean, Jedburgh, seat with a majority of 121
over Liberal Democrat Patricia Miller. It was her who succeeded in
having a sheriff declare the original result void.
Mr Dobson's majority in the original vote in April was also one.
A sheriff ordered the rerun because two ballot papers which would have
given Mrs Miller victory had not been franked by election officials and
were not counted.
The voting last night was: James Brown (SNP) 165; Thomas Dobson
(Independent) 339; Patricia Miller (Lib/Dem) 218; Thomas Tubb (Scottish
Conservative) 49.
Mr Tubb was the only candidate not involved in the original contest.
After the new result Mrs Miller said: ''I think it was worth having
another election. One good thing that has come out of it is that we have
got a good clear result this time.''
The new councillor said he felt that Mrs Miller's court action had
resulted in a ''pretty big backlash against her''.
He added: ''I feel it has been a great waste of time and money for
everybody.''
The percentage poll was 52.2%.
</TEXT>
