<HEADLINE>Tracing the life and climbs of a dedicated heroine</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KIRSTY SCOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>PROFILE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830582</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Alison Hargreaves was a family woman first and a climber second.
Kirsty Scott looks at the ups and downs of a committed climber
THERE are those who will never understand Alison Hargreaves, just as
there are others who have seen beyond the hype and the how-could-she and
glimpsed the spirit that has driven her to the risks and rewards waiting
on the roof of the world.
We generally like our heroines to be feisty Girl's Own types, strong
and resourceful, but with a subtle shading of vulnerability, a trace of
frailty. Alison Hargreaves was never going to fit that mould.
When she returned from her solo and oxygen-free ascent of Everest in
May, the climbing community was awestruck at the sheer willpower and
mental and physical strength that had propelled her to the top. ''This
climb was truly world-class,'' said one colleague. ''It was not just
good for a Brit, or a woman, it was genuinely world-class stuff.''
Born in Belper in Derbyshire 33 years ago, Alison made her first
acquaintance with the mountains when her counterparts were toying with
hop-scotch or skipping.
''I have been a mountaineer since I was knee-high to a grasshopper,''
she said in a recent radio interview. ''My parents used to take me
hillwalking when I was six or seven years old. . . I got the love of
climbing to the top and standing on top looking around and thinking,
wow, I have achieved something.''
She graduated on to Peak District rock faces in her early teens and it
was here, says her husband, Jim Ballard, that she was hooked and her
Everest ambition born. ''When you see her going on a mountain, she
changes,'' he said. ''She is what used to be called a child of nature.
She looks as though she has always been at one there.''
She became Britain's only professional woman climber, making her
living from sponsorship, articles, lectures, and a book -- A Hard Day's
Summer.
Everest may have brought her untold riches but a couple of years ago,
she was so strapped for cash that she had to think twice about buying a
bottle of shampoo to wash her hair after scaling the Matterhorn.
It was in the Alps that she started to show the dedication and genius
which would take her to the top of Everest. Six years ago she scaled the
north face of the Eiger while six months pregnant with her son, Tom, and
she became the first person to climb the six classic north faces of the
Alps -- the Eiger, Matterhorn, Grandes Jorasses, Dru, Badille, and Cima
Grande -- in 1993 solo and in one summer. She also climbed the Croz Spur
in the French Alps alone and unroped.
She had made one previous, unsuccessful attempt on Everest last year.
Going in from the Nepal side of the mountain, she got within 1500ft of
the summit before blizzards drove her down. But it was her dream and she
wanted it badly.
Her second attempt was blessed by relatively good weather and on May
13, in brilliant sunshine, she reached the top.
She said later: ''I just felt this overwhelming surge of emotion and
burst into tears.'' She stayed for 45 minutes and left a silk flower in
memory of those who had gone before and not survived the attempt.
Calling base camp she sent a message to the family: ''To Tom and Kate,
my two children. I am on top of the world and I love them dearly.''
Back in Spean Bridge, where the locals know her as the Spiderwoman,
husband Jim said she was ''as near to a genius as one can be,'' and it
is acknowledged that she could be the greatest climber ever, regardless
of gender.
Amongst her colleagues she is known for her supreme technical skill,
her guts, her fitness -- both mental and physical -- and her
determination not to take unnecessary risks.
In the wider public she was known as a mum of two who had climbed the
world's highest mountain, and that is probably how she would have wanted
to be seen. She has always been unequivocally clear about her commitment
to Tom, six, and Katie, four, and has patiently explained her family
ties to those who had poked and prodded about her climbing and its
compatibility with being a mother. On the day that Tom was born, she and
Jim had been bouldering near their home when she calmly informed him
that her waters had broken.
''Climbing is part of my life, obviously a very important part of my
life, but I'm not absolutely totally obsessed with it,'' she said
recently. ''At the end of the day my children are the most important
thing to me, so probably you could say that I am obsessed with them.''
She was well aware of the risks that were facing her on K2. ''It's got
this incredible aura about it, K2 the Killer Mountain people call it,
and it has taken a lot of lives, but so has Everest.
''I am just praying for the weather to be all right as I prepare for
my actual bid for the summit. I had luck with me on Everest but the law
of averages says that I should not get such a good break on K2.''
Yesterday, Jim quoted her favourite proverb in a tribute to his wife:
It is better to have lived for one day as a tiger than one thousand
years as a sheep.
Whatever the outcome over the next few days, and whatever the
prejudices and preconceptions that some amongst us hold, the least
anyone can do now is pay similar tribute to a true heroine; a dazzling
and dedicated climber, a warm and engaging personality and a loving and
much-loved partner and parent.
</TEXT>
