<HEADLINE>'Mugging out of Disneyland' for tourist from US</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830583</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN American visiting Stirling was robbed of 20p by a man wielding a
crowbar, a court heard yesterday.
Mr Martin Spizman, 33, who had arrived in the town only hours earlier,
was heading for a youth hostel on Wednesday when he was approached by
Robert McDougall, 25, who was swaying about and bleeding from a head
wound. McDougall said: ''Give me 20p or I'll kill you.''
Mr Spizman, who works in electronics in California, said last night:
''I've lived all my life in LA and never been attacked or mugged and
I've been all over Europe and this is the first time anything has
happened to me.
''But it was a mugging out of Disneyland -- when somebody approaches
you covered in blood and waving a crowbar and demands 20p, what do you
do? I had to ask him twice because I thought I'd misheard.''
The attack happened less than half a mile from Stirling Castle where
guests will assemble after the European premier of Mel Gibson's film,
Braveheart, in a fortnight's time.
Stirling Sheriff Court heard yesterday that although the street was
crowded and it was the middle of the afternoon, no-one went to Mr
Spizman's aid. However, one driver did stop to suggest that Mr Spizman
should phone the police.
McDougall, of Bruce Street, Stirling, was arrested a short distance
from the scene, still swinging the crowbar.
He admitted menacing Mr Spizman with the crowbar and robbing him.
He also pled guilty to shouting, swearing, and being disorderly on the
way to Stirling Police Station after being apprehended.
Sheriff Robert Younger refused bail and remanded McDougall in custody
to be seen by a psychiatrist. Sentence was deferred until September 7.
Defence agent Alisdair Mackie said McDougall had got locked out of his
flat after consuming ''a huge quantity of drink''. He had been using the
crowbar to try to get back in and when he could not he decided to make a
phone call. He had approached Mr Spizman for money for the telephone.
</TEXT>
