<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000121</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000121</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tribute to wife: It is better to have lived one day as a tiger than a thousand years as a sheep.Children told: Be good for daddy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS, HIGHLAND CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830586</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A family waits in hope for the return of a loved one. David Ross,
Highland Correspondent, reports on a day of extraordinary courage at
Aonach Mor
ALISON HARGREAVES wrote a touching letter to her husband, Mr Jim
Ballard, and their children soon after arriving at K2 at the end of
June.
In it, she urged six-year-old Tom and his four-year-old sister, Katie,
to ''be good for Daddy, have a lovely summer and enjoy your holiday''.
The letter, sent from base camp on K2 more than six weeks ago,
includes a simple line drawing of the fearsome peak.
Alison writes: ''Jim, how's things? We arrived at base camp yesterday
-- after five days bad weather. Now is perfect -- but metres of fresh
snow.
''Hope you and the children are well and that you all enjoy a great
summer. We'll keep you as updated as possible.
''Could you please encourage Tom to read below:
''Tom and Katie,
''We have arrived at our Base Camp. The trek was difficult -- it
snowed every day. The mountain I have come to climb is called K2, it
looks like this.''
The letter ends: ''Be good for Daddy, have a lovely summer and enjoy
your holiday. With lots and lots of love from Mum.''
Later, during her climb, she sent further letters, faxes and sketches
to her family.
At Aonach Mor yesterday, as tourists ascended the mountain on Nevis
Range's gondola, Mr Ballard, 49, a public relations consultant, emerged
from the gondola station every two hours or so to tell the waiting media
that there was still no confirmation that his wife was dead.
With extraordinary courage and forbearance, he allowed the world into
his family's confused tragedy, as he prepared to tell his young children
that their mother might not be returning.
Throughout, he tried to talk in the present tense, but every so often
it slipped. The respect he held for his wife and her achievements never
did.
''She had climbed the mountain. She was the first woman to climb
Everest and K2 without supplementary oxygen, and in classic style. She
was on her way down, so at least inside she would have had the happiness
of having reached the summit.''
He bridled only at the suggestion that perhaps his wife should not
have been climbing dangerous mountains when she was the mother of such
young children.
''Nobody told the athletes at Gothenburg that they shouldn't run
because they were mothers and might hurt themselves. Nobody says to men
that they shouldn't climb because they are fathers.''
His news conferences were conducted just yards from where he had said
goodbye to Alison just a few weeks earlier. ''I said, have a good time,
lass, and keep in touch if you can. See you when you come out.''
When asked how he might remember his wife, he said: ''If I had to keep
one mental picture of her, it would be her stood on the summit of
Everest dedicating her unbelievably successful climb to her children.
''If one has to have an epitaph, it is the finest one can have; to
have climbed the highest mountain on earth in the most simple and
perfect style, no artificial oxygen, no help.''
The staff of Nevis Range were with him all day yesterday as some had
been throughout the previous night, good friends of the couple,
beavering away all day in the background trying to get hard information,
sad in their work.
All the time, a helicopter was working outside delivering pylons up
the mountain for a new ski-lift.
The sounds of a helicopter are common, but they normally mean that a
climber is missing on Ben Nevis, and one onlooker observed: ''How often
have we written off climbers lost for three days up there for them to be
found safe and well days later? It could happen again.''
</TEXT>
