<HEADLINE>Lawless Rothesay</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830587</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
D J MacLeod poses the question as to whether local authorities have
powers to prevent cyclists cycling on the pavement (Aug 10).
The answer is probably No but the police do. According to the Highway
Code it is an offence to do so under the Roads (Scotland) Act, 1984.
In Rothesay there is more cycling done on pavements than on the road.
As a beat policeman is such a rare sight it is not surprising. I think
the local inspector must be known only to his colleagues.
The same applies to the litter and dog-fouling laws.
A Robertson,
42 Argyle Street,
Rothesay.
</TEXT>
