<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fears for stranded Muslims</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830588</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) said today that
Croatia had brought in buses to an area near 30,000 stranded Muslim
refugees and feared they would forcibly repatriate them to Bosnia.
The agency also called on Croatian authorities to allow trucks
carrying clean drinking water to reach the refugees near Vojnic, close
to the Bosnian border.
Earlier, the United Nations accused Croatia of barring access to the
refugees, followers of rebel Bosnian Moslem leader Fikret Abdic who fled
from the Bihac pocket into Croatia this month when Bosnian troops struck
at his forces.
Croatian police also turned back a UN medical convoy bound for the
refugees, saying the area was threatened by diehard Serb rebels who took
to the hills during Croatia's reconquest of the breakaway Krajina region
this month.
''The Croatian authorities are severely restricting our access to them
at a time when the situation among these displaced people is
deteriorating considerably,'' UN spokesman Chris Gunness said.
Gunness said disease was breaking out among the refugees, with 500
cases of diarrhoea so far. Many people were camped in the open.--Reuter
</TEXT>
