<DOCNO>GH950818-000124</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000124</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Army doubles its force and makes ready bomb shelters around Dubrovnik. Croatia prepares for new offensive. Milosevic meets US peace envoy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830589</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CROATIA doubled its military strength and readied bomb shelters around
the Adriatic port of Dubrovnik today in preparation for a possible
confrontation against rebel Serbs in nearby hills.
The Croatian army has moved in 2000 more troops to the area since
Wednesday morning, bringing the total number of soldiers to 4000, a
United Nations spokesman said.
The UN believed an offensive could begin within days, spokesman Chris
Gunness said.
While war loomed over the historic city, pounded by Serb gunners in
1991, a senior United States envoy met Serbian President Slobodan
Milosevic and appeared to have won his support for an American plan to
end the war in former Yugoslavia.
After five hours of talks with US Assistant Secretary of State Richard
Holbrooke, Milosevic praised Washington's efforts.
''We could see from the talks that the government of the United States
wishes to help in this as much as possible to achieve urgent peace and
stability in the Balkans,'' Milosevic told reporters in Belgrade.
Milosevic, often blamed by the West for fueling the ethnic wars which
erupted when Yugoslavia broke up in 1991, said that the two men had
agreed on the ''dire urgency'' of ending conflict in Bosnia and Croatia.
Holbrooke, who planned to resume discussions with Milosevic this
morning, described his talks as ''extremely useful''.
He was due to travel to the Bosnian capital Sarajevo to meet President
Alija Izetbegovic.
He has already met Croatian President Franjo Tudjman and Bosnian
Foreign Minister Muhamed Sacirbey.
Western politicians are keen that Milosevic help negotiate a
settlement to the war while his government is under increasing strain
from the thousands of refugees flocking into Serbia after fleeing from
Krajina in Croatia.
Milosevic has made it clear that his priority is to get United Nations
economic sanctions on his country lifted, and he has advised Bosnian
Serb separatists to cut a deal.
As US envoys toured former Yugoslavia in a round of shuttle diplomacy,
the Croatian army was concentrating its troops and armour around
Dubrovnik for a possible assault to push Bosnian Serb artillery out of
range of the walled town.
''We are increasingly concerned about a Croatian offensive,'' Gunness
said.
Workmen boarded up artefacts in the seaside town and local radio
advised residents to stay close to bomb shelters in case fighting
erupted.
Dubrovnik was pounded by Serb gunners in a 1991 siege during Croatia's
war for independence from Serbian-led federal Yugoslavia.
Bosnian Serb shelling over the past few days set off brush fires
around Dubrovnik, just three miles from the historic old town.
Firefighters managed to put out the blaze on Thursday afternoon and
shelling had subsided.
The old town has not been directly targeted recently but its
hinterland, including the airport, has been shelled this month from
Serb-held Trebinje in Bosnia, nine miles inland.
Diplomats say Croatia, confident after seizing the Krajina from rebel
Serbs two weeks ago, appears poised to fight to secure Dubrovnik -- the
last segment of coastline still under threat from Serb guns.
In Sarajevo, senior Bosnian government officials refused to meet
European Union peace envoy Carl Bildt on Thursday, saying the peace
process he represented was dead.
Neighbouring Croatia has also said it will have no more dealings with
Bildt after the former Swedish premier criticised Zagreb for shelling
civilian targets.
Bildt arrived in Belgrade and met Milosevic on Thursday evening.
Meanwhile, a power struggle between the military and civilian leaders
of Bosnia's separatist Serbs appears to be coming to a head.
The rivalry, centred on political leader Radovan Karadzic and army
commander General Ratko Mladic, is certain to have an effect the new
regional peace initiative being pushed by the US.
The Bosnian Serb army, in a statement from its general staff today,
accused Karadzic of deception.
It said he was intent on demoting Mladic, a popular hero in the
Bosnian Serb ''republic'', but was trying to buy time so that widespread
opposition to the move would die down.
Karadzic reshuffled the BSA command two weeks ago, shunting Mladic to
a dead-end post. BSA generals rejected the move and Mladic refused to
go, forcing Karadzic into embarrassed retreat.
The general staff statement said Karadzic had backed down for now only
because ''he does not have support in the basic levers of our society -
the people and the army.''
The root of the problem is Karadzic's mistrust of Mladic and his close
ties to Karadzic's arch-foe Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic.
Milosevic has trying to oust Karadzic for the past year. He broke with
Karadzic after he repeatedly rejected an international peace plan for
Bosnia.
The latest warning by the generals suggested that the matter may be
brought to a head by negotations over the American peace plan.
</TEXT>
