<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Don't blame the Buckfast</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830590</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHOULD ''Buckfast be in the dock'' (August 17)? This dreadful case
provides an extreme example of mistaken -- and frequent -- assertions
about the power of alcohol to remove choice in relation to personal
behaviour. Buckfast is only one of many essentially similar alcoholic
drinks.
A more important issue is that the public interest is not well served
by claims that alcohol is a direct cause of violence. Such claims simply
perpetuate widely held myths that people are less capable if
intoxicated.
The balance of evidence demonstrates that (some) people are aggressive
when intoxicated because of the social influences that have shaped their
behavioural repertoire, their personal beliefs about alcohol, and their
personal beliefs about how they should behave -- not simply because
alcohol controls behaviour.
There is a pressing need to reinforce the message, wherever and
whenever possible, that people are responsible for their actions when
intoxicated. The more people believe that alcohol can be blamed for
their actions the more likely that reprehensible behaviour will occur.
Niall Coggans,
Senior Lecturer,
Department of Pharmaceutical Sciences,
University of Strathclyde,
204 George Street, Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The benefits of immigration</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830591</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Rev James Small is guilty of using misleading statistics to try to
make a point (August 15).
He says that the real drop in Scotland's population from 1981 to 1991
is 15.7%. He does this by excluding 12.4% of the 1991 population who
were born outwith Scotland.
What he does not seem to have done is subtracted a similar figure from
his 1981 population figure to provide a correct comparison. His
speculation that follows about what Scotland's population might have
been is therefore invalid.
I find it amazing that Mr Small wishes to exclude from his figures the
612,397 people who were born outwith Scotland but have chosen to make
Scotland their home. Not only is it somewhat insulting, it demeans the
positive benefit that immigration has brought to Scotland, whether it be
internal movements of people within the UK or people coming to Scotland
from overseas.
Scotland now has a lower unemployment rate than the UK average for the
first time in many years and exports more per head than Japan. For a
country that has about 9% of the UK's population, it manages about 25%
of the UK's pension funds and is one of Europe's biggest computer
producers.
Hardly a case of the ''continuous destruction of the Scottish economy
since 1707''.
Andrew Brocklehurst,
35 Polwarth Street,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000127</DOCNO>
