<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Taking the strain on stressways</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830592</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
D J MACLEOD writes of the increasing danger of pedestrians being
knocked down by cyclists making use of pavements (August 10).
Local authorities have done well in extending cycleways and relieving
cyclists of the stress of competing with motor traffic. But with more
relaxed cycling attitudes pavements are included in the cycletrack
network and pedestrians now take the strain on the resulting stressways.
D J Macleod would like to see local authorities enforcing rules to
ensure the safety of pedestrians. What are the rules? What are the
penalties for breaking them? Do cyclists pay compensation for injuries
inflicted on the pavement?
Children of all ages use pavements as speed tracks -- seemingly with
the approval of their parents. Cycling proficiency courses are now a
regular feature of the school curriculum. Are they aimed only at
increasing skill and confidence? Is there any mention of responsibility?
M T Kennedy,
30 Southampton Drive,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
