<HEADLINE>Precincts penetrated</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830594</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOUR correspondent John Kennedy hits the nail on the head today in
saying that the menace of cyclists on pavements is a growing problem
(August 15).
Further, it is almost certainly a serious accident waiting to happen.
Every day now I observe instances of schoolchildren on their large
''grown-up'' cycles dashing along narrow suburban pavements while the
more mature cyclists speed through city centre pedestrianised areas
luckily rather skilfully dodging pedestrians by millimetres.
Indeed, Glasgow's prestigious pedestrian precincts are rapidly
becoming a nonsense in this respect.
Only this morning pedestrians had to scatter for their lives in the
Sauchiehall Street area as a courier came down the hill at high speed on
a heavily loaded cycle.
Bells on cycles -- at one time considered to be an essential
precaution -- are now conspicuous by their total absence. So much for
adult common sense.
At one time a bobby on the beat would have dealt with such dangers but
how often does anyone see a bobby on the beat these days.
That leaves the council . . .
David Mitchell,
3 Sinclair Drive,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
