<HEADLINE>Excess growth of open-cast mining</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830599</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALTHOUGH I do not wish to comment on the specific planning
applications mentioned in your leader (Open-cast destruction, August
15), the escalation in numbers of proposals for open-cast mines
demonstrates the weakness in the Government planning guidance covering
the topic.
This guidance purports to take a sustainable approach to the
development and extraction of mineral resources but, while paying lip
service to the need to promote alternative materials and the need for
recycling, it starts from the standpoint that the level of mineral
extraction is a consequence of customer demand, is a matter for market
forces, and that planning authorities therefore should not attempt to
become involved in attempting to influence this demand.
It should therefore come as no surprise that the approach taken by the
Scottish Office has led to the growth of proposals for mineral and
aggregate extraction throughout Scotland.
Surely if our environment is to be viewed in a sustainable manner it
should first look at how best to minimise demand for these aggregates
rather than merely attempt to cope with this demand in the best possible
way.
Craig McLaren,
Director, The Royal Town Planning Institute in Scotland,
46 Northumberland Street,
Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
