<HEADLINE>The truth about a flyting</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830600</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I AM afraid the otherwise interesting pieces on literary feuds were
rather spoilt when you rehearse the background to the flyting of William
Dunbar and Bishop Kennedy (Weekender, August 12).
The Kennedy in question was Walter Kennedy, third son of the first
Lord Kennedy of Dunure, who graduated from Glasgow University in 1478
and was at various times examiner at that university, Provost of the
Collegiate Church, Maybole, and Depute Baillie of Carrick. It was his
uncle, James Kennedy, who was the Bishop of St Andrews.
This flyting should not be taken at face value for, as Roderick Watson
has recently pointed out, ''It is a mock-serious genre undoubtedly
derived from the Gaelic tradition''. He was held in high regard as a
poet by his fellow makars, Gavin Douglas and Sir David Lindsay.
His erstwhile victim, William Dunbar, in his Lament for the Makars
pays Kennedy the final accolade by giving him alone amongst all their
contemporaries a whole stanza to himself in this stately elegy:
Gud maister Walter Kennedy
In poynt of dede lyis veraly --
Gret reuth it wer that so suld be.
Timor mortis conturbat me.
Neil R MacCallum,
18 Redford Avenue,
Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
