<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830601</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOUR editorial and article on open-cast mining will have struck a
chord in many parts of rural Scotland (August 15).
Tillietudlem in Clydesdale faces similar intrusion by a proposed
open-cast mine. The area attracts large numbers of tourists and other
visitors and Craignethan Castle is a well-known local feature. This area
is on a major tourist route to New Lanark.
It is very unlikely the mine will create a single local job. Past
experience of open-cast mines is that the labour force is imported.
The inhabitants of Draffan and Tillietudlem face not only loss of
amenity and environmental damage but also long-term harm to the local
economy. Home owners may well find the value of their property falling.
The only winners are the private mining companies.
If Scottish Office ministers are puzzled by their unpopularity this
example can tell them why. The local community, and I as their
councillor, oppose the development. The Scottish Office will, as always,
back the quick-buck merchants.
They can rest assured that the Clyde Valley, like Ormiston, will fight
every inch of the way in defence of its environment and the local
economy.
Councillor Ann Winning,
20 Holding,
Stonebyres,
Kirkfieldbank.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
