<DOCNO>GH950818-000138</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Podium poser</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALEXANDER LINKLATER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830603</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Alexander Linklater confronts the good and bad faces of public
lecturing
THE Post Office Lecture this week should have been a mainstay of the
Book Festival. When a major British author gets together with a big
audience which includes many of her peers, the reasonable expectation is
that the occasion will focus the concerns which make literature worth
celebrating: the function of reading and writing, the projects of
fiction, contemporary conditions, the future.
Rose Tremain gave her audience almost nothing of this. She spoke
exclusively about her historical novel, Restoration, and its recent
adaptation for cinema. Very carefully she picked her way through the
book's central relationships and critical moments, explaining how they
were indispensable to the logic of her story. The film was failing, she
said, because it couldn't accommodate the symbolic transitions of
fiction.
This all took quite a long time to explain without being remotely
revealing. The whole scenario is so familiar. Stories about films which
ruin books are as old as Charlton Heston's Moses. And it wasn't even as
if this particular one sounded that bad. Rose Tremain was clearly quite
tickled by the idea of Hugh Grant and Robert Downey Jr playing her
characters.
Here was a talk about film-making by someone who didn't know much
about it. (Anyone who can say ''cinema is a literal medium'' can't have
seen that many films). The end result being that nothing much was said
about either movies or novels.
Which made it, by contrast, all the more exciting to listen to two
historical biographers who so profoundly understood the nature of good
fiction. Yesterday morning Claire Tomalin and Richard Holmes dug deep
into the private passions which lead them to search among a detritus of
letters, documents and historical fact for the hidden human story.
George IV's mistress, Mrs Jordan, gave him 10 children before she was
dumped. She had already had three. And yet no previous biography goes
into the domestic realities of her life. Claire Tomalin looks at history
through a line of mothers to pursue the secrets of such a character.
She had to know what it was that made someone like Mrs Jordan endure
her life with such wit, professionalism, and generosity. In between the
lines of official history such stories can be exhumed if you have the
investigative patience and a good narrative nose.
Richard Holmes told a story which was in itself a perfect explanation
for the storytelling obsessions of biography.
In Edinburgh, the city of Burke and Hare, Deacon William Brodie led
the double life of cabinetmaker and burglar. When he was caught they
hanged him on gallows made to his own design. But another of his
creations, a peculiar double-doored cabinet, found its way into the
possession of one Robert Louis Stevenson. This cryptic piece of
furniture and the split life of its maker gave Stevenson the dreams
which led to Jekyll and Hyde.
In talking about the personal secrets of the dead, Holmes was utterly
engrossing. He refuted the notion that biography is a Freudian process
that seeks jealously to destroy the reputations of past heroes.
Fieldwork, dreamwork, empathy and trust are his guiding principles,
along with a quotation from Voltaire: ''To the living we owe respect,
but to the dead we owe nothing but the truth.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
