<HEADLINE>''What they've just done is an act of tremendous international provocation''. China faces fall-out after nuclear test</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830604</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENTS worldwide reacted angrily to an underground nuclear blast
by China, saying it flew in the face of an undertaking in May by all
nuclear states to exercise utmost restraint in nuclear testing.
Diplomats said its timing was at the very least tactless, coming just
days after the 50th anniversary of the world's first atomic bombing, at
Hiroshima in Japan.
China argues it needs to conduct more tests because its technological
know-how lags behind the big four nuclear powers: the United States,
Russia, Britain, and France. Military experts believe the aim of China's
tests is to create lighter, more powerful warheads.
The explosion, equivalent to 20 to 80 kilotons of TNT, took place at
the Lop Nor nuclear test site in western Xinjiang at 2am British time
yesterday and created a shock that registered 5.6 on the Richter scale,
the Australian geological survey said in Canberra.
The United States said the test could harm efforts to reach a
comprehensive nuclear test ban treaty.
''The United States deeply regrets this action. All of the nuclear
weapon states agreed at the Nuclear Non-proliferation Treaty Review and
extension conference to exercise 'utmost restraint' in nuclear
testing,'' a White House statement said.
Japan threatened the strongest retaliation, hinting at aid cuts, while
New Zealand said the test was reprehensible.
A Greenpeace activist, who helped pull off an unprecedented if brief
anti-nuclear protest in Beijing on Tuesday, called the test a disaster
for international efforts to pass a comprehensive test ban.
''What they've just done is an act of tremendous international
provocation,'' said Ann Dingwall, who was deported by China to Hong Kong
on Wednesday.
Dingwall said France, which is under international pressure to cancel
its own test plans at Mururoa Atoll, was likely to be the only nation
which would not be upset by China's action.
In London, the Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament condemned ''the new
nuclear nightmare of the 90s''. A spokeswoman said the Chinese test
would only encourage the French to stick to their own plans to resume
nuclear testing.
CND said there were increasing fears that testing by China and France
and the deployment of Trident by Britain are early signs of a new arms
race.
It called on Mr Major to unequivocally condemn the latest test and to
support growing demands for the French to abandon their planned test.
Britain said it was not surprised by China's latest underground test.
''You could characterise our response as resigned to the fact that there
will be one or two tests from various parties such as the Chinese or the
French,'' a Foreign Office spokesman said.
Australia, which has angrily condemned France's decision to resume
testing in the South Pacific, said the China test could lead to a
serious threat to world peace and regional security.
Prime Minister Paul Keating said the blast might reinforce aspirations
by non-nuclear states to develop nuclear arms.
New Zealand Prime Minister Jim Bolger called the tests reprehensible
and disturbing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000140</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000140</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Conference dilemma for First Lady</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830605</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington
THE Clintons are on holiday in Wyoming, but politics have followed
them there. They have to decide by next week whether Hillary Clinton
will attend the UN conference on women in Peking next month.
Relations between the United States and China are now worse than at
any time since President Nixon went to China to meet Mao Tse-tung in
1972. The Chinese were enraged when the president of Taiwan was allowed
to visit America earlier this year, and disputes over human rights in
China and Chinese trade practices continue to roil the waters.
A noted Chinese dissident, Harry Wu, now a US citizen, was arrested in
China this summer: he had smuggled himself into the country to
investigate abuses in the prison system. China continues to supply
long-range missiles to North Korea, Iran, and other countries and has
carried out naval manoeuvers near Taiwan.
The women's conference will bring 50,000 people to Peking from
September 4 to 15. China has tried to limit the number of unofficial
visitors and even some unsympathetic official delegates have encountered
long delays in getting visas. The fringe of the conference has been
banished to a town 50 miles from the main event.
If Mrs Clinton goes, she will be bitterly criticised by, among others,
Harry Wu's wife, who has written to her urging her to boycott the event,
the Republican Party, and those who most openly criticise China's
lamentable record on human rights.
They all say that China would use Mrs Clinton's presence to its
propagandistic advantage, whatever she had to say to the conference.
The White House hopes that China will release Mr Wu. It insists that
there would be no connection between his release and a decision to send
Mrs Clinton to Peking, but it would obviously be much easier.
Mrs Clinton herself wants to go. She says that the conference ''is an
important opportunity to focus attention on women'', that the US
delegation ''should play a very big leadership role in shaping the
agenda'', and ''the United States should do all it can to make sure that
barriers to women's participation are broken down and that training and
credit and political involvement and health care are available to all
women''.
State Department officials are keeping their heads down. This is a
matter Mrs Clinton will decide with the president. They say only: ''It's
a conference that's not about China, it's about women.''
All the same, they are aware of the difficulty of the choice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000141</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000141</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wolfgang Holzmair, Queen's Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL TUMELTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976830606</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE seemed to be a fairly clear division of opinion yesterday at the
packed recital given by Austrian baritone, Wolfgang Holzmair: you were
either for him or agin him.
The polarity of views stems directly from Holzmair's performing
manner. Simply, if you view the performance of Lieder and chansons as a
cerebral experience, Wolfgang Holzmair might be the ultimate turn-off.
He is famous for the intensity of his singing, but what I didn't
realise until yesterday was that his involvement in delivering the goods
is total. And physical.
Everything he performs is given the theatrical treatment; none of your
standing still at the piano, hands elegantly folded into each other.
Holzmair is of the whole body school of singing. In a set of Lieder by
Schubert, each clearly interpreted as a miniature music drama, and also
depicted as such by pianist Gerard Wyss, he veered -- in gesture and
delivery -- towards the operatic. Some listeners visibly retreated from
this approach; for me it meant even greater involvement.
His voice -- with occasionally suspect tuning at the top of the range
-- is handsomely equipped for his style. He can float a phrase as though
it is weightless, and, when he surges into power, he unleashes a volume
of sound that is appropriate to the operatic stage.
And what it did mean, in the glorious sequence of French chansons by
Duparc and Faure, was that -- though he could never match the subtlety
of the greatest native French singers -- he was unabashed about tapping
directly into the exquisite sensuality of this ravishing music.
* Sponsored by Bank of Scotland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000142</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000142</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Signs of a solution to the opera crisis</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RUTH WISHART</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL DIARY</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976830607</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
* OK. Are you sitting down? I think the diary has cracked it. I think
we are talking the complete solution to Scottish Opera's current fiscal
crisis no less. And his name is Peter Llewellyn-Jones.
To recap for new readers, Scot Op's overdraft is in a parlous
condition and its chorus of 50-plus (excluding weans) has been in a
mutinous condition these many months. On to which running sore some
temporary Elastoplast has been applied allowing the Festival production
of The Jacobin to go ahead and prove to us that your man, Antonin
Dvorak, knew more about fine tunes than even that nice Mr Anderson.
Which brings us to Mr L-J. Modestly clad in black trousers and
open-necked shirt, he appears on stage throughout the entire three acts
giving the plot his dramatic all as befits a chap who has regular
employment with the Royal Shakespeare Company.
Mr L-J, you see, signs productions great and small for the deaf. So
for the three hours of this opera he plays, well, just about everybody.
At one juncture he appeared to be signing on behalf of seven soloists
and the entire chorus. So we have to ask ourselves if Scottish Opera,
with the services of such a uniquely versatile performer to hand, really
needs anyone else.
PS. British Telecom has sponsored signed interpretations of 18 Fringe
shows this year. Details on 0131-226 5138.
PPS. Scottish Opera's chairman Sandy Orr, attempting to get away from
it all for a spell, rented himself a quiet little villa plus pool in the
wilds of Tuscany.
Except that when he got there he found the owner ensconced in an
annexe. A gregarious owner who had a party for some two dozen of his
close relations on the first night around what Sandy had fondly imagined
was his private poolside.
In the circumstances he did what a West Coast boy does in times of
trouble. Fled to Mull. Better weather too.
* MORNING coffee and much agreeable reminiscing with Mr Maurice
Roeves, here on a flying visit from Los Angeles to join the ever more
glittery cast-list assembled by Andrew Byatt for his Scottish Actors'
Studio workshops.
Twelve years in Luvvytown has not dimmed the Glasgow accent or the
straight talking even though his other regular base-camp is London.
He's just back from filming a new version of The Ten Commandments with
Ben Kingsley in Morocco where he plays Zerak -- the Edward G Robinson
role in the original Heston version. Happily the screenplay has
undergone something of a linguistic facelift in the interim.
Roeves, the recipient of the 1994/95 Best Stage Actor Award from the
LA Times, clearly hasn't been neglecting his board skills either,
although he tells me he's now suffering from a serious writing bug and
plans to spend the next 18 months chained to the word processor. However
he has a longer-term plan to keep him in suitably solvent style which
involves his enviable collection of original Levis.
Although the boyish features and ever lean body defy you to believe
it, Maurice is only a year distant from hitting the big 60. At which
juncture he plans to offer the jeans company a current snap of himself
poured into 30-year-old denim with the accompanying slogan . . . In His
Sixties He's Still In His Sixties!
* FRINGE-GOERS still baffled by the new-look Fringe Brochure now have
a visual aid to combat terminal indecision.
Now showing at a video screen near you, one-minute extracts from
scores of shows, made by the artistes themselves and knocked into
seamless shape by Scottish Television.
However Fringe director Hilary Strong did feel impelled to view every
foot of the rough cut in case these naughty thesps had inadvertently
offended against public decency. Which, of course, they hadn't.
Well, all right, there was the shot of that odd young man having
toilet paper set alight in close proximity to his hindquarters. But so
coy are this year's youth that he kept his Y's on all the while. Sweet
really.
* BEING a right on, PC sort of lot, Poulter and Duff invited several
groups who had been working in the public health field to their A-Z of
Drugs at the Assembly Rooms. Including Crew 2000 which works with young
people on harm-reduction schemes. Crew 2000 gave the anxious cast a
reasonable review afterwards.
And a list of currently popular substances they'd missed out!
* A WORLD first. This week saw the queues for the official Festival
tickets outgun the queues for the Military Tattoo. Or so alleges a
usually reliable eyewitness.
On the other hand, Brian McMaster probably isn't the most objective
source of comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
