<DOCNO>GH950818-000143</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000143</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Near perfection</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALLAN LAING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830608</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Allan Laing reviews a screen masterwork which ably develops the dark
sides of film noir and Glasgow
FOR a sum of money which would barely meet the cost of the catering
bill for your average Hollywood movie, director David Hayman and
producer Len Crooks have created a work of immense style, outstanding
quality, and exceptional depth. Quite simply, The Near Room is a
close-to-perfect example of what a contemporary film noir should be.
Armed with a potent storyline from writer Robert Murphy (the man has a
rare talent to deceive) which, though complex, never once loses its way
amid its dark twists and sinister turns, Hayman has removed the safety
catch and shot a tense and genuinely menacing thriller which is,
occasionally, rather startling in its execution.
The performances, particularly from Adrian Dunbar as the central
character Charlie Colquhoun, a hard-bitten tabloid hack, and David
O'Hara as Harris Hill, a too-good-to-be-true lawyer who specialises in
social causes, are both strong and peculiarly compelling.
The remaining cast (which includes James Ellis, Julie Graham, Sean
Scanlan, Robert Pugh, Hayman himself, and that great Scots actor Tom
Watson in particularly fine form) are faultless and do no mean justice
to the excellence of the script.
The Near Room is a story about demons. Not a horror tale; no fantasy
monsters here. In this, the monsters are all too human and the demons
are the personal ones which lurk in the minds of all of us should we
delve deep enough into our psyche to shake them into life.
When Charlie Colquhoun was a teenage schoolkid he fathered a child; a
little girl called Thomasina Stirling. They called her Tommy and they
placed her in care. Or maybe she was adopted. Or fostered. Colquhoun was
young; it was all the same to him.
But now years later, working as an investigative reporter in Glasgow
and answering to a foul-mouthed tyrant of an editor (Hayman), Colquhoun
gets a call from Clegg, an underworld contact. He's got a story. It's a
scandal about a kid. Her name is Tommy Stirling.
Dark memories return to haunt Colquhoun. Terrible thing, guilt. The
child is his. Must be his. He abandoned her and now she's in trouble; if
Clegg knows her then it's a dead cert she's in soapy. But then he finds
Clegg dead, his throat cut, his mouth permanently shut before he can
tell his story.
And so Colquhoun embarks upon a journey into the heart of his
darkness. Towards his own near room. And what is the near room? It's the
place ''where snakes scream and alligators play trombones''. The door to
the near room is there for everyone to open; go through it and you enter
your own personal hell where past demons reappear to raise their ugly
heads.
But Colquhoun is not the only person knocking on Hades' door. There's
Hill, his former schoolfriend, now a charismatic lawyer with a
conscience so pure that it just has to be suspect. What is his
connection to the affair? Why should he be so interested in a little
girl long-abandoned?
The journalist's search for his daughter leads him into the city's
disturbing demi monde, a place where it's always night and the people
you encounter are whores, pimps, and junkies. And here we find the real
star of the movie: Glasgow. Not the chocolate-box city of pretty parks
and sophisticated cafes. This is the squalid underbelly. Welcome to the
real world, its dangerous edge suffused in murky shadows (the lighting
is one of the movie's greatest strengths).
The dreadful truth emerges that Tommy was involved in a sordid
blackmail ring involving paedophiles. The finger of guilt trembles and
begins to point in Hill's direction.
Then there's a second murder, that of a shady policeman (Robert Pugh),
and suddenly Colquhoun emerges as the prime suspect.By chance, he speaks
to a terrified Tommy on the telephone and, finally, he drives to a
remote country house, home to a group of New Age tree-huggers, where the
child has sought refuge. Finally, he discovers the truth and returns to
the city with Tommy, intent on confronting the vile fiend who has abused
his daughter.
But en route Colquhoun turns his back for a brief moment and the child
is abducted at a roadside cafe. Now there is only one way to save her.
He has to face Harris Hill and, together, they must enter the near room.
Naturally, there is a sting in the tail, the ubiquitous denoument which
no self-respecting thriller should be without.
The Near Room is a wonderfully nasty piece of work which reeks of
low-life atmosphere. It is violent, but not excessively so. Faults?
Well, perhaps a small one. The F-word -- with which I seldom have a
problem -- is grossly over-used. To the point of distraction, in fact.
Okay, I know that it's simply an attempt to reflect the reality of the
Glasgow parlance. But when we hear it repeated with monotonous
regularity in a cinematic setting it tends to become far too
conspicuous.
Finally, a word of praise for young Emma Faulkner who plays Tommy, a
child much older than her years. Her performance will haunt you.
Outwardly she is tough and in-your-face but inside there is a
desperately sad and fragile little girl aching for a love she has never,
in her life, been allowed to find.
* The Near Room opens tonight at the Glasgow Film Theatre as part of
the Drambuie Edinburgh Film Festival.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
