<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lord Lovat wrote will in meticulous detail. Needs of friends filled final thoughts</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830609</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WAR hero Lord Lovat wrote his will on his death-bed two weeks before
he died, it has been revealed.
The 82-year-old veteran, once described by Winston Churchill as ''the
mildest man to ever scuttle a ship or cut a throat'', showed his
compassion for commoner and aristocrat alike.
He made many small bequests to Army comrades, estate workers, and
family friends but one of the largest was to Myra Freed, the woman who
nursed him when he had a near-fatal heart attack in 1951. She has been
left #3000.
He had been kept informed throughout his lengthy illness of the fate
that awaited his once-proud and vast estate and knew that it would have
to be sold to pay off the family debts.
However, in one final stance of defiance, Lord Lovat tried to ensure
that at least Balblair House, the mansion where he spent his final days,
would remain in the family.
He left it to his wife, Rosamund, and subsequently to their oldest
surviving son, Hugh. However, he also left strict instructions that if
Balblair House had to be sold, the current Lord Lovat, now his grandson,
Simon, should have the chance to buy it.
The contents he also left to Lady Lovat and in a further effort to
ensure she spends her final days in some comfort, he left permission for
the contents to be sold by her, if necessary, for her own benefit.
Lord Lovat gave up administering the huge family estate 26 years ago,
handing it over to his son, the Master of Lovat, Simon, who died from a
heart attack, aged 54, almost exactly a year before his father.
What the founder of the Commandos retained has been valued at #1.9m.
Around #1m of that is the value of Balblair House and other heritable
estate, while the remainder comprises mostly paintings, furnishings,
shares, and bank accounts.
One poignant remark logged in the document is a #500 gift to his
former Commando colleagues.
Lord Lovat instructed: ''To my old comrades in the First Commando
Brigade, men I once had the honour to command, I bequeath #500.'' The
money will be distributed by the Old Comrades Association.
Workers at Balblair House, where Lord Lovat lived with his wife, were
also remembered. Gardener Donald Jack, who still lives in staff quarters
at the house, was left #1000.
Forestry worker Ivan Stuart, who knew Lord Lovat for more than 30
years, was left #500 and his wife Janice was left #300.
Mr Stuart, of Millcroft, Kilmorack, said: ''We were pleasantly
surprised to find out about the inheritance. We were not expecting it.
But Lord Lovat was a kind man and a friend to many.''
In total, #16,000 was left to friends and staff.
Lord Lovat's favourite sport, shinty, was also recognised with Lovat
and Beauly Shinty clubs each receiving #500 to ''keep up and maintain
the manly and martial traditions of the Aird and Clan Fraser County''.
Highland Hospice and the Roman Catholic churches at Beauly and
Eskadale, where the funerals of Lord Lovat and his two sons took place,
also each received #500.
A #2000 account has been opened for the benefit of ''old friends from
the past who helped run the estate''. They are seven former heads of
staff who helped manage the once-massive Fraser lands, which are now up
for sale for more than #6m.
Closing date for offers was last Thursday but there has still been no
announcement about the eventual buyer. It is likely the estate will be
split among a host of purchasers.
One who has been tipped to buy the family seat of Beaufort Castle is
Lord Lovat's daughter, Tessa Keswick. She has been left a Raoul Millais
painting which hung over her father's fireplace.
Balblair House, its contents, and the remainder of the estate go to
Lord Lovat's widow, and the house will be passed on to his oldest
surviving son, Hugh, on her death.
Lady Lovat is already planning to move out of the house so that her
favourite son can make it home for his family now.
Hugh has also been given several areas of woodland and shooting
rights. He said yesterday: ''Although my father was dying, he was still
in possession of his faculties right up to the end. He rewrote his will
every year to ensure he was able to cover the many people he was close
to.''
The new Lord Lovat, 18-year-old Simon, son of the late Master of
Lovat, has not been forgotten. He has inherited the woodlands and
shooting rights of Eskadale Wood.
If a film is ever made of the life of one of the bravest and most
famous landowners in the country, his other daughter, Fiona Allen, will
inherit the rights of broadcasting or filming the book of his memoirs,
March Past.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000145</DOCNO>
