<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Case for a SCOTTISH press conomics Editor Alf Young argues in favour of independent newspaper ownership.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALF YOUNG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830610</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE prospect of Caledonian Publishing, owners of The Herald, mounting
a bid to buy Scotsman Publications and Aberdeen Journals, publishers of
our great rival, The Scotsman, and its sister title, the Press &amp;
Journal, has stirred up a foaming froth of speculation in the rest of
the media and in Scottish business circles.
The facts of the matter are simply stated. The Connecticut-based
Thomson Corporation, having sold its English regional newspaper chain to
Trinity, has hung For Sale signs round its two Scottish newspaper
businesses. It has indicated that it would prefer to sell the papers in
a single package. Caledonian, together with a large number of other
media groups, has registered its interest in that sale.
Once Caledonian and its advisers have studied the books of the
Edinburgh and Aberdeen-based businesses -- and remember, it is two years
since either filed separate accounts, following their consolidation into
the Thomson Regional Newspapers UK accounts -- a firm offer to acquire
may follow.
These are the unvarnished facts. But already the mere prospect of
three of Scotland's four morning daily broadsheets being owned by a
single publisher has sent the hares of speculation, indignation, and
malice scampering through the heather, acting for all the world as if
this were March not August.
It is suggested, notably by former Scotsman editor Sir Alastair
Dunnett, that a Glasgow-based company isn't a fitting owner for
Edinburgh's established broadsheet. It is alleged by another former
Scotsman editor, Englishman Andrew Jaspan, that Caledonian's management
is hardly up to running the titles it's got, let alone a stable boosted
by Thomson's Scottish portfolio.
There is the absurd charge that Caledonian wants to buy The Scotsman
simply to shut it down. There is the widespread assertion that, for
Caledonian, frustrated so far in its ambitions for a stock market
listing, this deal represents ''double or quits''. And there is a
knee-jerk reaction, in some quarters, insisting that any plan to put The
Herald, The Scotsman and The P&amp;J under the same Scottish-based ownership
would automatically fall foul of the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
The heat already generated by the news of Caledonian's interest in the
Thomson titles suggests the outcome of this sale matters deeply to a
great many people. But why is who owns these papers so important? I
believe Herald readers have the right to have the key arguments
rehearsed. That is why this article is devoted to matters very close to
home, here in Albion Street.
I do not write as a mouthpiece for Caledonian. I offer, as I always
try to do, my own perspective. But first, let me declare a small
personal interest. I own 169 shares in Caledonian Publishing, around the
same number as most other members of staff. I do not expect to make my
fortune from that holding, no matter how successful Caledonian proves to
be. So, what follows is not motivated by the glint of future gold.
I have worked in newspapers since 1981, first on the late-lamented
Sunday Standard, then, for nearly three years, with The Scotsman and,
since November 1986, here at The Herald. In all that time the indigenous
Scottish broadsheet market has remained as balkanised as ever it was.
Excluding the tabloids, Glaswegians predominantly read The Herald. The
Scotsman dominates Edinburgh's breakfast tables. Dundonians take DC
Thomson's Courier. And in Aberdeen, The P&amp;J reigns supreme.
Management strategies to break into each other's core markets have
come and gone. But, while small circulation gains have been made at the
margin, local reader loyalties have, on the whole, held firm. When
Edinburgh acquaintances have occasionally expressed dissatisfaction with
The Scotsman, I have always inquired why more of them don't switch to
The Herald. Their answers are strikingly consistent.
''You don't list the Edinburgh births, deaths and marriages.'' Or
''You don't carry enough east coast classified ads.'' Or ''I couldn't
sell my house through The Herald.'' Only when these social and practical
concerns are out of the way have we ever got down to debating editorial
issues, like the relative coverage of local news.
In recent years that balkanised stand-off has been shaken from the
outside. London-based newspaper groups, after years of neglect and, in
some cases, effective withdrawal, have rediscovered the Scottish
marketplace. The Sun has reinvented itself, embracing the nationalist
cause, but only north of the Border.
The Murdoch papers, The Mail, and The Express, have exploited modern
production technology to launch Scottish cover versions of what you can
buy in London, printed here and introducing a leavening of local news
stories, Scottish columnists and Scottish sport to the mix. Even The
Financial Times now prints in Leeds, bringing later-breaking financial
news to its small Scottish readership.
I have no quarrel with that increasing competition for Scottish
readers. It stimulates all of us to try harder and produce even better
newspapers than we did yesterday. But this reawakening of interest in
the Scottish newspaper market has coincided with a protracted
cover-price war which does carry with it worrying implications.
Rupert Murdoch started it. Conrad Black's Telegraph responded, as did
The Independent. The Scottish version of The Mail is, thus far, a
cut-price offering too. Even The Scotsman and its Sunday stablemate,
Scotland on Sunday, have had to respond with cut-price coupon offers.
There is clear evidence that slashing the cover price does attract
extra readers. The Mail has nearly doubled its Scottish readership. The
Scottish circulation of The Times is up almost 50%. Indigenous Scottish
titles, lacking the resources to respond in kind, have borne much of the
pain.
When I was at The Scotsman 10 years ago, its daily circulation was
knocking on the door of 100,000. Today it stands at barely
three-quarters of that. The Herald has fared better, but has still lost
4.5% of its average daily sales in the latest Audit Bureau half-yearly
figures.
Bluntly, the indigenous Scottish broadsheet press is facing the
fiercest battle for readers in its long history, against expansionist
southern rivals with much deeper pockets who can and will price their
product well below the cost of production. Ironically, this battle is
joined at the very point where Scotland -- assuming the opinion polls
are correct -- is poised to receive a significant measure of home rule
and its own elected assembly in Edinburgh.
In the midst of this bitter fight for readers, the Thomson Corporation
decides to put its Scottish papers up for sale, a once-in-a-generation
opportunity. A management buy-out of Scotsman Publications, similar to
that which brought control of The Herald back to Glasgow, has been ruled
out. There is talk of other consortia bids to keep control of the titles
in Scotland. There is also talk that the DC Thomson empire in Dundee is
interested in the Aberdeen titles. But so far the only concrete
expression of interest which would keep the Thomson titles Scottish has
come from Caledonian.
Mr Jaspan, who was so dismissive of that interest on Radio Scotland
last week, was responsible, in his brief tenure of the editor's chair at
North Bridge, for a radical revamp of The Scotsman. That revamp
coincided with a further significant fall in Scotsman sales.
Mr Jaspan, who purports to care about the continued vitality of an
independent Scottish press, but who failed to tell his radio listeners
that he has been encouraging his new employers, Guardian Media Group, to
bid for Thomson's Scottish titles, might care to answer one simple
question.
If Caledonian does not pursue its interest in the Thomson papers, what
stands between them and control by a London or overseas newspaper group?
And if a deep-pocketed outsider buys The Scotsman and unleashes another
round of the cover-price wars north of the Border, what prospect The
Herald's continued independence, as well?
He is vituperative about Caledonian's management. But neither he, nor
anyone else at the time of the Caledonian buy-out, could have foreseen
how protracted the recession would be, the prospect of a damaging
cover-price war or the rocketing price of newsprint. Caledonian's
management is not perfect. No management, in my experience, ever is.
But the commercial challenges our parent company faces are the same
ones facing the Thomson titles and every one else in the industry. The
fact that Caledonian has not yet achieved a stock market listing is more
a matter of luck and timing -- key factors in the success of any
leveraged buy-out -- than anything else.
The Midland Independent buy-out in Birmingham did make it to market.
But their shares today trade at a significant discount to the offer
price, effectively spiking the appetite of investors for more of the
same.
If we follow through the logic of a deep-pocketed London group buying
The Scotsman and then buying readers by slashing the cover price, it is
not difficult to sketch a scenario in which a Scottish Assembly opens
for business with all the main Scottish broadsheets, with the exception
of The Courier, controlled by newspaper groups with decidedly
London-dominated agendas.
Even if the Tories recover and win the next election, and the prospect
of devolution recedes, a Scottish press controlled by major London
newspaper groups would mark, in my view, a seriously retrograde step,
one which ought to concern Scots of every political persuasion.
With The Herald owned by Lonrho and The Scotsman and The P&amp;J owned by
Canadians, the proprietorial hand on the editorial tiller was light. If
Scotland, with or without an assembly, has any real pretensions to
maintaining its distinctive national identity, it needs a responsive
press with the freedom to reflect Scottish aspirations and priorities,
Scottish concerns and choices. That objective cannot be achieved by
inserting a Scottish supplement here, an opportunist change of political
allegiance there, or a tartan wrap-round everywhere. It would be
extinguished if every major broadsheet ended up being owned by London
press barons.
There has been a lot of ill-considered talk about a Caledonian bid
creating a monopoly in the Scottish newspaper market. Even if The
Herald, The Scotsman and The P&amp;J were all owned by one company, total
daily sales of the three titles at present account for no more than 17%
of all morning newspaper sales in Scotland. And, as I've already pointed
out, there is modest overlap in their respective circulation areas. If,
as it should do, Caledonian gives firm guarantees of editorial
independence to each title, there should be little to worry the MMC in
such a deal.
The real prize, at a time when other Scottish companies, like
ScottishPower and Scottish &amp; Newcastle, have been turning the tide of
hostile takeover which so eroded Scotland's corporate base in the 1980s,
is a Scottish media company of sufficient size and diversity to add
further weight to that renaissance. A company which, once listed, we
could all invest in.
If it matters to have a Scottish system of justice and a distinctive
educational tradition, Scottish banks and churches and our own solutions
to issues as diverse as economic development and water and electricity
privatisation, it matters that Scotland retains a Scottish-owned press
which reflects that diversity. That's what is really at stake in the
bidding for The Scotsman and the other Thomson titles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
