<HEADLINE>Those Irish troupers dig the King's</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SARA VILLIERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830611</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TO THE trenches, boys, the Abbey is coming -- the stage management at
the King's Theatre must be crying this week. For the second year in
succession the Abbey Theatre Company is making an assault on the
Edinburgh theatre.
Abbey director Patrick Mason makes a full confession: ''Last year we
filled the theatre with mud for The Well of the Saints, they're probably
still finding clumps of peat in the pit, and now we're taking a big hole
out of the stage.''
Staff at the King's have been furiously digging to prepare the massive
10ft by 3ft 6in trench for the Abbey's production of Frank McGuinness's
Observe the Sons of Ulster Marching Towards The Somme, part of the
International Festival programme.
The play was first produced 10 years ago by the Abbey and Mason
restaged it last year to mark the Northern Ireland ceasefire. At a press
conference yesterday McGuinness explained his motivation for writing a
drama which, in celebrating the blood sacrifice of Ulstermen during the
First World War, might seem at odds with his own Nationalist background.
''I felt a challenge to try to enter the Protestant experience and
imagination,'' he said, emphasising that: ''the play is more about
recognition than reconciliation. If we are going to redefine our culture
then we have to make massive acts of recognition.
''The Protestant people in Ireland have a story and a history and I
wanted to tell it.''
Festival director Brian McMaster is hoping the Abbey will also be
making an assault on audience figures -- and with over 50% of tickets
already sold and with a near-capacity crowd for tonight's opening
performance, he is confident that ticket bookings will escalate through
word-of-mouth acclaim.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
