<DOCID>GH950818-000148</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Villagers urged to take a stand against thugs</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830613</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Sutherland village of Brora is being ''held to ransom'' by a hard
core of local youths, according to a senior police officer.
Members of the public are said to be afraid to report witnessing
assaults and vandalism because of fear of reprisals.
Inspector Donald Oliphant, based at Dornoch, said at a community
council meeting that the police were unable to solve the problem without
public support.
He said: ''We have a hard-core element of about 12 who are basically
holding the Brora community to ransom. They are dictating the level of
behaviour. Police officers get involved with them but our problem is we
are lacking witnesses to incidents.
''People will phone us and complain about this particular group but
they do not wish to become involved. The moment they say that to us, our
hands are tied because we cannot progress it any further.
''Unless people are prepared to stand up and be counted, they will get
the level of behaviour in the community which they deserve because they
are not standing up for their community.''
Mr Oliphant was told, however, that many people would be afraid of
giving evidence in court because they felt that they would be victimised
by the youths.
Community councillor Margaret Jaffrey said elderly people in
particular were afraid to come forward.
She said: ''Part of this element have quite a widespread family
network in the village and it is causing problems. People are scared to
speak out.''
Mr Oliphant said intimidation was ''totally unacceptable'' and would
be treated more seriously than any original offence.
The community council's vice chairman, Mr John MacDonald, agreed that
people had to be ready to report incidents to the police. He warned that
a serious or fatal injury could happen if something was not done soon.
He said: ''Unless we all support the police, we will all be hostages
to this problem, and if it goes on it won't be long before something of
an appalling nature happens.''
Community councillors are to look at the possibility of setting up a
neighbourhood watch scheme and of inviting a crime prevention officer to
meet them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
