<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000153</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000153</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Runaway girl ordered back to Ireland</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE MCKAIN, LAW CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830618</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A 13-YEAR-OLD girl who ran away to Scotland after hiding under a bed
from her mother has been ordered by a judge to go back to Ireland.
Lord Dawson decided that Victoria Marshall should return to Kinsale,
in County Cork, despite the opinion of a psychologist that she should be
allowed to stay with her father in Fraserburgh.
The judge took the view that there was a ''degree of exaggeration'' in
Victoria's reasons for being unhappy in Ireland.
The girl's mother, Mrs Mary Marshall, asked the judge at the Court of
Session for an order under the Child Abduction and Custody Act for the
return of her daughter. This was opposed by the girl.
Lord Dawson was informed that Mrs Marshall and her husband, Paul, were
married in 1974 and had five children. They lived in Kinsale until June
last year, when they separated and Mr Marshall moved to Scotland.
Mrs Marshall formed a relationship with another man and Victoria
alleged that the couple were more interested in going out drinking than
caring about the children.
This claim was denied by the couple, who disputed that they went out
or drank to excess.
Victoria said she had become more and more unhappy and confided in her
aunt for whom she babysat on a regular basis.
In April this year, she decided that she had had enough and, with her
aunt's help, caught a plane to Edinburgh after telephoning her father.
Before she left, her mother had been searching for her all night and
had gone to the aunt's house. She was told that Victoria was not there
but, in fact, she was hiding under a bed.
Under the Hague Convention on which the Child Abduction and Custody
Act is based, a child is normally returned to where he or she has been
living, for the courts there to decide on custody.
However, that may not happen if the child has a valid objection to
being returned and the judge is satisfied that he or she is mature
enough for these views to be taken into account.
Lord Dawson said he had not found it an easy case to decide.
''Victoria was clearly unhappy with her life in Ireland. I was quite
satisfied that her objection to returning was genuine and heartfelt. I
was also satisfied that she was happy to remain in Scotland and was
under no pressure from her father to remain.''
The psychologist who interviewed Victoria had also told the court that
Victoria was old enough and mature enough to understand what she was
doing.
The psychologist said: ''It is my opinion that her wishes should be
respected, that she would not agree to live with her mother and would
return to Scotland at the first opportunity.''
Lord Dawson said there had to be good and valid reasons for the girl's
objecting to being sent home.
He had heard evidence from her mother, the boyfriend, and Victoria's
older sister as well as independent witnesses who contradicted
Victoria's version of events.
The judge took the view that she was exaggerating her reasons for
being unhappy in Ireland.
He pointed out that her father, who lives in Mid Street, St Combs,
Fraserburgh, had not noticed that Victoria was unhappy during his visits
to Ireland shortly before she ran away.
Lord Dawson added: ''I therefore hold that it has not been established
that, standing the age and maturity of Victoria, there is sufficient
substance given for her objection to returning.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000154</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000154</DOCID>
