<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000157</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000157</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The grim list of those who died reaching for the summit</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830622</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE grim list of K2 fatalities was first compiled for one of the
classic books to stem from the mountain, The Endless Knot by Kurt
Diemberger, and it was reprinted by Jim Curran.
The first death was on July 30, 1939, when an American, Dudley Wolfe
died of what now looks like high altitude sickness and exhaustion at
7550 metres on the Abruzzi Spur. Wolfe was a strange figure, a wealthy
playboy with yachts, power boats, fast cars and much enthusiasm for
mountains coupled with a near-total lack of ability. It reportedly took
two guides to haul his bulk up easy climbs while he could only descend
safely under constant supervision.
Chosen probably for his funds in a highly-unbalanced American team, he
died a miserable and appalling death in a tent beyond any hope of relief
and rescue, the lowest point of a doomed attempt which led to endless
recriminations throughout American mountaineering. It is almost a
footnote to that episode that three Sherpas also lost their lives.
It was August 1953, before the next death, that of another American,
Art Gilkey -- a fatality around which legend has grown. Gilkey, who had
developed blood clots in the veins of his left leg at around 7800
metres, certainly knew he was doomed. After a traumatic fall which
almost wiped out the whole expedition as they tried to bring Gilkey
down, did Gilkey cut himslef loose to save the others?
No one will ever know, but the Hunza porters built a memorial cairn on
a spur above the confluence of the Savoia and Godwin-Austen Glaciers.
Others have been buried close by over the years.
The first famous British climber to perish was Nick Estcourt, in June,
1978. Estcourt was slab avalanched while crossing an exposed snow slope
at 6500 metres on K2's West Ridge. Doug Scott, on the other end of the
rope, was saved when his heavy rucksack anchored him, snapping the rope.
The deaths continued sporadically through the 70s and early 80s,
including heart attacks to a Pakistani climber and a Pole. Then came the
climactic events of 1986 which began with the deaths of Americans John
Smolich and Alan Pennington in an avalanche at 6000 metres on the SSW
Ridge. Three days later the French couple Liliane and Maurice Barrard
were killed while descending the Abruzzi Spur. On July 10, 16 days
later, the famous Polish climber Tadeusz Piotrowski, fell while
descending the Abruzzi, and six days later the Italian Renato Casarotto
fell into a crevasse at 6500 metres.
The grisly roll call continued with the death of Wojceich Wroz, a
Polish climber who fell while descending on August 3 and a Pakistani,
Mohammed Ali, the following day -- killed by a stonefall low down on the
mountain. Three days later came the death of Julie Tullis, an event
still attended by controversy. Tullis died apparently of exhaustion
after a fall, having reached the summit late in the day with Kurt
Diemberger.
Alan Rouse, another famous British name, died of high altitude
sickness and exhaustion three days later, the same day that the
Austrians Alfred Imitzer and hannes Wieser and the great Polish woman
climber Dobroslawa Wolf also perished from the same causes. Then
followed a pause in the deaths as K2 saw fewer exhibiitions in the
following five years. But 1993 saw five more climbers die and last year
a similar number as the rate of expeditioning picked up once more.
Of those who reached the summit in the fateful year of 1986 and
survived the descent, five subsequently died -- Michel Parmentier and
Petr Bozik on Everest, Jerzy Kukuczka on Lhotse, Gianni Calcagno on
Denali, and Wanda Rutkiewicz on Kangchenjunga.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
