<DOCNO>GH950818-000159</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000159</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Travel firm is fined #1000 over brochure</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830624</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TRAVEL company was fined #1000 yesterday for using false information
in its holiday brochure.
Airtours claimed that the Club Tahiti apartments in Costa Teguise,
Lanzarote, were air-conditioned. However, Glasgow couple Kevin and Alice
McDaid arrived to find that this was not the case.
Airtours, of Helmshore, Lancashire, pleaded guilty at Glasgow Sheriff
Court to a contravention of the Trade Descriptions Act.
Sheriff Craig Henry said it was important that tour operators ensured
the information in their brochures was correct.
Miss Diane Turner, prosecuting, said the McDaids, of 3 Central Path,
Mount Vernon, booked a holiday in Lanzarote for July last year. Two days
before they were due to leave, they were told by their travel agent that
the apartments had been overbooked, and were offered alternative
accommodation.
Mrs McDaid got the firm to fax her the brochure page describing the
Club Tahiti, which said the apartments were air-conditioned and were
rated three keys, and then accepted the new location.
Mr Michael Ritchie, defending, said the company very much regretted
what had happened and had taken steps to tighten up its system of
checking accommodation.
The lawyer said that normally Airtours double-checked the brochure
descriptions were correct. ''Normally, if a mistake is made, the second
check ensures it is corrected and rectified before it appears,'' he
said.
Mr Ritchie said the company had compensated the couple.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000160</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000160</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ice cream on ration as firm feels the heat</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830625</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN ICE cream manufacturer admitted last night that it was rationing
its products to cope with unprecedented demand.
Birds Eye Wall's said that, despite round-the-clock production at its
Gloucester factory, it was ''allocating'' supplies of ice creams to
retailers.
Ice lollies have been the big sellers.
A spokeswoman for Birds Eye Wall's said: ''Soft drinks manufacturers
are in exactly the same position. We supply shops, petrol forecourts and
leisure outlets and we are allocating stock to make sure everyone gets
some.''
It meant that ice cream outlets would not necessarily receive all the
products they ordered.
She said ice cream sales in August were forecast to be double that of
the same month last year while Wall's sales in July soared to 100
million portions -- or two ice creams for every man, woman and child in
the UK.
''The unprecedented and prolonged hot weather has caused huge demand
in a short space of time, especially for the refreshment lines
(lollies).
''We are working full-pelt 24 hours a day to keep up with demand.''
* Mushrooms are the latest victims of the heatwave. They don't like
the heat and are refusing to grow and there is now a nationwide
shortage.
Supermarkets and restaurants are having to buy the Dutch variety at
more than double the price.
A spokesman for Scottish Mushrooms said yesterday that even a week of
cooler weather could have production back to normal.
''But while the hot weather continues we don't stand a chance'' he
said.
* With the royal family in residence, the area around Balmoral -- with
temperatures hitting 82F -- was one of the hottest in the country
yesterday. Nearby Aboyne boasted the highest officially recorded
temperature of the day in Scotland.
The only places to rival Deeside were a few sheltered Highland glens,
and Glasgow and Dumfries came close with 81F.
Weather forecasters promised a hot and sunny weekend almost everywhere
in Scotland, with the dry spell showing no signs of ending.
A spokesman for the Glasgow Weather Centre said: ''The charts show it
will stay fine right into next week. There may be a little cloud in the
North-west, but the high pressure will continue.''
* Experts say the bookmakers' money is safe -- the odds are
lengthening against the temperature hitting 100F.
Boookmakers stand to lose a fortune if that happens.
However, after shortening the odds last week, they are breathing more
easily.
Met Office experts now say it is unlikely that temperatures will go
above the 98.9 degrees recorded in Cheltenham in August 1990.
The days are starting to shorten as the sun sets earlier and earlier,
reducing the chances of it getting any warmer.
* AS lawns remain parched in the dry spell, Woburn Golf club in
Bedfordshire admitted pouring 65,000 gallons of water a day for the last
three months on their greens and fairways.
Automatic sprinklers have been pumping water every night to prepare
the 18-hole Duke's course for today's Women's British Open.
The club -- which is owned by the Duke of Bedford -- made an agreement
with Anglian Water to use its entire quota watering the championship
course.
Mr Alex Hay, managing director of Woburn Golf and Country Club, said
the company was spending about #200 a night on watering the course.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000161</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000161</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>India 'is controllingthe hostage takers'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BRUCE, DEFENCE CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830626</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITISH hostages Paul Wells and Keith Mangan may be the victims of a
secret Indian Government ''dirty tricks'' operation to discredit
militant Kashmiri separatist movements, according to military sources.
It is also understood that New Delhi has so far resisted an offer made
earlier this week by Whitehall to provide an SAS assault team for a
rescue mission to free the four surviving captives by force.
They were reported yesterday to be ''quite healthy''. Mr K V Krishna
Rao, governor of India's Jammu and Kashmir state, said a government
intermediary had contacted the Al-Faran militants, who killed a fifth
hostage by beheading him.
He said that while a rescue raid would be risky, it remained an
option. However, a senior military source claimed last night it was
increasingly probable the little-known Al-Faran faction was being armed
and funded by India and may even be led by undercover Indian commandos
or Afghan mercenaries. Some of its hard-core members may not even be
aware who was controlling them.
He said: ''The events of the past week have all the hallmarks of a
covert Indian 'black' operation aimed at isolating Islamic militants in
Kashmir by turning international opinion against them. The hidden agenda
is an end to criticism of New Delhi's military repression in the region
and freedom of action to take decisive military steps.
''The fact that the four remaining hostages are British, American, and
German -- drawn from three of the most influential Western nations -- is
no coincidence.
''The beheading of the Norwegian captive earlier this week was a
classic terror tactic calculated for maximum shock effect. His
decapitation was a deliberate and cruelly cynical attempt to grab world
attention and shape opinion.
''Al-Faran has also been communicating remarkably freely and directly
with both the Indian Government and its state-controlled media. No other
genuine Kashmiri resistance group has done so in more than five years of
armed conflict.''
Pakistan also accused India of being behind the kidnappings to raise
tension in the disputed region for political ends. Foreign Minister
Aseff Ahmad Ali told a news conference his government believed New
Delhi's aim was to defame what he called the Kashmiri freedom struggle
and give a political boost to Indian Prime Minister Narasimha Rao. India
and Pakistan have fought two full-scale wars over the disputed state
since 1965.
The overwhelmingly Islamic state is the centre of growing resistance
to rule by Hindu India. More than 100 liberation groups, with up to
40,000 men, are fighting the Indian administration.
Al-Faran has demanded jailed militants be freed in exchange for the
hostages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000162</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000162</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The savage beauty which refuses to be tamed by generations of climbing legends. When K stands for killer. . .</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES FREEMAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>BOOK REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830627</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
K2, the ultimate test, can exact the highest price from a climber.
James Freeman looks at the history of a formidable challenge and those
who have perished in an attempt to conquer it.
WHEN the next chapter in the history of K2 is written, the name of
Alison Hargreaves will inevitably figure large in what has become an
epic of human endeavour punctuated by tragedy.
Alison's name will join a lengthy roll call of illustrious climbing
legends who conquered the planet's highest mountains yet failed to
survive the conquest of K2.
Among those who have perished are some of the leading woman climbers
of the post-war period, including such as Julie Tullis, the
Englishwoman, and the Pole Dobroslawa Wolf -- both figures whose lives
and deaths attracted more controversy than that of Alison Hargreaves.
There are bound to be other books about what is becoming known,
tabloid-style, as The Savage Mountain. The second highest point on earth
and the toughest of the 8000-metre peaks, it has always attracted the
best climbers. As recently as 20 years ago, it still awaited a second
ascent and fewer than 120 people have attained the summit compared with
more than 600 who have stood atop Everest.
K2 is special: Everest may be 237 metres higher but K2 is the ultimate
test, the greatest prize. This theme -- the unique cachet for
mountaineers of K2 -- comes through strongly in the latest book on the
mountain, Jim Curran's K2, The Story of The Savage Mountain*, published
last month.
The physical beauty of the mountain, a mighty symmetrical cone
dominating the remote peaks and glaciers of the Karakoram range in
Pakistan, 300 miles north-west of the Himalayas, has something to do
with its attraction.
That must necessarily be superficial, however, since Curran notes that
K2 is like the Matterhorn in this respect, the familiar outlines
disappearing in a mass of shattered buttresses, ribs, and gullies the
closer you get.
Although less remote than it was, K2 is still a difficult and exacting
mountain to reach -- much more so than Everest. Despite this and despite
its formidable reputation for prolonged poor weather, people such as
Alison Hargreaves seem driven to try an ascent.
Jim Curran was on K2 in the summer of 1986 when the death toll reached
absurd levels and the world looked on in disbelief at what appeared to
be collective climbing madness.
In his new account, he dismisses any attempt to ''look for patterns
where there are none, to find blame where that does not exist. . .'',
preferring the summation of one magazine which recorded the tragic
events as the result of numerous ascents by disjointed groups meeting in
the wrong place at the wrong time.
Early in 1986, the Pakistani Ministry of Tourism, driven by the need
for foreign currency, gave permission for no fewer than nine expeditions
to attempt K2, concentrated on a tiny handful of main routes.
Many of the individual climbers involved were top drawer but by
summer's end 27 people had climbed K2 and 13 perished in the process
including three famous woman climbers, Liliane Barard, Julie Tullis, and
Dobroslawa Wolf. Of these 13, seven died on the descent and the bare
figures disguise the sheer magnitude of the efforts by which others
achieved survival.
By the end of last year's climbing season, the number of ascents had
reached 113 but K2 had claimed 38 lives in the process -- a figure,
Curran says, worth pondering on by future would-be ascensionists.
The Pakistanis have, however, reined in, allowing only six expeditions
a year and Curran expresses the hope that the days of the great caravans
of the past with 600 porters and 20 climbers fixing ropes up the routes
are historical relics. He acknowledges the dangers of pure Alpine-style
ascents, asking what possible value there can be in using a sledgehammer
to crack a nut.
K2 is still not at the evolutionary stage of Everest, which has been
climbed by practically every face, ridge, buttress, and gully plus all
their variations. The majority of the main ridges of K2 await ascent and
will undoubtedly fall in the next few years.
However, Curran makes a plea that smaller teams and less environmental
impact are desirable. The criterion of success, in the light of the
appalling statistics, should be the safe return of all team members. He
asks: ''Is there so much commercial gain and self-interest around the
climbing world that mountaineers value their lives less highly than they
did. . .''
He also expresses doubts on the wisdom of guided ascents on the
toughest 8000 metre peaks (although, as he says, the tradition of guided
Alpinism is as old as climbing itself), pointing out that on K2 of all
mountains there is no way a guide could assume total responsibility for
his client.
While there have been notable solo speed ascents on K2 and parapente
and ski descents from the summit are inevitable, K2, unlike Everest, has
been mercifully free from gimmicks and stunts.
It was on September 10, 1856 -- 138 years ago -- that Lieutenant T G
Montgomery of the Great Trigonometric Survey of India climbed to 5000
metres above the Vale of Kashmir with his theodolite and turned north
towards the unknown Karakoram.
He noted the two highest peaks, sketched them, and named them K1 and
K2. K1 turned out to have a local name, Masherbrum but K2 did not,
Montgomerie's appellation becoming over the years a byword for danger
and impersonal savagery.
*K2, The Story of the Savage Mountain, by Jim Curran. Hodder and
Stoughton, #17.99.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
