<DOCID>GH950818-000166</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Textile factories to pay off 44 workers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830631</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORTY-four jobs are to go at two clothing factories in Annan and
Dalbeattie.
Kastix Ltd employs more than 200 at the two factories. When the job
cuts are achieved, it will have 175 people on its books at Silverlaw,
Prestonfield Road, Annan, and the larger plant at High Street,
Dalbeattie.
A spokesman for the Yorkshire-based firm, which also has factories at
Holmefirth and Methil in Fife, said 25 jobs were going at Dalbeattie and
19 at Annan.
The decision in the main was caused ''by a reduction in styles for
United Kingdom manufacture for the spring and summer 1996 season''.
Kastix said one of the problems it had been facing was difficulty in
recruiting skilled labour, which had led to an imbalance in the
workforce.
The firm, mainly involved in the production of casual wear, is one of
the leading employers in the south-west of Scotland.
Director Laurence McArdle said voluntary redundancy was being sought
but this would not cover the whole number involved.
''We have been involved in talks with the union representatives about
the job losses and there will be further talks with senior union
officials. We hope that some of the older workers may take advantage of
the terms on offer,'' said Mr McArdle.
</TEXT>
