<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000168</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000168</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hurdles on the road to Beijing</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRACE FRANKLIN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976830633</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Grace Franklin and the small band of Scottish representatives who will
attend the UN World Conference on Women in Beijing find that poverty
begins at home, and many women fighting deprivation here cannot get the
money to go to China to debate the issue and push for reforms
POVERTY is one of the major issues to be examined by the United
Nations' Fourth World Conference on Women in Beijing next month. The
irony of that has not been lost on women in Scotland. For poverty is
what is preventing more of them attending this global planning meeting.
At most, half a dozen women from Scotland will have to speak on behalf
of the two million living in this country. They include women
representing ecumenical sectors, black and migrant workers and refugees.
And though they are few in number, they have put their best foot
forward. As well as lobbying for their causes, they will be
demonstrating Scottish country dancing.
''It is one way of flying the Scottish flag,'' said Margaret Anderson,
a past-president of the Church of Scotland Woman's Guild.
Stepping out on the long journey to China with Anderson will be her
guild colleague Jane Osborne, Mary Shanahan representing the NEWS
ecumenical women's group of Action for Churches Together, Cassandra
McGrogan of Edinburgh Film Workshop, Sana Sadolla as an individual
representing refugee women, Mucami McCrum representing black and migrant
women, and myself going as a journalist reporting for The Herald and
also representing the Scottish Joint Action Group.
The main business on the agenda in Beijing is women and how countries
can make sure their women citizens enjoy equality, development and
peace. Cassandra McGrogan has made a film with Cathy McCormack about the
plight, and fight, of poor women in Scotland.
''I was going to Beijing to show that film and to make one of Cathy as
she worked her way through the United Nations processes to get the
action she wants written into the agreement which comes out of the
conference,'' explained McGrogan. ''But I'm going alone.'' While she got
funding from the British Council, she could not get money to pay Cathy's
fare. ''It seems incredible, but the one person who should be there
won't be.''
Anderson and her guild colleagues had discussed sending a
representative to Beijing when it was first known that was to be the
location of the UN Conference on Women.
''The cost was prohibitive -- over #1500 -- but the more we heard
about the agenda for women, the more we thought we should be there,''
said Anderson. The only reason the guild is able to send her and Osborn
is because a woman left the guild a legacy.
''When we first applied for accreditation we did not have a lot of
faith we would succeed. There was so much confusion about the process.''
Apart from having attended preliminary meetings held in New York,
Vienna and other places in Europe, an organisation had to be acceptable
to the United Nations and the Chinese Government. An intricate process
eventually produced, for some, a vital registration number from the UN
in New York which was the key to the Chinese Government allotting
accommodation in Beijing. Proof of those two elements have to be
presented to the Chinese Embassy in the UK where visas are issued. But
there is no automatic right to a visa.
Anderson also expressed disappointment that more women and women's
organisations in Scotland have not put their money where their mouth is.
''How can we expect our Government to respond to our demands when we
don't seem to have support at home?''
As chair of the Scottish Joint Action Group, Lorna Ahlquist knows how
hard it was to raise money to send delegates. ''We combined with SEAD
(Scottish Education and Action for Development) and worked very hard to
get money to send women to Beijing. My organisation sent out 500 letters
and got back #60. Those donations came from the women's organisations
who could least afford it -- Dumbarton Women's Aid, Strathclyde Rape
Crisis and the like. The UN conference may seem as dry as dust to people
but the document which will come out of it will be ratified by our
Government and we can use it as a tool to achieve our objects to improve
life for women.''
A similar lack of support has been felt by Sana Sadollah, who works
for the Scottish Refugee Council. ''I am paying my own way because the
council does not have a budget to send people to conferences. Funding is
a serious obstacle. I have tried many places -- including the Scottish
Office -- but have received no financial help. It seems as if women's
issues are not important enough to be supported.''
Originally from Kurdistan, Sana has lived and worked in Scotland for
almost 20 years, and she, with the few from Scotland who are heading for
Beijing, will join with an estimated 30,000 other women to get their
action points on poverty, health, housing, violence and other issues
important to women written into the United Nations Action Plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000169</DOCNO>
