<DOCNO>GH950818-000172</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000172</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Smith's Iona grave to be walled off</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830637</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SO MANY tourists are visiting the grave of Labour leader John Smith
that the cemetery is to be walled off.
More than 1000 visitors a week go to Iona and many take the chance to
make for the corner of the ancient graveyard where he is buried.
They are trampling over the graves of kings, destroying thirteenth
century pathways, and angering islanders by damaging the graves of
relatives.
Now a wall is to be built at the area where Mr Smith and islanders are
interred, separating it from the ancient graveyard.
The entrance to the section will have a padlocked gate to prevent
further damage.
The decision to spend #10,000 to secure the site was taken yesterday
after Mr Sandy Taylor, deputy director of Argyll and Bute's
environmental services department, reported ''significant damage'' to
plots where islanders have been interred.
Access to the walled-in section, he said, would be given ''only to
local residents and, perhaps, to one or two visitors''.
Stone for the 12-metre long wall will have to be shipped from nearby
Mull. ''You cannot place a tent peg on Iona without disturbing some
historical artefact,'' said Mr Taylor.
Councillor John Wilson, who represents Iona and Mull, said the
trampled ancient cemetery became ''like a quagmire'' when it rained.
''The residents on Iona are complaining and I think we have every
right to protect their interests and address their fears,'' he said.
Mr Smith lies only yards from the holy site of Tor Abb, where St
Columba, who landed on Iona in 563 AD with a dozen followers, is
believed to have prayed.
Mr Smith's family were given permission for the burial because he was
raised in Argyll and led a main political party.
Mr Smith's widow, Elizabeth, has several times urged tourists to show
more respect for the island.
</TEXT>
