<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000173</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000173</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BBC World Service's secret war</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES MCKILLOP</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830638</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TO those who tune into the World Service every night it will come as a
bit of shock that BBC executives were full and willing participants in a
top-secret Government scheme to flood the world with anti-communist
propaganda as the Cold War got under way.
However, that is the unmistakable message leaping out of the newly
released papers covering the establishment of the clandestine
Information Research Department within the Foreign Office.
''I know that we have no detailed control over the BBC with regard to
shaping its programmes; nevertheless our situation is now such it seems
essential that we should approach the BBC in these matters and cause
them, by persuasion if possible, to undertake such programme
developments as might help us in the task imposed on us by the new
policy,'' one secret document declares.
The new policy was that, after some initial reluctance, Prime Minister
Clement Attlee accepted the necessity for a propaganda exercise to
counter-balance tirades coming out of Stalin's Soviet Union, intent on
undermining Western power and influence.
It resulted in the establishment of the Information Research
Department, which was to continue under secret funding until it was
abolished in 1977.
While the public at large knew nothing of what was going on, some of
those in the know -- including Lord Healey, then working in the
international department of the Labour Party -- were kept fully informed
and were keen and willing participants in the exercise.
The folders enclosing the papers covering the unit's birth leave no
question or doubt over what it was all about. Each one of them blasts
the message ''anti-communist propaganda''.
It is those concerning the BBC that caused most interest yesterday.
There can be no doubt about it -- the BBC went into this arrangement
with the special unit with its eyes open.
Initial contact was through Major-General Sir Ian Jacob, a BBC
employee who held the title, Director of Overseas Service.
The papers suggest that, while it was argued in certain quarters that
there should be editorial direction within the BBC over this issue, that
was finally overruled.
''The corporation should remain independent in the preparation of
programmes for overseas audiences, though it should obtain from the
Government Departments concerned such information about conditions in
those countries and the policies of His Majesty's Government towards
them.''
An early meeting in London's Cafe Royal was arranged between Mr Ralph
Murray, the man in direct control of the new propaganda machine, and the
two most senior BBC executives involved in the World Service --
certainly those in control of the key target areas outlined by the
Government -- Mr R McColl, controller of overseas services and Mr E
Tangye Lean, editor of European services.
One paper described how it would be unlikely that BBC chiefs would
ignore suggestions coming from the new unit.
The author was confident that the BBC would accept suggestions for
features that would get the British message on international labour
problems that would be of interest to the working classes in the target
areas -- particularly in Italy and France, under threat from an upsurge
in communist sympathy.
''It would then follow automatically that they (the BBC) would echo
the developments of policy expressed in Government statements, or any
information officially issued either by HMG or by eg the Labour Party or
TUC and would indeed create a market for our own information and our
exposure of the reality of communist pretensions.''
Another official thought the BBC would probably prefer to be adopt an
oblique rather than a direct technique.
''That is to say they will probably prefer to get in their digs at
communism by reflecting opinion in this country rather than by engaging
in direct commentaries of their own.''
The Ministry of War put in its own suggestions. The Army in Germany
thought that the condition of PoWs returning from the Soviet Union
compared with that of Afrika Corps PoWs sent home from Britain would
make a brilliant propaganda piece.
''There is little sympathy in our target areas in Western Europe,
which have recently been under German occupation, for what happens to
German prisoners of war,'' was the response to that one.
There was constant communication across the Atlantic to ensure that
our anti-red propaganda efforts were not conflicting with the
Americans'.
At one such meeting it was suggested that there might be a tie-up
between the BBC and the CIA-funded Voice of America.
However, the Brits thought the American operation was too obvious and
robust.
''The BBC takes the greatest pains to ensure that it is not regarded
as a propaganda organisation . . . There is a large gap between the BBC
'reflecting the policies and views of HMG' and material just
broadcasting anti-communist propaganda.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
