<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Body of woman found in drain</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830639</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE discovery of the badly-decomposed body of a woman started a murder
inquiry in Edinburgh yesterday.
The find was made by plumbers sent to clear the drains in gardens
behind a block of tenement flats just off the Meadows after local
residents reported a bad smell.
Plumber Kenneth More described his shock at opening the manhole cover
and finding the remains of the woman three feet under water in the
drainage shaft below.
Entrance to the flats at 100 South Clerk Street, just a few minutes
from the festival's main venues, were sealed off immediately by police,
around midday yesterday.
Forensic teams were called in and uniformed officers combed the
surrounding area for clues. Door-to-door inquiries were carried out as
police tried to identify the victim.
A Lothian and Borders Police spokesman last night appealed for
information as a post-mortem examination on the body was being carried
out.
The man leading the murder hunt, DCI Iain Cowden of Lothian and
Borders Police, said: ''It appears the body has been in the common green
area for some time but at this stage of our inquiry it is impossible to
say for how long.''
Police were searching their missing persons file to find a match for
the murder victim but said no local woman had been reported missing
recently.
Locals living in the area, a popular bed-sit area for students, were
shocked at the discovery.
Carpet shop owner Cathy Scales said she had noticed a bad smell over
the past few weeks. ''This is a real shock,'' she said. ''The drain
where the body was found is level with the basement of the flats on the
way to the garden. I knew there was a bad smell but just put it down to
the warm weather.''
An Edinburgh District Council spokesman said last night there had been
complaints about the smell in the general area around the common green
in South Clerk Street.
He said after a site visit there on August 9, discarded rubbish was
found in the general area by environmental health officers.
Afterwards, local residents were reminded about the procedures for
disposing of household waste and reminded that any complaints about the
drains should be reported to Lothian Regional Council.
It is not clear whether any complaints about the drains were ever made
to the regional council.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
