<DOCNO>GH950818-000175</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000175</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trail turns north in hunt for the killer of 'very private and lonely' motorway prostitute. Search for mystery hotline caller</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JONATHAN NORTHCROFT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830640</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN anonymous woman caller to a Strathclyde Police hotline might hold
the key to a 17-month-old inquiry into the murder of a motorway
prostitute.
Detectives from Leicestershire travelled to Glasgow yesterday to
appeal to the woman to come forward.
The caller, who might be a prostitute in the Glasgow area, contacted
the Crimestoppers line on July 24. She left a message on an answering
machine saying she had information about the death of Tracy Turner, 30,
from Stafford, who was murdered in March 1994.
She spoke to same answerphone again on July 31, promising to call
back, but has since made no further contact.
Police believe the calls were in response to publicity surrounding the
murder of 22-year-old Glasgow prostitute Leona McGovern in June,
although they are not connecting the two murders.
Leicestershire Police re-issued an appeal to help trace the driver of
a meat lorry, called Gary or Gavin, who is believed to be based in
Strathclyde and was once Ms Turner's boyfriend.
Tracy Turner was found dead on the grass verge of a narrow lane in
Bitteswell, Leicestershire, a short distance from the M1, on March 3,
1994. Her body was naked and she had been raped and strangled.
She was last seen at a Stafford service station 60 miles away on the
previous evening. Police believe she was picked up by a vehicle
travelling north.
Detective Superintendent David Cox, in charge of the investigation,
said yesterday: ''I would appeal for the woman caller to get in touch.
She obviously knows something about Tracy Turner and I can appreciate
that she may be scared.
''If she rings us we promise that her call will be dealt with in the
utmost confidence.''
Mr Cox and a colleague will be based at Glasgow's Cranstonhill police
station over the next 48 hours in the hope they can speak to the woman
personally.
He said that Ms Turner had led ''a very private and very lonely life''
in which her hobby had been to befriend and travel with lorry drivers
along the nation's motorways.
She was ''an occasional prostitute'' he said, who operated in North
London and in service stations along the M6 and M1.
Blonde, and always wearing Walkman headphones which were connected to
a hearing aid, she was also a constant feature at lorry stops along the
routes, where it is believed she may have met Gavin/Gary.
Early calls received during the murder hunt suggested she had
travelled to Glasgow several times with the lorry driver, whose vehicle
is described as bearing a ''Scotland'' logo, and had stayed in hostels
in the city, occasionally operating as a prostitute.
The Crimestoppers message detailed some of her visits to Scotland and
it is believed the caller knew Ms Turner and possibly Gavin/Gary.
Mr Cox said: ''The inquiry is 17 months old and there are few avenues
left for us. It could be that this caller is the key to the
investigation.
''If we don't catch the killer it is very possible they might kill
again. It was a particularly nasty murder, involving abduction and rape,
and once a person reaches such a level of crime, they seldom regress to
less violent ones.''
A spokesman for Strathclyde Police stressed that the murder was
''entirely dissimilar'' to that of Leona McGovern, but said: ''It is
very unusual for someone to telephone following one murder with
information about another.''
Those who have information about Tracy Turner can contact MR on 0141
532 3200, or the Crimestoppers hotline on 0800 555 111.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
