<DOCNO>GH950818-000176</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000176</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Go-ahead for Tube strike</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830641</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE London Underground last night was facing the threat of a one-day
strike after two unions joined forces in disputes over pay and
conditions.
Aslef, which represents most Tube drivers, voted by a three-to-one
margin in favour of a stoppage, and later RMT members, representing a
range of Tube workers, also backed strike action.
The RMT's first stoppage has been called to coincide with Aslef's,
next Friday, threatening chaos to commuters and travellers the day
before the Bank Holiday weekend.
The RMT also announced two further one-day stoppages, from 7.30pm on
Thursday, August 31 and from 7.30pm on Sunday, September 3.
A London Underground spokesman said: ''The result is a big
disappointment. We are deeply saddened for our customers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000177</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000177</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BBC in from the cold</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES MCKILLOP</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976830642</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE BBC World Service was recruited as the main vehicle to distribute
anti-communist propaganda during the Cold War by a top secret Government
unit, official papers released yesterday reveal.
The unit was set up especially for the purpose by the post-war Labour
Government and the documents are a severe blow to the long-term boast by
the BBC that its service is the most impartial in the world.
Because of their sensitivity, the papers have been delayed beyond the
normal 30-year rule for withholding official documents.
From the outset, the BBC was swamped with anti-communist propaganda by
the clandestine Foreign Office unit, the Information Research
Department, set up by Clement Attlee's Government in 1948. It remained
in existence until 1977, when it was scrapped by the then Foreign
Secretary Dr David Owen. Finance came from a secret MI6 budget.
The documents also reveal how Lord Healey, former Chancellor of the
Exchequer, offered his full support to the unit when in charge of the
Labour Party's international organisation. Others who assisted the unit
included philosopher Bertrand Russell, poet Stephen Spender, traitor Guy
Burgess, and Vic Feather, later to become general secretary of the TUC.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000178</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000178</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The pressure on women climbers to prove a point</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES FREEMAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830643</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN news filtered through that Alison Hargreaves would not be
returning from K2, Nicola Tannahill, in common with many other Scottish
climbers who knew and liked her, felt an immediate sense of personal
loss.
''Like many others, I had met her at functions and presentations. Like
everyone else, I followed her exploits. Through it all, she was totally
sincere and genuine. I felt as though I had lost a sister,'' she said..
Ms Tannahill, 26, works part-time in a Glasgow leading climbing shop,
and, with her partner, runs Outdoor Discovery, based in Wishaw. In that
capacity, she works with parties who want to learn to hillwalk, ski,
climb, canoe or mountain-bike -- all with the emphasis on performing
these activities in safety.
In summer, she climbs rock to a good standard in Glencoe and in the
Cairngorms; in winter, she can be found on the classic snow and ice
climbs in the same areas.
''I came to climbing through hillwalking which is how most people
start,'' she said.
''The motivation is very strong. Once I have done a route, all I want
to do is to get back into the hills to do something else. That is the
key to people like Alison -- it is the adrenalin flowing that takes you
back again and again.
''I admit that sometimes the same adrenalin buzz pushes you into a
situation where you end up saying to yourself: 'Hey, wait a minute. I
don't like this'. Common sense then dictates that you get off that point
or out of that situation.
''There is another element coming in all the time and that is the
male-female thing. If I am leading a party and I make a map reading, I
often see men in the party turning to another one of the fellows and
checking what he thinks -- even though I have employed the guy to work
for me. I always have to be the first to volunteer to carry the heavy
rope, or the big first-aid pack in my sack because otherwise they would
be thinking I was shirking because I am the only woman. It is good
natured, but the undercurrent is there.
''You have to make sure that the need to prove yourself does not
affect your judgment.
'' I climbed a couple of years ago with people who were out of my
league and it scared the wits out of me.
''It is good on the other hand to climb with people who are at the
same level as yourself or just above your level. That way you can
improve at a good pace. If you try routes that are too hard for your
ability at that point you simply end up scaring yourself and that can
set you back.
''I fell on a glacier in Iceland and it put me off for quite a few
weeks. I am very concious of the stereotyping that goes on -- that
climbing is seen as a male world and no place for women.
''The flaws in that thinking are obvious.    ''There is no difference
between a man leaving his kids behind to climb than a woman doing the
same thing. At the same time, there is always an element of having to
prove yourself to be one of the boys.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950818-000179</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950818-000179</DOCID>
<DATE>950818</DATE>
<HEADLINE>K2 heroine swept away. Climber's body left hanging on killer mountain</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS, HIGHLAND CORRESPONDENT ELIZABETH BUIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976830644</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE body of Alison Hargreaves has been seen by a fellow climber
hanging from a ledge on K2 after an avalanche. It was ''out of reach''.
The words of New Zealander Peter Hillary, son of Sir Edmund Hillary
and a member of her expedition team to K2, ended all hopes she could
have survived the storm on the mountain. Six fellow climbers were also
feared dead.
Mr Hillary gave his account to the expedition organiser, Mr Nazir
Sabir, who said the bodies would have to be left on the slopes of the
mountain, close to the peak, as they were ''almost impossible to
reach''.
Mr Sabir said: ''There is absolutely no chance at all for any of them
to have survived but I don't know yet in what circumstances this has
happened.''
He said he had spoken to Mr Hillary, a survivor of the ferocious storm
and avalanche, by satellite phone.
Ms Hargreaves's two young children had been told earlier their mother
may not be coming home from her successful conquest of K2, the world's
most dangerous mountain.
Six-year-old Tom and his sister Katie, four, last saw their mother
nine weeks ago when she left Spean Bridge to mount an assault on K2 in
Pakistan's Karakoram range, only 17 days after her return from becoming
the first woman mountaineer to conquer Everest without oxygen
assistance.
Husband Jim Ballard, a mountaineer, photographer, and public relations
manager, told his children an avalanche is thought to have killed their
mother.
''I have told them there had been a big storm, they had seen big
storms, they have been in them, and that their mum was missing and we
didn't know where she was, and it was possible that she would not be
coming home,'' he said at the Aonach Mor ski resort, which his wife had
used as a climbing base for the past year.
''Tom said he wanted time to think about that as we sat on the floor
in the board-room, the only place where there weren't other people and
the phones weren't going. He just cuddled up to me. Katie had a little
cry and a cuddle and said she would be brave and do her best to help.
''It is probably the most difficult thing I have ever done.''
He went on: ''The children have gone home now, but they have had a
splendid day on the hills up Aonach Mor. It is where I think their
mother would have liked them to be.''
As for himself, he said: ''I have been rehearsing this scene for 10
years, but it was one I hoped I would never have had to do.''
Before her departure in June, Ms Hargreaves rejected claims that her
job as Britain's only female professional mountaineer was cruel to her
children, but she did concede that she was no stay-at-home mother.
''I've got an ego as big as Mount Everest,'' she once said.
Yet, her first thoughts when she reached the top of Everest were for
her family. She radioed the message: ''To Tom and Kate, my two children,
I am on top of the world.''
Just before she left on her latest expedition, she said that although
she believed she had the technical ability to reach the summit of the
world's second peak, she was ''going into this expedition as I always do
-- with my eyes wide open and fully aware of the risks''.
She added: ''I believe it is the weather, rather than my climbing
abilities, that will hold the key as to whether I succeed. I had luck
with me on Everest, but the law of averages says that I should not get
such a good break on K2.''
Throughout yesterday he had refused to accept that all hope had gone,
saying: ''If anyone can do a Houdini, Alison can.'' He said: ''What
appears to be nearly certain is that Alison climbed the mountain
sometime on Sunday followed by Rob Slater from America and Bruce Grant
from New Zealand. They radioed back and this was heard by an American
team.''
It emerged yesterday that Ms Hargreaves, 33, had decided to change
climbing partners for the K2 attempt last month.
A Tyneside-based mountaineer, Mr Alan Hinkes, 41, said he had walked
with her to the base camp of K2, they had shared the same tent at Camp
2, and she had been due to partner him on his attempt on the summit. But
then she decided to team up with a member of an American expedition on
the mountain, and Mr Hinkes prepared to make the ascent with other
climbers.
On his descent he met Ms Hargreaves again at Camp 2, at 22,500ft, on
July 18. With the weather worsening she returned to base camp, 6000ft
lower, and he last saw her there on July 23 when he left to return to
the UK.
Mr Hinkes said yesterday: ''Inevitably, I can't help feeling that if
she had not decided to change partners this would not have happened.''
Another former member of the K2 expedition, Mr Kevin Cooney, told how
a 100mph wind had blown across the mountain ''with brutal cold'' as Ms
Hargreaves and fellow climber Rob Slater made their way from the summit.
Ms Hargreaves' parents, John and Joyce, had been waiting for news at
their home in Belper, Derbyshire.
Mr Ballard summed up the feeling of the climbing community: ''Alison
was a genius as a climber and if she is dead she has at least died where
she wanted to be, and she was on her way down after becoming the first
woman to climb the two highest peaks on earth without oxygen and in pure
style.''
He quoted a Tibetan saying which was a favourite of his wife's: ''It
is better to have lived one day as a tiger than a thousand years as a
sheep.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
